ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON  
  
UNANSWERED QUESTIONS  
(None)  
INFORMATION TO BE INSERTED   
(None)  
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Good morning--Here begins videotape 
No. 1 in the deposition of Brian Kaelin in the consolidated cases of 
Fredric Goldman, Sharon Rufo and Louis Brown vs. Orenthal 
James Simpson in the Superior Court, State of California, County 
of Los Angeles, the lead case number of which is SC 031947. 
Today's date is Wednesday, February 14, 1996. The time is 
approximately 9:43. This deposition is being taken at 11377 West 
Olympic Boulevard in Los Angeles, California and was made at 
the request of plaintiff of the Law Offices of Mitchell, Silberberg 
& Knupp. The videographer is Rod Rigole, employed by Coleman, 
Haas, Martin & Schwab of Los Angeles. California. Would 
counsel please identify yourselves and state whom you represent.  
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Good morning. Here begins videotape 
No. I in the deposition of Brian Kaelin. Volume II, in the 
consolidated cases of Fredric Goldman, Sharon Rufo and Louis 
Brown vs. Orenthal James Simpson in the Superior Court, State of 
California, County of Los Angeles, the lead case number of which 
is SC 031947. 
 
Today's date is Thursday, February 15th, 1996. The time is 
approximately 11:23. This deposition is being taken at 11377 West 
Olympic Boulevard in Los Angeles. California, and was made at 
the request of plaintiff of the Law Offices of Mitchell, Silberberg 
& Knupp. 
 
The videographer is Rod Rigole, employed by Coleman, Haas, 
Martin & Schwab of Los Angeles, California. 
 
Would counsel please identify yourselves and state whom you 
represent. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Daniel Petrocelli for Fred Goldman. 
 
MR. MEDVENE: Edward Medvene, Fred Goldman. 
 
MR. BREWER: Mike Brewer, Sharon Rufo. 
 
MR. KELLY: John Kelly for Brown. 
 
MR. PHILLIP BAKER: Phil Baker, Mr. Simpson. MR. ROBERT 
BAKER: Bob Baker, Mr. Simpson. 
 
MR. ARTHUR GROMAN: Arthur Groman for Mr. Goldman. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: Michael Plotkin for the witness Brian Kaelin. 
 
BRIAN KAELIN, having been previously sworn, was examined 
and testified further as follows: 
 
EXAMINATION 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: Q: Good morning, Mr. Kaelin. A: Good 
morning. 
 
Q: When you saw Mr. Simpson on June 12 after the McDonald's 
trip -- okay? You with me? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: At any time thereafter did you see him in a black robe? 
 
A: No. . 
 
Q: Terry cloth robe? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Any other kind of black robe? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Or a dark robe? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Any robe? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: I want to go back to some of the conversations that you spoke 
about yesterday on the 11th and on the 12th of June. There was 
conversation between you and O.J. Simpson about Paula Barbieri 
on those two days. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: There was some on Saturday and some on Sunday. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: The conversation that you described yesterday about Ms. 
Barbieri being upset that she could not go to the recital, do you 
remember that? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: When did that occur? 
 
A: On Sunday. 
 
Q: June 12. 
 
A: June 12th, Sunday. 
 
Q: Do you know approximately what time that occurred? 
 
A: That was in the afternoon. It was afternoon. The noon hour. 
 
Q: What did O.J. Simpson say to you about that? 
 
A: That I believe that Paula wanted to invite herself to this dance 
recital. and O.J. wasn't comfortable to have her there because he 
just wanted to make it kind of a family thing, and not to have Paula 
there would be a better thing. So -- and if Paula was there, it would 
be maybe some friction. 
 
Q: With whom? 
 
A: Possibly the Brown family or Nicole. 
 
Q: That's what he said? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: What else did he say? 
 
A: And he really didn't want her to go. He wanted to be there with 
just the family. 
 
Q: And what did O.J. Simpson say to you that Paula Barbieri said 
on that subject? 
 
A: That Paula probably wasn't the one to get married. She wanted 
kids. and O.J. already had kids, and he wasn't going to have more 
kids. 
 
Q: Did -- That's something that Mr. Simpson told you that he and 
Paula had discussed? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And that there was friction about that subject? 
 
A: Yeah. I think -- I don't know if it was 100 percent to Paula 
discussed it. He told it to me that he wasn't going to -- you know. 
that she probably wanted to get married. She did want to get 
married. she loved O.J. a lot and she wanted the kids, and that was 
him telling me that. 
 
Q: What did O.J. say about whether he wanted to marry Paula and 
he wanted to have kids? 
 
A: That she probably wasn't the one, and he didn't want to have 
kids. 
 
Q: Did he tell you why he didn't want to have kids? 
 
A: He has kids already. Why would he want more kids? 
 
Q: Did he tell you what Paula's reaction was to Mr. Simpson's 
unwillingness to invite her to the dance recital? 
 
A: That she was upset. She got upset with him that she couldn't go 
to the recital, and she was complaining. 
 
Q: And O.J. Simpson told you this in this meeting -- this 
conversation on the 12th? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did he tell you what Paula said to him when she got upset at 
him? 
 
A: I think it was that she just wanted to be invited, and she was just 
ticked off that she couldn't go. I think it was the thing that if she 
could go, it would kinda show that -- if she was there, then Nicole 
would know then for sure that she was the woman. 
 
Q: Did O.J. tell you whether he wanted Nicole to know for sure 
that Paula was the woman? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did he discuss that with you? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did he discuss his feelings towards Nicole in that conversation? 
 
A: The conversation was just about having a family. It came up 
once or twice about having a white picket fence and having the 
kids run around, to be a happy family. That conversation came up. 
 
Q: You're telling me now about something that came up in the 
conversation in the afternoon of June 12th? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: In that conversation did he express to you his feelings toward 
Nicole? 
 
A: No 
 
Q: Did he say that he wanted Nicole to be that one who would be 
with him at the house with the picket fence and the kids? 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Well, I object on two grounds: Number 
one, there is no foundation for that from this witness' testimony --  
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: You can answer. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: -- and, number two. there is -- he's never 
talked that O.J. wanted a white picket fence. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: You can answer. 
 
A: Yeah, that he said that he wanted a white picket fence, the 
family. There was a futility to saying the relationship was over 
between he and Nicole. 
 
Q: O.J. Simpson told you that the relationship between Nicole and 
him was over? 
 
A: That it was over. 
 
Q: And he said it was -- when you said "finality," you mean over 
once and for all? 
 
A: That it was going to be over, and that's somewhat why I had the 
Tracy Adell call and all that because I thought I was being a good 
guy, and also like Susan Wilkinsen. She was like a Christian girl, 
and she was -- it was just bringing my friends in because it was 
kinda like be okay to do that. 
 
Q: Did O.J. tell you that the relationship with Nicole was over for 
good? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did he tell you how it came to be that that relationship had 
ended for good? 
 
A: I don't -- it was -- it had to do with the argument with -- that 
IRS thing, that he was putting pressure on her with the IRS. 
 
Q: Tell me what he said to you about that. 
 
A: I don't know exactly how the IRS thing was working, but it was 
the change of address, that somehow it was going to screw up 
Nicole and she was going to get in trouble with the IRS. 
 
Q: O.J. Simpson told you that? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And he told you that he would take some action to get Nicole in 
trouble with the IRS? 
 
A: To report it to the IRS. 
 
Q: That's what he said? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. You know, the reason I keep asking you, "That's what he 
said.'" is because I want to know who the speaker is, who's doing 
the talking. 
 
A: Okay. I should say who said it. 
 
Q: If you could, it would be helpful. I know Mr. Baker would 
appreciate that. too. Now, you had a conversation with O.J. 
Simpson on the same day after the recital. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Now, you said you played some basketball when Mr. Simpson 
went off to the recital? 
 
A: Yeah, at some point in the afternoon I played basketball in 
Santa Monica, like 14th Street school and --  
 
Q: I -- I'm sorry. 
 
A: -- and at some point the recital was over with, and I was in the 
kitchen nook area with O.J. 
 
Q: At some point. 
 
A: At some point. And he said he --  
 
Q: What -- hold on. Let me stop you right there. I don't want to get 
into the conversation quite yet. When you left Mr. Simpson after 
the first conversation that you just decided, you said you went off 
to play basketball. Right? 
 
A: At some point, yes. 
 
Q: I think you said yesterday you also went to Vons and had a 
California roll. Right? 
 
A: A carton, right. 
 
Q: Excuse me? 
 
A: A carton of those. It was not fresh. 
 
Q: A carton. You ate them in the car? 
 
A: Ate them in the car. 
 
Q: While sitting in the parking lot. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did you do anything else before you had the conversation with 
Mr. Simpson about the recital? Did you watch any TV or --  
 
A: I watched the playoff game. 
 
Q: Excuse me? 
 
A: The playoff game, the Knicks and Astros -- Houston. Houston. 
not the Astros. 
 
Q: The Houston Rockets. 
 
A: Rockets. I watched that. That was on that afternoon. I don't 
know if it was Game 7 or not. but I was watching that game, and --  
 
Q: Do you remember watching it? 
 
A: Yes. I remember being in my room and on the floor. because I 
was sweaty from I believe my run. 
 
Q: Do you remember if that was before or after the playing of 
basketball that you watched the Rocket game? 
 
A: I don't remember 100 percent, and -- I just don't remember, but I 
know that I did watch that game. 
 
Q: You are not a hundred percent sure of the sequence of some of 
these events. 
 
A: Exactly. 
 
Q: Is that what you're saying? 
 
A: Yes, I am. 
 
Q: Okay. Tell me, at some time -- at some point you said you 
ended up in the kitchen nook with Mr. Simpson after the recital? 
 
A: Yes, I did. 
 
Q: And just you and he? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Were you sitting down? 
 
A: Yes, I was. 
 
Q: And was Mr. Simpson sitting down? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: You said yesterday that Mr. Simpson said that he was upset 
because Nicole was playing hardball with the children. Right? 
 
A: Yes, I did. 
 
Q: Now, can you -- you also said that he was upset about the 
wearing of a tight black miniskirt. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Right? 
 
A: Right. 
 
Q: That's what he said to you. Right? 
 
A: Yes, he did. 
 
Q: Did -- I'll tell you what: Why don't instead of asking you how 
upset he was, why don't you show us. 
 
A: It was sitting down. There's a phone here when he sits down, 
and I'm sitting across about five feet away, and it was, "Nicole's 
playing hardball with me. Sydney's my child, too. I can see her 
when want to. "And the dresses, the dresses they wear. I mean. 
Kato, what are they gonna do when they're grandmas? Are they 
going to wear those kind of dresses? Come on, how can they wear 
those dresses when they're older like that. It was a recital. They 
shouldn't -- it was like they're wearing stuff that they would wear 
to a club." 
 
And the phone would ring -- and the phone was ringing constantly, 
and he'd pick up and go "Hello" --  
 
Q: Let me ask you about that -- Are you finished? 
 
A: Yeah. So the phone would ring, and then it would go -- let him 
do the phone call. and it would change into some other -- the 
subject was sort of over then, and it was on to the phone call, and I 
wasn't paying attention, or trying not to, when he was on his calls. 
 
Q: So when he was talking about his interaction with Nicole at the 
recital he talked in the way that you just tried to describe to us? 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: I object as leading. There is no 
foundation for that from that testimony. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: Q: You can answer. 
 
A: That's what happened. 
 
Q: You just tried to recreate how he appeared to you and what he 
said to you. Is that right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
a After the recital. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Talking about what had happened at the recital? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did he tell you whether he and Nicole spoke words to one 
another at the recital? 
 
A: I don't think they did speak. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Move to strike. I guess we're withholding 
all those, because I would have been on the record more than he 
would have been. The question had to be responsive. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: Q: Did -- We'll, if you have objections, 
Mr. Baker, you should make them. 
 
Q: Did he tell you whether or not Nicole and O.J. exchanged words 
at the recital? 
 
A: I think it was just that he wasn't going to be getting his 
daughter, and they took off. 
 
Q: Now, you said that there were some phone calls during this 
conversation with Mr. Simpson about the recital. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: When he answered the phone, did his demeanor change at all? 
 
A: It was "Hello" however you pick up the phone when someone 
calls. 
 
Q: And when he spoke on the phone, did he speak in an agitated 
way? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Was he sort of normal. relaxed? 
 
A: If the phone would ring, you'd answer "Hello." 
 
Q: Did he express any of his frustration about Nicole playing 
hardball with the people on rhe phone? 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: I object to your characterization. 
 
THE WITNESS: No. No. he didn't. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: Q: He did not? 
 
A: He did not. 
 
Q: He didn't share any of what he was telling you to the people 
who called? 
 
A: He did not. 
 
Q: He did not. Just normal banter? 
 
A: Conversation with whoever was on the phone. 
 
Q: Did you even see him laughing from time to time while he was 
on the phone? 
 
A: Yes. Q: You tried not to listen? 
 
A: I did listen -- I mean, if there were conversations going on, it 
was normal conversation tone: I could hear. 
 
Q: When he got off these phone calls, did he then resume talking 
about Nicole and what had happened at the recital? 
 
A: I don't know if it came up again. I mean, it might have gone on 
to something else. The exact dialogue, I don't know. but the 
Sydney incident sort of was that one comment about playing 
hardball and shaking of the head. "She can't do that." that sort of 
statement. But the phone call -- there was no real point to repeating 
it anymore, so there was nothing more really said about that to me. 
 
Q: Then you went off and took your Jacuzzi? 
 
A: At some point I did, yeah. I was also reading -- there was all 
this Sunday paper there, so I was reading a lot of the newspapers in 
that nook area while conversions were going on. 
 
Q: Okay. Later on you took the ride in the Bentley to McDonald's. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: You already told us about that yesterday. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Can you describe Mr. Simpson 's mood in the Bentley to and 
from McDonald's? 
 
A: Well, I said I was kinda forcing conversation in the -- on the 
ride. I felt that because I kind of invited myself for that ride, and I 
thought he was -- myself thought he was in thought, like deep 
thought and gloomy. It was --  
 
Q: Gloomy? Gloomy? Did you say "gloomy"? 
 
A: Yes. I didn't want to talk, but I brought up conversations. 
 
Q: Introspective? 
 
A: Yeah. He was in thought. 
 
Q: Quiet? 
 
MR. PHILLIP BAKER: Leading. 
 
THE WITNESS: He was leaned back and driving. He was just very 
-- sort of just very relaxed and in thought. and I was bringing up 
conversation, but l knew it was kinda forced conversation, and I 
was comfortable bringing up things because I was trying to get a 
conversation. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: Q: Why was it forced? 
 
A: Because I was forcing it. I was, "So what time's the flight?" 
"Where you going?" 
 
Q: What made it forced in your mind? 
 
A: There was no dialogue. He wasn't bringing up anything. So I 
thought it was my lead to bring up stuff, and then when there's just 
kind of one answers to the things. I thought, all right, Kato, don't 
talk. 
 
Q: Were you feeling awkward about even asking for a straw? 
 
A: After I got my stuff, yeah. I already had the stuff and I was 
gonna say to myself, "Okay," in my head, "Should I ask for a 
straw? Ask for the straw," so I asked for the straw. 
 
Q: In other words, you had to go through a process of deciding in 
your mind whether you should ask for a straw. 
 
A: Yeah 
 
Q: Did you ask him you know, what was wrong? 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Well, I object. There is no indication that 
anything was wrong. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: Q: Did you ask him what was wrong? 
 
A: No. I just -- if anything, I just felt he didn't want to talk, and 
maybe lonely, and I brought up maybe being tired, that he should 
get a nap. 
 
Q: Did you ask him if anything was bothering him? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Was it your habit to ask questions like that? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: In your relationship with O.J. Simpson, did you pry into his 
personal matters? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you inquire about his personal matters? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you inquire about his private feelings? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Why not? 
 
A: I think if that would ever come up the other person would bring 
it up to me more than me having to pry. 
 
Q: you wouldn't bring it up. A: I wouldn't bring it up. 
 
Q: Why not? 
 
A: Because I would think, he's O.J. Simpson. I'm not going to ask 
him what's going on. what was wrong. 
 
Q: You didn't feel close enough to him? 
 
A: To ask him personal questions, no. If they were going to come 
up, I thought he would bring them up. If he wanted to talk, he 
would ask me. 
 
Q: Did you share with Mr. Simpson personal things about your 
life? 
 
A: Maybe one or two. I mean, nothing really. 
 
Q: Why not? 
 
A: There's nothing really going on. 
 
Q: No. What I am getting to is: Did you feel close enough to him 
that you would share personal things in your life with him? 
 
A: No. If I had personal problems. no, I wouldn't bring it up to 
him. Q: you would not. 
 
A: I would not. 
 
Q: Yesterday we were talking about your conversations with 
Nicole during the year 1993 when you were living at Gretna Green. 
and you told us about a number of conversations that she and you 
had about O.J. Simpson. 
 
A: Right. 
 
Q: Did you talk to Nicole about things other than O.J. Simpson? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Frequently? 
 
A: I think Nicole would mostly bring up other things that were 
going on in her life. She would tell me about her friends, the 
people she hung out with, what she was gonna do for the day or 
what she didn't do for the day. She pretty much told me exactly 
what was going on in her life. When I was around, what I was 
gonna do. 
 
She talked about Cora. She had running friends,Cora and Cici, that 
would usually come over in the morning and the friends, Cora 
almost every day, and then after that they would all go to the coffee 
-- I don't know what coffee place they go to, but they get their 
coffee and then hang out at the pool. 
 
She told me things about Cora. She didn't like going out at night so 
much with Cora because she didn't really like drinking and 
partying, and she kinda had a thing of friends, going Cora wasn't 
the big party -- Cora wasn't big at drinking --  
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Excuse me, Mr. Simpson. 
 
THE WITNESS: Cora wasn't the big drinker. She would go out, 
but she wasn't like the big drinker. where if Faye went out -- Faye 
and Cici I think. I think it's those two that hated each other. 
 
So it would be a certain clique of friends that would always go out, 
and one friend didn't get along with one of the friends. I'm trying to 
think of who. I think it was Faye and Cici that didn't -- couldn't 
stand each other. 
 
Cici was more the one they made fun of, that she kept looking for a 
man. Cici could never get a guy and always in search. Faye, she 
said, was always someone going after like the rich guy, always had 
to find the richest guy, was Faye's motive to -- for money, just 
money was the big motivation thing and... 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: She had views like this about all of her friends, different views 
for different friends? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: The question that I was asking you -- I think you've answered it 
-- is whether or not Nicole talked with you about a wide variety of 
things, and the answer is what? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And frequently? 
 
A: Yes, she would talk to me a lot. 
 
u -- Okay Did Nicole ever talk to you about Mr. Simpson being a 
jealous man? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: What did she say to you about that? 
 
A: She just would say, "O.J.'s a very jealous person? that he liked 
