It's too confusing. 
 
Q: Welt, let's see if we can put it in parameters. By May of 1993 
you were aware that they, that being O.J. and Nicole, had agreed to 
try a reconciliation. Correct? 
 
A: I believe so. 
 
Q: So -- and she started chatting with you about personal details of 
her Life. Let's see if we can concentrate between February of 1993 
and May of 1993. Okay? 
 
A: Okay. 
 
Q: Now, during that period of time did Nicole suggest to you that 
she wanted to get back to having a marriage with O.J. Simpson? 
 
A: Yes, it came up. 
 
Q: And she told you that she wanted to remarry O.J. Simpson, 
didn't she? 
 
A: I believe so. 
 
Q: And she told you she was in love with O.J. Simpson, didn't she? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And she told you that some of the best times she'd ever had in 
her life was in the company of Mr. O.J. Simpson. Isn't that correct? 
 
A: Yeah. That's when the photo albums would come out. That's her 
thing, when she would show me that stuff. 
 
Q: And she told you that he was a charming, gracious guy, didn't 
she? 
 
A: At times. yes, she did. 
 
Q: And she at that time indicated to you that she was having this 
affair with Marcus Allen. Is that correct? 
 
A: Well, it was a time where she had told me that Marcus started 
taking a real liking to her, and she didn't really like Marcus. So she 
had got -- told me that he kept coming by, and she goes, "I just 
don't like Marcus that way. I like Marcus as a friend." 
 
And then she would tell me that she had stuff in common, that 
Marcus has been such a good friend that she didn't think it would 
be good to be like a lover. And then she would say that "He's really 
a great guy, and we like the same music, and Marcus was 
religious," and she was telling me all these like good things, but 
she wasn't in love with him. And so that's the parts that I knew, and 
I didn't know what kind of went after. 
 
Q: All right. As I understand your testimony, Mr. Kaelin, you were 
reasonably certain that after May of 1993 until May of 1994 Nicole 
was monogamous with O.J. Correct? 
 
A: That the marriage was monogamous. That she told me in our 
conversations that the whole time she was married to him, she 
never, ever cheated on O.J. during the marriage. 
 
Q: Let me go back, and I want to reask my question, or maybe I 
asked it poorly. 
 
A: Okay. 
 
Q: Your understanding was in May of 1993, O.J. and Nicole got 
back together for an attempted reconciliation. Correct? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And you've testified in this proceeding that between the time 
that Nicole agreed to get back and wanted to get back with O.J. for 
a reconciliation, that she was never untrue to O.J. Correct? Never 
cheated on him. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: I don't believe that was his testimony. 
 
THE WITNESS: I don't remember that part. I don't know. 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: I understand. But I mean it was your impression that subsequent 
to May of 1993 and certainly up to and including May of 1994, 
Nicole did not have any relations with men that you're aware of 
other than perhaps with O.J. Correct? 
 
A: Yeah, I thought that was the time they were going to try to 
make it work. It was one of those things where -- that I had 
mentioned one time they had a good relationship. It was a stormy 
relationship, but Nicole would say she was together with him since 
19 and it was like 17 years together, and although they still were 
friends, and they would go apart, and it was very stormy, and yet I 
said that was good because they're still in each other's life. And I 
thought it was kind of like that unconditional thing, that although 
she said that during the relationship that O.J. cheated, that she still 
took him back. It was kind of that stormy --  
 
MR. SIMPSON: Took him back? 
 
THE WITNESS: And that's how I said it was kind of a good 
unconditional, that it was still happening; they were getting 
together. 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: Q: I want to use a time frame here. 
and if in fact it was your impression that Nicole was not being 
untrue to O.J. following their reconciliation in May of 1993, at 
least up to May of 1994, the incidents when Marcus Allen would 
come over were before May of 1993. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Now, when -- between February of 1993 when you first started 
learning the personal intimate details of Nicole 's life and May of 
1993, when did Marcus Allen come over and park his car any place 
other than in the front of the house? 
 
A: There was a trip that O.J. and Nicole took I think to Cabo back 
then. That would get my memory if I knew the date, because it was 
before then that Marcus was coming over and seeing Nicole. I 
think they might have took the trip in April. 
 
So Marcus was maybe coming there in April. I don't know when 
they took the trip in -- to Cabo, and that was Like -- I think that's 
when Nicole told him that Marcus was seeing her. I don't know the 
exact thing, but I think Marcus was coming over in April. 
 
Q: All right. Let me go back a bit further. After you moved into the 
back house at Gretna Green, you were aware that O.J. didn't go 
into the house. He would pick up the kids from the front. Isn't that 
true? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And O.J. -- Strike that. And Nicole told you that O.J. had 
agreed not to come in the house, didn't she? 
 
A: I think so. 
 
Q: And before O.J. was even coming in the house, Nicole was 
telling you that she wanted to get back and remarry O.J. Simpson 
because the best years of her Life was when she was married to 
him. Isn't that right? 
 
A: There were times when she said she wanted to get back together 
with O.J., yes. 
 
Q: And she told you that she was making a concerted effort to get 
back in O.J.'s life between February and May of 1993. Isn't that 
true? 
 
A: Yes. she was trying to get back together at times. 
 
Q: And during that period of time she informed you that she had 
told O.J. about her relationship with Marcus Allen. Right? 
 
A: I believe so. 
 
Q: And it was in April of 1993 that she indicated to you that she 
told O.J. about this relationship. Isn't that correct? 
 
A: I think it was April, yes. 
 
Q: And at that time O.J. was coming around the Gretna Green 
house, was he not? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And he was not jealous or angry or at all upset to your 
knowledge about anything she had done with Marcus Allen. Isn't 
that true? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Calls for speculation.  
 
THE WITNESS: Yes. 
 
BY MR. ROBERT LAKER: 
 
Q: And as a matter of fact, Mr. Kaelin O.J. -- Well, strike that. 
 
A: There was -- can I say something? There was a trip that was 
took, and she said the first two days of the trip were real tough, but 
they got better with O.J. I think that was after the Marcus situation. 
 
I don't -- that was -- it was like very tough. There was a fight and 
she almost came back, she said, but they stuck it out there, and I -- 
but I -- I think it was in April. That was the Cabo trip. 
 
Q: Now, Mr. Kaelin, as you sit here today and yesterday, you have 
heard a lot, you've read a lot about the surrounding events of the 
murders of Nicole Simpson and Ron Goldman. True? 
 
A: True, 
 
Q: And can you tell us that the testimony that you gave all 
yesterday was clearly your recollection of events unaided by 
anything you've read or heard? 
 
A: I think some of the --  
 
MR. KELLY: Well, objection. I think he's already testified as to 
what he's reviewed and heard prior to his testimony. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I object to the question as to form. Lacks 
foundation. 
 
THE WITNESS: The question again? 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: Sure. Can you tell us that the testimony that you gave yesterday 
and up to an hour ago or so when we took the break and they 
changed the tapes was all your testimony from your recollection 
unaided by anything you've read in the media, unaided by anything 
you've seen on the electronic media and simply your recollection 
of events? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I am going to object, Mr. Baker. I think the 
question is fundamentally unfair because it literally requires him to 
canvas each and every piece of testimony that he gave over two 
days and make an association as to whether or not he read anything 
about it or heard anything about it, and I don t think it's possible 
for that question to be answered, and I object to it. It lacks 
foundation, it's overbroad, it's compound, it's vague and it's 
ambiguous. Those are my objections for the record. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: I just have a question 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Ripkin doesn't recognize any of them. Go 
ahead, ,Mr. Plotkin. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: If you will clarify the question. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Does Ripkin wear a robe? 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: He was too smart to do that. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: These days he's not wearing much of anything. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: We won't let the judge read that part, Mr. 
Baker. 
 
MR. KELLY: I might give it to him.. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Yeah, RIVERA LIVE tonight. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Let Mr. Plotkin put what he wants on the 
record, please 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: Simply to understand the question, are you asking 
whether his reaction to what is now I guess 18 months of media 
and the like has tempered his -- or are you asking whether 
something he read in preparation for this deposition affected his... 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: Basically what I'm asking, Mr. Kaelin, is: What you have heard 
on the media, whether it be on the radio, on television, what you 
have read in the news media print, has that tempered your 
recollection and has altered your testimony from what you 
previously have given to the Grand Jury --  
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Same objection. 
 
MR. BREWER: Same objections. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Okay. 
 
THE WITNESS: Should I go? 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: Go ahead. 
 
A: This is -- obviously I have seen some things on TV: I have seen 
things in print, but with my testimony maybe -- I don't know -- like 
the degree I can't give but, yeah, I've read certain things that it 
didn't taint what I said. but certain things did come up that I didn't 
know before from trial and. . . 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: Can I ask one favor? l assume when you whisper 
to Mr. Baker that you don't intend for me to hear what you're 
saying. 
 
MR. SIMPSON: Did you hear what I just said? 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: No, but I've heard a number of things that you 
have said. 
 
MR. SIMPSON: Well. you can hear. No secrets. I've got no 
secrets. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: I just think in fairness that you ought to be aware 
of it. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Thank you. 
 
Q: Now. you testified within the last hour and a half something to 
the effect, "I don't know because it's been so long ago and there's 
been so many news stories, that I'm confused " Do you recall your 
testimony in that regard when you were talking about your 
movements on June 12th, 1994? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Now, have you read anything about the background of Nicole 
and O.J. Simpson that has colored your testimony relative to the 
time period between February of 1993 and May of 1993, if you 
know? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Same objections. 
 
MR. KELLY: Objection to the form of the question. 
 
THE WITNESS: I don't know the answer. 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: All right. Fair enough. 
 
Now. do you have a recollection of when you were talking to 
Nicole in this time frame between February and May of 1993. that 
she indicated to you that O.J. would be upset about Marcus Allen? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Tell me when that was. 
 
A: It was when Marcus was coming by, those trips before he was 
going to leave for camp, and she just said that O.J. would be so 
pissed if he knew Marcus was coming over. 
 
And I went, "Really?" Because I didn't know anything was really 
even going on and -- but he was parking on a different street. 
 
Q: And then you found out later that, of course, O.J. wasn't upset at 
all about Marcus when Nicole actually told him that she wanted his 
assistance to end Marcus coming over to the house. Isn't that right? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: That misstates his testimony, Mr. Baker. 
 
MR. BREWER: Also calls for speculation. 
 
THE WITNESS: I just -- I think so, because I know he got married 
at her house -- at his house. I didn't know what the situation was 
with Marcus at all, what was actually going on. but I didn't -- I 
know that he got married at the house, so I thought everybody was 
--  
 
MR. PETROCELLI: He is not asking you if he got married. Listen 
to the question. 
 
THE WITNESS: Oh, okay. I just know -- I didn't know -- there 
wasn't any -- 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: How come you didn't do that when you 
were questioning? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I tried to, but you inter -- 
 
Listen to the question. That's why I did it Mr. Baker. He's running 
out of paper. 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: Now, you indicated to Mr. Shapiro that O.J. was never upset 
about Nicole dating other men, did you not? 
 
A: At that time, yeah. I think O.J. knew Nicole was seeing other 
people. 
 
Q: He was never upset about that, was he? 
 
A: Not that I saw. 
 
Q: He never told you he was upset about Nicole dating anybody. 
Isn't that true? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Now, what point of time? 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: At any time that you were either a guest in Gretna Green or a 
guest in Rockingham. 
 
A: Well, there was a thing with the pushing of buttons that I 
mentioned that started happening at the Gretna Green -- Q: Well, 
maybe you didn't understand the question. 
 
MR. PLOTKIN: Why don't you let him answer the question. 
 
MR. KELLY: Well Objection. I'd like to See if he can answer it 
before you decide if he didn't understand it, Mr. Baker. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: All right. 
 
THE WITNESS: There was --  
 
MR. PLOTKIN: Wait, wait, wait, wait. Let's make sure that you do 
understand the question, and then --  
 
THE WITNESS: I think what you're trying to say is, was there any 
-- was O.J., mad that Nicole was dating others. 
 
BY MR. ROBERT BAKER: 
 
Q: No, that isn't what I asked at all. I asked you: Did O.J. ever tell 
you that he was upset that Nicole would date other men? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: That's the question. It's different from before, 
but that's the pending question. 
 
THE WITNESS: Not that I can remember. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Ed says it was different. I agree with him.  
 
Now, I think we're running out of paper, and why don't we --  
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Call it. 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: -- call it for today. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: 9:30 tomorrow' 
 
MR. ROBERT BAKER: Why don't we make it 10:00. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: 10:00 o'clock tomorrow? 
 
You guys can get an early tee time before then, can't you? You can 
play nine. 
 
MR. SIMPSON: My normal game -- THE VIDEOGRAPHER: 
This concludes the deposition of Brian Kaelin, Volume II. The 
number of videotapes used was two, We are going off the record, 
and the time is approximately 4:53. 
 
(ENDING TIME: 4:53 PM.) 
 
I DECLARE UNDER PENALTY OF PERJURY THAT THE 
FOREGOING IS TRUE AND CORRECT 
 
SUBSCRIBED AT _________ CALIFORNIA, THIS DAY OF 
_________ 19__ BRIAN KAELIN 
