<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: O.J. Simpson</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Faye Resnick describes O.J. Simpson as a drug-abusing wife beater in the first day of her three-day deposition. He played the part of star athlete in public. But when he got angry with his wife, "His jaw would protrude, his teeth would clench, sweat would come pouring from his head," she said. "The only way to describe it is animalistic."</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
SUPERIOR COURT FOR THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA IN 
THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES 
-------------------------------------------------------x        
SHARON RUFO, Case No. 
Plaintiff, SC 031917; 
-against- C/W Case No. 
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al., SC ()36340; 
Defendants. C/W Case No. 
--------------------------------------------------------x SC 036876 
FREDRIC GOLDMAN, an individual, and as 
personal representative of the Estate 
of Ronald Lyle Goldman, Deceased, et al., 
Plaintiffs, 
-against- 
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al. 
Defendants. 
----------------------------------------------------x 
LOUIS H. BROWN, as Executor and 
personal representative of the 
Estate of NICOLE BROWN SIMPSON, 
Plaintiff, 
-against- 
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, 
Defendant. 
 
Videotaped deposition of FAYE RESNICK, taken 
by Plaintiff, pursuant to notice, at the offices of 
John Quinlan Kelly, Esq.,330 Madison Avenue, New York, New 
York, on February 10,1996 at 1:43 p.m., 
before Cary N. Bigelow, a Shorthand Reporter and 
Notary Public within and for the State of New York. 
 
APPEARANCES: 
MITCHELL, SILBERBERG & KNUPP 
Attorneys for Plaintiffs Fredric Goldman, et al. 
11377 West Olympic Boulevard, Sixth Floor 
Los Angeles, California 90064-1683 
BY: DANIEL M. PETROCELLI, ESQ., of Counsel 
 
JOHN QUINLAN KELLY, ESQ. 
Attorney for Plaintiff Estate of Brown 
330 Madison Avenue 
New York, New York 10017-5090 
-and- 
MARK KRONE, ESQ., of Counsel 
 
HORNBERGER & CRISWELL 
Attorneys for Plaintiff Sharon Rufo 
444 South Flower Street, 31st Floor 
Los Angeles, California 90071 
BY: MICHAEL A. BREWER, ESQ., of Counsel 
     
BAILEY, FISHMAN & LEONARD 
Attorneys for Defendant Orenthal James Simpson 
66 Long Wharf 
Boston, Massachusetts 02110 
BY: DANIELLEONARD, ESQ. 
    
GOLD, FARRELL & MARKS 
Attorneys for the Witness Faye Resnick 
41 Madison Avenue 
New York, New York 10010 
BY: LEONARD M. MARKS, ESQ. 
-and- 
MARK S. LAFAYETTE, ESQ., of Counsel 
    
ALSO PRESENT: 
PAUL CYNAMON, Videographer 
 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Good afternoon. Today is February 10, 
1996. The time is 1:43 p.m. This is tape number 1 of the 
videotaped deposition of Faye Resnick taken on behalf of plaintiff 
in the case of Sharon Rufo, plaintiff, versus Orenthal James 
Simpson, et al., defendants. The venue of the case is the Superior 
Court of the State of California in the County of Los Angeles, Case 
SC 01947, SC 03640 and SC 036876. The deposition is being held 
at 330 Madison Avenue, in New York City. My name is Paul 
Cynamon, certified video specialist from the firm of Barrister 
Video Services, 1056 Olympia Road, North Bellmore, New York 
11710. Will counsel please introduce themselves? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Daniel M. Petrocelli, of Mitchell Silberberg 
& Knupp, for plaintiff Fredric Goldman. 
 
MR. KELLY: John Kelly for Plaintiff Brown. 
 
MR. KRONE: Mark Krone for Plaintiff Brown. 
 
MR. LEONARD: Daniel Leonard for O.J. Simpson. 
 
MR. LAFAYETTE: Mark Lafayette for Faye Resnick. 
 
MR. MARKS: Leonard Marks, attorney, with Mark Lafayette, for 
Faye Resnick. 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Would the court reporter please identify 
himself and swear in the witness. 
 
THE COURT REPORTER: This is Cary Bigelow, the court 
reporter. 
 
FAYE RESNICK, called as a witness, having been first duly sworn 
by the Notary Public (Cary N. Bigelow), was examined and 
testified as follows: 
 
MR. MARKS: I just want to make a brief statement that Faye 
Resnick has agreed voluntarily to testify under oath. Both sides can 
question her. I want to advise both sides that the questions asked 
her should be material and necessary, relate to the allegations of 
both sides in the pleadings in the case and please do not ask 
argumentative questions. Thank you very much. 
 
EXAMINATION BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q. Good afternoon, Ms. Resnick. 
 
A. Good afternoon. 
 
Q . You were a friend of Nicole Brown Simpson; is that right? 
 
A. Yes. Q. You may have to speak up a little bit so that the people 
at the other end of the table can hear. 
 
A. Yes, I was. 
 
Q. When did you first meet Nicole? 
 
A.  I met her in 1980 - 1987, briefly, with O.J. Simpson. 
 
Q. While O.J. Simpson and Nicole were married? 
 
A. Yes, 
 
Q. And at that time did you form a relationship or friendship with 
Nicole? 
 
A. No, I did not. 
 
Q. Did you see her much thereafter? 
 
A. No, I did not. 
 
Q. At what point in time did you next see her? 
 
A. The next time I spoke with her was in 1990. 
 
Q. And what was that occasion? 
 
A. My friend Kris Jenner took me to her house to meet her. 
 
Q. And after you met Nicole at the Jenners' house at that time in 
1990, did you then develop a friendship and a relationship with 
her? 
 
A. Pardon me, I met her at Rockingham, at O.J.'s house in 
Rockingham; Kris and I went to their house. 
 
Q. Is that when your friendship sprung up with her? 
 
A. No. 
 
Q. When did you next speak with or see Nicole? 
 
A. The next time was May of 1992. 
 
Q. What were the circumstances? 
 
A. We all went to Cabo San Lucas, the Jenners, for - every May, 
we took, we did this. 
 
Q. By "the Jenners," you are referring to Kris Jenner, with a K, and 
Bruce Jenner? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Who else went? 
 
A. Cici Shahian, of course, Nicole, Joseph [Name Deleted], Isha 
Levy, all of our children, my ex-husband, Paul Resnick. 
 
Q. Now, at that time, in May of 1992, what was Nicole's marital 
status? 
 
A. She was separated, in the process of getting a divorce. 
 
Q. From O.J. Simpson? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And was it about this time, in May of 1992, that you began to 
develop a friendship with Nicole? 
 
A. Not really. She was - she was - it wasn't until July 4, 1992, that 
Nicole and I became great friends. 
 
Q. And can you describe to us what the evolution of that friendship 
was, what happened in July 1992 and thereafter? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I am going to object to the form. It's vague. 
 
Q. You can answer. 
 
A. We were at, once again, we were at the Jenners' home in Malibu 
and Nicole and I had met briefly in Cabo San Lucas. She was 
dating my then ex-boyfriend, Joseph [Name Deleted], and she was 
asking me on July 4th, because Joseph had not wanted to be around 
Nicole any longer, what she could do to encourage him to come 
back. 
 
Q. And you and she started talking about this? 
 
A. Yes, we did. 
 
Q. And Joseph [Name Deleted] was a man whom you had 
previously dated? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And you shared that with Nicole and the two of you started 
talking about Mr. [Name Deleted]? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Now, thereafter, is it true that you and Nicole began to get close 
to one another, as friends? 
 
A. Yes, very close. 
 
Q. Did that friendship grow and grow progressively? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Object to the leading. 
 
A. The friendship with Nicole from July 4th was immediate. It was 
immediate. It was the kind of friendship I felt was kindred. 
 
Q. Starting at that point in time, July 4, 1992 when, as you say, 
your friendship with Nicole sprung immediately into existence, did 
you then begin to see her regularly? 
 
A. Yes, I did. 
 
Q. Did you speak to her regularly? 
 
A. Yes, I did. 
 
Q . Did the two of you go out regularly? 
 
A. Yes, we did. 
 
Q. Did you talk on the phone regularly? 
 
A. Yes, we did. 
 
Q. Did you share experiences together? 
 
A. Yes, we did. 
 
Q. Did you confide in one another? 
 
A. All the time. 
 
Q. She and you? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q . She confided in you? 
 
A. And I confided in her. 
 
Q. And you confided in her? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Object to the leading. 
 
Q. Did the two of you confide in one another? 
 
A. Yes, we did. 
 
Q. Did - now, you have a child, Ms. Resnick? 
 
