A. No, I am not. Q. Would Mr. Simpson, during this period of 
time, this one-year or so period of this attempted reconciliation, 
call you more than one time a day? 
 
A. Sometimes Mr. Simpson, O.J., would call me six and seven 
times a day, sometimes more, sometimes less. 
 
Q. And would he call at all hours of the day or night? 
 
A. All hours. He used to call at 2 o'clock in the morning, 3 o'clock 
in the morning. 
 
Q. While you were sleeping? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And did you ever confront him with the fact that it's 3:00 in the 
morning and you are sleeping and why is he calling you? 
 
A. Every single time he called and woke me up I confronted him 
with it. 
 
Q. What did he say? 
 
A. "I just have to talk, I can't take it, l can't take it." Sorry. 
 
Q. That's what he would say? 
 
A. He had to talk. He had to talk. He had to release his anger, he 
had to release his frustrations. 
 
Q. Would you hang up on him? 
 
A. At times, I would. 
 
Q. Would you, at times, talk to him? 
 
A. Most of the times I would talk to him. I felt he was - when I 
would hang up on him, he would just call back, so I tried to talk 
him through it. 
 
Q. Would you tell Nicole about these conversations that you and 
Mr. Simpson would have? 
 
A. Yes, I did. 
 
Q. Did Mr. Simpson, to your knowledge, know that you were 
relating the information to Nicole? 
 
A. No, he did not. 
 
Q. Did he ask you not to? 
 
A. Yes, he did. 
 
Q. Your loyalty was to Nicole? 
 
A. Yes, it was. He used code names when he called my house. 
 
Q. He did? 
 
A. Yes, he did. 
 
Q. What do you mean by that? 
 
A. Because [Name Deleted] and Sydney were good friends. He did 
not want [Name Deleted] saying to Sydney, oh, your daddy is 
calling so much, your daddy called 10 times or your daddy called 
five times. So he used to say his name was Charles or James when 
he would call. 
 
Q. For the record, Sydney is whom? 
 
A. Nicole's daughter. 
 
Q. O.J.'s daughter? 
 
A. Yes, O.J.'s daughter. 
 
Q. So he didn't want his own daughter to know that he was calling 
so often when Sydney was at your home with [Name Deleted]? 
 
A. Yes. And he also didn't want [Name Deleted] telling Sydney 
when [Name Deleted] was at their home, that her father was calling 
our house all the time. 
 
Q. So he would leave the name - 
 
A. James or Charles. 
 
Q. Are these names that he told you were designated code names 
for O.J. Simpson? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Did you have a code name, too? 
 
A. No. 
 
Q. Did you tell Nicole about these code names? 
 
A. Yes, I did. She was furious. 
 
Q. Do you know whether Nicole - 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Withdrawn. 
 
Q. Did you, during this period of time when Nicole and O.J. were 
seeing each other again, ever see them get into arguments together? 
 
A. Many. 
 
Q. You witnessed them? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Did you ever see O.J. get really angry at Nicole? 
 
A. Yes, l have. 
 
Q. Did you ever see him up close get angry at Nicole ? 
 
A. Yes, l did. 
 
Q. More than once? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Many occasions? 
 
A. Three that really stick out in my mind. 
 
Q. That you personally witnessed? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Did O.J. Simpson, in your opinion, have a quick temper? 
 
A. Yes, he did. He had a very volatile - he was very volatile. 
 
Q. You have seen him fly off the handle? 
 
A. Yes, I have. 
 
Q. Now during those occasions when you saw Mr. Simpson get 
very angry toward Nicole, describe what his face would look like 
when he would get angry. And for that matter his - you can 
describe, like, his whole body. You know what I mean? 
 
A. Yes, I know. O.J. would get very - his facial structure, his jaw 
would protrude, his teeth would clench, sweat would come pouring 
from his head. You could see that his body, that he would perspire 
through his clothing. His eyes would get narrow and black. He 
became - and the only way to describe it is animalistic when he 
would become angry at Nicole. 
 
Q. And would this happen suddenly? 
 
A. It would happen within minutes. 
 
Q. You could visibly see these changes in his face? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. What about his body? Was there any body language that also 
changed? 
 
A. He just became bigger than life. He just got big. 
 
Q. Dominant? 
 
A. Very - it was very aggressive, just, you - 
 
Q. Did it frighten you? 
 
A. Absolutely. 
 
Q. How did you feel when you saw O.J. Simpson get that way? 
How did it make you feel? 
 
A. I felt very small and insignificant. I felt afraid for myself also. 
 
Q. Would he yell? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. What tone of voice? Loud? 
 
A. He would be very deep but very loud. It was as if a different 
person just took over and it was like watching a possessed man. 
 
Q. Would he use profanity? 
 
A. Oh, yes, the worst. The worst. 
 
Q . Were any of these three occasions where you witnessed Mr. 
Simpson in this way in public places? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Did he - and he did this even though he was in public? 
 
A. He had no control over it. Yes. 
 
Q. You are saying he would use loud profanity, yelling, in public? 
 
A. Yes, he did. And one particular, the first time I had seen it was 
in Hermosa Beach at a sushi restaurant. 
 
Q. California Sushi? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Describe that incident, please? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Can we get a date, please? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: If you don't, you have the- 
 
