A. Never. 
 
Q. Did you ever see him wear any disguise in public? 
 
A. Never. 
 
Q. Did he ever tell you that he was going to buy a disguise or use a 
disguise in order not to be recognized in public? 
 
A. He loved the public. He loved to be seen, he loved it. 
 
Q. So he - 
 
A. He never said that he ever would even - he never said that at all. 
 
Q. Did he ever tell you that when going out with the children to 
places like Disneyland or Knotts Berry Farm, that he would don a 
disguise to conceal his identity? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. Leading. 
 
Q. Did he ever tell you that? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. 
 
A. He never told me that. I have been with O.J. Simpson in public 
numerous - too many times to count and he - I have been with him 
to all of these public places. He never - he enjoyed the attention. 
He never said he would ever not enjoy it. He didn't even like to go 
to other countries because he didn't get the attention in other 
countries . 
 
Q. Is that what he said to you? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Focusing on the children for a moment, did he ever discuss with 
you the subject of using a disguise when with the children in 
public? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. 
 
Q. Did he ever discuss that topic with you? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. 
 
A. O.J. Simpson never discussed ever using a disguise. As I said, I 
have been with him to a lot of different public places. I have been 
with him, with the Simpsons, to Disneyland. I have been with them 
to many public places. He never wore a disguise. 
 
Q. Did you ever go anyplace with O.J. Simpson and Sydney and 
Justin Simpson in public? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And did he ever wear a disguise? 
 
A. Absolutely not. 
 
Q. Did he ever try to avoid people or publicity on those occasions? 
 
A. Never. He loved it. 
 
Q. Did O.J. Simpson ever discuss with you whether Nicole's 
conduct was hurting or helping his public image? 
 
A. Yes, he did. 
 
Q. What did he say on that subject? 
 
A. O.J. had said, right before Nicole was murdered, in a 
conversation that I had with him over the phone, that Nicole had 
ruined his public image twice before and he was not about - not 
about ready to let her ruin it again by leaving him. 
 
Q. Tell me when that conversation occurred. 
 
A. The conversation occurred on May 2nd or May 3rd of 1994. 
 
Q. And tell me as best as you can recall, what else O.J. Simpson 
said on that occasion. 
 
A. That was the phone call that O.J. said he would kill Nicole. 
 
Q. Tell us everything that was said in that telephone conversation 
by O.J. Simpson and by you. 
 
A. O.J. was - there was a - their relationship at that point was very 
volatile and Nicole had told him she never wanted to see him 
again, and due to the fact that he had just - we had just gotten back 
from Cabo San Lucas and he had blatantly, in front of all of - in 
front of the Jenners, in front of myself, in front of Christian, in 
front of all of us, flirted with a blonde woman at the table that we 
were at, and then - 
 
Q. In Cabo - 
 
A. In Cabo San Lucas. And then O.J. that night or the next night 
had said, was making jokes about being a frogman, telling us about 
how he was learning all of these techniques with, you know, 
underwater night - you know. He was telling us about his filming 
of The Frogman episode and talking about the wet suit and talking 
about how his wife's biggest fear is frogs and he was now The 
Frogman, and saying, What do you think of this, and Nicole 
responded in a way, I don't think that's funny, O.J., I don't think it's 
funny at all. Nicole, from those two incidences, went from willing 
and ready to actually marry this man, in Cabo San Lucas, when we 
were there, to, I never want to see him again, I know he is going to 
kill me, I know this is all - that I cannot be with him anymore. 
 
Q. Let me stop you right there. What you just described occurred 
in Cabo San Lucas? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And you were present? 
 
A. Yes, I was. 
 
Q. And you witnessed those statements by O.J. Simpson? 
 
A. Yes, I did. 
 
Q. And by Nicole Brown Simpson? 
 
A. Yes, I did. 
 
Q. And this was in late April 1994? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
MR. LEONARD: I'm going to object to your characterization of 
the statements. There was a rambling answer. It wasn't clear to me 
at all there were statements - there might have been some 
statements in there. Some of them were thought processes and so 
forth, so - 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Mr. Leonard, I don't believe you were 
listening to the testimony. Because I believe the witness described 
all kinds of statements by O.J. Simpson. In any event, the record 
will speak for itself. 
 
Q. You said that Nicole Brown Simpson had a fear of frogs? 
 
A. She had a phobia of frogs. 
 
Q. Did she ever tell you that? 
 
A. Oh, yeah. 
 
Q. Describe what she said to you about her fear of frogs? 
 
A. She said that - she said that she wasn't afraid of anything. This 
was - she didn't have phobias, she wasn't a girl that used to go in 
for - she was - let me just keep it brief. She said that she had a 
phobia against frogs. In fact, my ex-fiance had a frog collection, a 
ceramic collection, that she didn't even go close to. She was 
phobic. She was afraid of frogs and she - she was afraid of frogs. 
 
Q. Did she ever tell you what it was about frogs that frightened 
her? 
 
A. No, she never did. 
 
Q. Who was this ex-fiance that had the frog collection? 
 
A. Christian Reichardt. 
 
Q. Now, back to Cabo. Did O.J. Simpson say anything to Nicole 
on the subject of frogs or the frogman? 
 
A. He said - he explained to us the frogman episode. He explained 
that he loved the episode, that he felt like it was - it was exciting, 
and then he went on to make jokes about how Nicole feared frogs 
more than anything in the world and he was now the frogman. 
 
Q. Did he say that? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. What did he say? 
 
A. He said - 
 
MR. MARKS: Didn't you just ask her that? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: I want to make sure I am understanding. 
 
Q. Just tell me, as best you remember, what did he say about being 
the frogman? 
 
A. He said, Isn't it interesting or isn't it funny that my wife's 
biggest fear is frogs and I'm the frogman. 
 
Q. You heard him say that? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And you saw Nicole's reaction? 
 
A. Oh, yes. 
 
Q. And what was it? 
 
A. She said, That's not funny at all; I'm afraid of this. She - Nicole 
went - I think maybe Nicole was - he had just at that point, from 
that moment, Nicole stopped blocking any of the - she stopped 
fantasizing that the relationship could work. 
 
Q. Now on this same trip in Cabo - 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Withdrawn. 
 
Q. How did - did you see Mr. Simpson's reaction to Nicole's 
reaction to the frogman comment? 
 
A. I didn't really notice his reaction. 
 
Q. Okay. During this same trip, you said you saw, with your own 
eyes, Mr. Simpson flirting with another woman'? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Was Nicole present when Mr. Simpson did that? 
 
A. Yes, she was. 
 
Q. Did she see Mr. Simpson do that? 
 
A. Yes, she did. 
 
Q. Did she say anything to you about it? 
 
A. She just - at the time, she didn't respond. She just looked like, in 
disgust. 
 
Q. Did you see Mr. Simpson - 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Withdrawn. 
 
Q. Did Mr. Simpson say anything to you or you to him, about this 
flirting episode? 
 
A. Yes, I did. I had a conversation with he and Kris Jenner about it 
afterwards. 
 
Q. And tell me what you said and what Mr. Simpson said in that 
conversation. 
 
A. Nicole had went to the restroom and Kris and I had said, why 
are you doing this so blatantly, so openly? You are not only 
embarrassing us, you are embarrassing Nicole. Why are you doing 
this? I'm not doing anything. I'm just a little flirting. Our children 
are here, your wife is here. It's not funny. 
 
Q. Were the children present at the restaurant when Mr. Simpson 
was doing the flirting? 
 
A. Yes, they were. Yes, they were. 
 
Q. And who were the children? 
 
A. Sydney and Justin and I believe a couple of the Jenners' 
children. 
 
Q. Can you describe the flirtatious activity that you saw Mr. 
Simpson do? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Please do so. 
 
A. We were sitting at the very edge of the restaurant at the wall and 
O.J. and Nicole were sitting on this side, and the bar was here. I 
had my back to the bar, facing the Simpsons, and I could see, O.J.'s 
face started doing the - you know, he started flirting and I -you 
know, what is he looking at, so I turned around and looked, and 
there was this blonde girl that was flirting back with him. And they 
were waving, they were smiling and they were winking. It was 
disgusting. It was - it was blatant. And that was it. 
 
Q. Okay. Did you - I think you said previously that when Nicole 
went on this trip to Cabo, she was prepared to remarry Mr. 
Simpson? 
 
A. Oh, they were this close. They were both so ready to remarry. 
 
Q. How long were the Simpsons in Cabo, during this trip? 
 
A. We had stayed longer, Nicole and I. O.J., I believe, was there 
for three days, three or four days. 
 
Q. And he left? 
 
A. And he left to go to Puerto Rico to continue the filming of the 
frogman. He was strictly on break. 
 
Q. And by the way, going back to the frogman incident, did Mr. 
Simpson describe to you and the others that were present, the - any 
particular episode or sequence in the frogman movie that he was 
filming? 
 
A. Only that he loved the filming of it, that he got to - only what I 
had said earlier. 
 
Q. Did he describe any scene, any - 
 
A. No, he did not. 
 
Q. -- any action by him? 
 
A. No, he did not. 
 
Q. Did he mention anything about using a knife? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection, leading. 
 
A. No, he did not. 
 
Q. Did the subject of a knife come up? 
 
A. No, it did not. 
 
Q. Okay. Do you know whether Nicole told O.J. about her change 
of heart before Mr. Simpson left to go to Puerto Rico? 
 
A. No, she did not. 
 
Q. Do you know that she did not tell him - 
 
A. Yes, I know that she did not. 
 
Q. And how do you know that? 
 
A. Because I had asked her. 
 
Q. You asked her what? 
 
A. I asked her if she had told him. She said, no, I'm not going to 
tell him yet. 
 
Q. Now, you said that after these two incidents, namely the flirting 
incident and the frogman incident, that Nicole expressed to you her 
feeling that she was finished with Mr. Simpson? 
 
A. She expressed to me that she felt that all of the thoughts that she 
had had in the past all of the threats that he had made to her in the 
past of killing her, would some day come true and she wanted 
nothing more to do with him, nothing. 
 
Q. She said that to you? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Did she - 
 
A. She said it was over. 
 
Q. She said it was over? 
 
A. Mm-hmm. 
 
Q. Between her and Mr. Simpson? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. And what did she say to you about the subject of threats? What 
did she say specifically about that, to you? 
 
A. This is when Nicole - the next day, that O.J. left, this is when 
Nicole told me about all of the abuse, and she also told me about 
all of the threats and she also told me about - from that night on, 
Nicole was a different person. Nicole was no longer in a fantasy 
world. She had realized that all of the threats, she remembered all 
of the abuse. She had broken through that pearl that she had 
formed around the abuse and was now having a catharsis by telling 
me about it. 
 
Q. The two of you were alone? 
 
A. Yes, we were. 
 
Q. Where were you? 
 
A. We were at the Palmilla restaurant in Cabo San Lucas. 
 
Q. Was this a long conversation over dinner? 
 
A. It was before dinner. We had left early and others had joined us 
after that for dinner. 
 
Q. And Nicole sort of poured all of this out? 
 
A. Everything. 
 
Q. How long did that conversation last before the others joined 
you? 
 
MR. MARKS: Approximately. 
 
Q. Approximately. An hour? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Object to the leading. 
 
Q. How long did it last? 
 
A. I couldn't tell you. I didn't - I - 
 
Q. Well, as best you can recall, what did Nicole say about abuse 
and threats? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I didn't hear the end of your question. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: About abuse and threats. 
 
MR. LEONARD: Okay. 
 
Q. What did Nicole say to you in that conversation about abuse and 
threats? 
 
A. Nicole had said that - when I asked her, because - I knew she 
was afraid of frogs and I knew that there had been abuse, but it was 
such a dramatic change that she had made, and it was so quick, that 
I needed to talk with her about it, so I asked her, what is going on, 
explain to me the - you know, why you have suddenly changed 
your mind so abruptly when you knew all of this stuff in the past, 
this is the same man. And she said, it just all came pouring back to 
her the night he had talked of frogs, the night he was flirting, 
blatantly flirting, that he had threatened her life many a time, 
threatened to take her children away from her. He had beaten her 
too many times to count, he had locked her in a closet and beat her 
with wine bottles. He had bruised her, broken her ribs, sent her to 
the hospital, made her tell the doctor that she was - she had fallen 
off a bicycle; that on one particular occasion he had locked her in 
the closet and - he had locked her in the closet and he had beat her, 
kicked her, slapped her, pulled her hair, threw her in the closet and 
left her there for 15 minutes, and then she came back to - and he 
came back and opened the door and she thought he was going to let 
her out and he started beating her again and he continued doing 
that all night long to her; that every time she would think that he 
would come back he was going to kill her. She thought that he was 
going to beat her to death that night. And he would go and watch a 
football game between the times that she was left in the closet. And 
that was unbelievable to me. Nicole thought she was going to die 
that night. She had told - 
 
Q. The night of the beating? 
 
A. The night of that particular beating. 
 
Q. That was what she was telling you? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. Okay. Please continue. 
 
A. She had told me about the pregnancy beatings, when he used to 
kick her in the stomach and tell her that she was worthless and he 
talked to her, he beat her. When she found the earrings that he had 
given to Tawny Kitaen, he - she had told me that she had had so 
many beatings over Tawny Kitaen that she couldn't even count 
them. And she said that - she said that Sydney saw some of them 
and, um - 
 
Q. Take your time. 
 
A. She - can I stop for a minute, please? 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Are we going off the record? 
 
MR. MARKS: Yes. Let's go off the record now. 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: The time is 4:56. We are going off the 
record. 
 
(Discussion off the record.) 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: The time is 4:57. We are back on the 
record. 
 
Q. I realize this is very difficult for you, Miss Resnick, and I 
apologize. We will try to get through this as quickly as we can. 
You were telling us about the evening when, in Cabo, Nicole was 
relating to you, really for the first time, the history of abuse and 
threats at the hand of Mr. Simpson. Is that right? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection to the leading. 
 
Q. Is that what you - 
 
A. That is correct. 
 
Q. Now, did she mention anything to you about an incident in Las 
Vegas? 
 
A. Yes, she did. 
 
Q. Can you describe what Nicole said to you about that incident? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Object to the leading. 
 
A. Nicole said that she had been at a party with O.J. in Las Vegas 
and there was a lot of important people there and she had 
embarrassed him in some way in front of Dean Martin, people that 
were important to him, and he told her that he wanted her to go to 
the room until she was - until he had joined her, until he was ready 
to come, and she did. And when he came to the room, he - she was 
in her panties, getting undressed, and he just attacked her because 
he said that she embarrassed him, and he viciously beat her that 
night and he threw her outside in the corridor of the hotel and left 
her there. That's what she said. 
 
Q. In talking to you about the many beatings resulting from Mr. 
Simpson's relationship with Tawny Kitaen, did the subject of 
earrings ever come up? 
 
A. Yes. 
 
Q. What did Nicole Brown Simpson say to you about that? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection to the leading. 
 
A. I had mentioned the earrings prior. She was walking - she was 
cleaning up around the house and she was putting something in his 
dresser drawer and she saw a little red box and she opened the box 
and there was a beautiful pair of earrings inside and she - 
 
Q. By "beautiful," do you mean expensive? 
 
A. Yeah. She said they were very big, very expensive. She thought 
they were very expensive. 
 
Q. More than a thousand dollars? 
 
A. She said something like $20,000. And she was thinking it was - 
they were coming to her as a present because her birthday was 
coming. 
 
Q. This is while she was married to Mr. Simpson? 
 
A. This is while she was married to Mr. Simpson. And she put 
them back, you know, wanted to be surprised with them. And her 
birthday rolled around and she never received the earrings. And 
she had found out through a friend that O.J. had given those 
earrings to [Name Deleted] and she was - and Tawny was walking 
around town, flaunting them, this is my present from O.J. And 
Nicole eventually heard all of this stuff back. I mean, she heard all 
of the gossip. O.J., you know, was a star at the time, I guess, when 
it happened. Nicole had heard, and also a friend had mentioned it 
to her. And she got really upset about it and she asked him about it 
and he beat her up viciously that night because - 
 
Q. That's what Nicole told you? 
 
A. Yes. Because she was not supposed to ask questions about his 
private life and he - she said that he made it her fault, like he makes 
everything her fault. She told me that he had been beating her since 
she was 17. And that's all I can recall. 
 
Q. This is the evening, and the conversation in Cabo when Nicole 
told you that she had had it with Mr. Simpson? 
 
A. Mm-hmm. Yes, it is. 
 
MR. MARKS: May we adjourn? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Sure. 
 
MR. MARKS: Are you finished with this area, at the current point? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: We can adjourn here, if you would like. 
 
MR. MARKS: Okay. 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: The time is 5:03. This is the end of tape 
number 2 of the deposition of Ms. Resnick and we are adjourned 
for today. 
 
(Time noted: 5:03 p.m.) 
 
FAYE RESNICK 
 
Subscribed and sworn to before me this day of, 1996. 
 
(Notary Public) My Commission Expires: 
 
CERTIFICATE 
 
STATE OF NEW YORK 
 
COUNTY OF NEW YORK 
 
 I, CARY N. BIGELOW, a Shorthand Reporter and a Notary 
Public within and for the State of New York, do hereby certify that 
the foregoing deposition of Faye Resnick was taken before me on 
the 10th day of February, 1996; That the said witness was duly 
sworn before the commencement of her testimony; that the said 
testimony was taken stenographically by me and then transcribed. I 
further certify that I am not related by blood or marriage to any of 
the parties to this action nor interested directly or indirectly in the 
matter in controversy; nor am I in the employ of any of the counsel 
in this action. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, I have hereunto set my 
hand this 13th day of February, 1996. 
 
 CARY N. BIGELOW February 10, 1996 
 
EXHIBITS PLAINTIFFS' FOR IDENT 78 Book entitled Nicole 
Brown Simpson: The Private Diary of a Life Interrupted 21 79 
Book entitled Shattered, In the Eye of the Storm 22 
