<H2>Bombing Trial's New Look, Issues</H2><P>

By Robert Schmidt <BR>
<I>Legal Times</I><BR>
November 4, 1996 <P>

One of the biggest federal trials ever staged suddenly has been transformed into two of the biggest trials ever. <P>

And as the Oklahoma City bombing case moves forward, that transformation not only has implications for each side's legal strategy, but also will touch witnesses, the crime victims and their families, and U.S. taxpayers. <P>

Most notably, Chief Judge Richard Matsch's surprising Oct. 25 decision to sever the trials of accused bombers Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols appears to be a setback for the prosecution. <P>

The government had argued that the two former Army buddies who were charged together should be tried together. And although prosecutors downplay the ruling's significance and say they are eager to get their evidence before a jury, they now face the challenge of planning and carrying out two highly charged, sensational trials instead of just one. <P>

Moreover, the government must prove that the two men were engaged in a conspiracy to bomb the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building -- without the prospect of both alleged conspirators sitting next to each other in the courtroom. <P>

Defense lawyers for McVeigh and Nichols proclaimed the severance ruling a victory, saying that separate trials will force the prosecution to try each case on its merits, rather than allowing the government to paint the defendants with a broad brush ofguilt. <P>

"This, at least in theory, sets the stage for a fair trial," says Stephen Jones, Timothy McVeigh's lead counsel. <P>

Jones adds that he is quite pleased with the outcome of his pretrial wrangling with the prosecution, in which he prevailed not only on the severance issue but also on bids to get the case heard by a judge not from Oklahoma and to move the trial out of state. <P>

Still, prosecutors appear upbeat and confident of their ability to win convictions against McVeigh, who is alleged to have actually carried out the bombing in Oklahoma City, and Nichols, a Kansas farmer alleged to have helped plan the bombing. The April 19, 1995, blast resulted in 168 deaths and more than 500 injured. <P>

"Nothing affects the admissibility of evidence in the severance ruling," says prosecution team member Larry Mackey, special attorney to the U.S. attorney general. <P>

"We were not looking for any strategic advantage [in arguing for a joint trial]," Mackey offers, "but looking, hopefully, to the advantages that would flow to the victims, the witnesses, and the judicial system that would reap the benefits of earlier closure." <P>

While most observers agree that Matsch's decision can be seen as a boost to the defense, experts caution that its costs and benefits are not as clear-cut as they may seem. <P>

The prosecution, for example, derives a potentially huge hidden benefit from the ruling, in that it eliminates the defendants' most significant appealable issue-the claim that a joint trial violated their constitutional rights. <P>

And while it seems that Nichols, who will be tried second, appears to be in the better position, his defense team will have to sit mum as the judge makes evidentiary rulings in the first trial that will likely affect Nichols' trial, too. <P>

As the pretrial hearing schedule in U.S. District Court in Denver winds down (the pretrial hearings will continue to be tried together) and the lawyers prepare to litigate United States v. Timothy James McVeigh, experts say that subtleties such as these will keep all three legal teams busy. <P>

Among the questions the three sides need to consider, say a number of law professors and litigators, are: Will McVeigh have to worry that prosecutors will cut a deal with Nichols in exchange for his testimony? Will the government hold back on some of its evidence so that Nichols' counsel, watching the first trial, won't have a clear map of the prosecution? Will the jury pool be so tainted by publicity by the time Nichols' case begins that his lawyers will move for another change of venue? <P>

"It has got to change the strategies of everybody involved," observes defense attorney Henry Asbill of D.C.'s Asbill, Junkin & Moffitt, who adds that the ruling bodes well for McVeigh and Nichols. "This decision to give separate trials, coupled with the fairness and length of the jury selection process, are the two keys to winning this case." <P>

One clear effect of Matsch's severance ruling is that it goes a long way toward helping McVeigh secure a fair trial, say outside experts, as well as his own attorneys. <P>

Because of the severance, the jury in McVeigh's case will not hear the nine hours of statements Nichols made to agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation shortly before he was arrested; those statements are said to pin much of the blame for the blast on McVeigh. (The complete statements are sealed, as is much of the evidence in the case, under the judge's order not to disclose sensitive discovery material.) <P>

Although the statements previously were ruled inadmissible against McVeigh, Judge Matsch feared that a jury in a single trial would be unable to consider them only against Nichols. <P>

"[T]here is an unacceptable risk that the jury will use Terry Nichols' extrajudicial statements against Timothy McVeigh," Matsch wrote in his 20-page order. "Timothy McVeigh will be profoundly prejudiced by a joint trial of this case." <P>

POTENTIAL PREJUDICE <BR>
Indeed, Matsch based his ruling largely on the potential prejudice to McVeigh from Nichols' statements, which he said could violate McVeigh's Sixth Amendment right to cross-examination and his Fifth Amendment right to due process. The statements reportedly mentioned McVeigh's name more than 60 times, but because Nichols cannot be compelled to testify, McVeigh's attorneys would be powerless to punch holes in the highly incriminating statements. <P>

The judge in his opinion also gave credence to the defense lawyers' arguments that the two defendants had antagonistic defenses. While the defenses were not mutually exclusive, Matsch noted that "there will be substantial and significant differences in the tactical approaches taken by their respective counsel." <P>

In fact, by separating the trials, Matsch removed the potential for much acrimony inside his courtroom. Both Jones and Nichols' lawyer, Michael Tigar, indicated in their severance briefs that their clients were poised to blame each other for the crime.Even if they continue this strategy of finger-pointing, it will now be more muted. <P>

"Severance changes the whole dynamic of the trial because there won't be quite the same finger-pointing and falling out amongst the attorneys for McVeigh and Nichols, at least not in front of the jury," observes Paul Rothstein, a professor at Georgetown University Law Center who teaches criminal procedure. "Fighting and refuting each other makes them both look noncredible" to the jury, Rothstein notes. <P>

The ruling should also make each trial quicker than a joint proceeding would have been. There will only be one cross-examination of each witness and one defense case, and the prosecution will be able to pare down its case by focusing on one defendant. <P>

"[Severance] streamlines the case," says Professor Stephen Saltzburg of the George Washington University Law School. "You don't need to worry about two defense lawyers trying to weaken the case. It's now a straightforward U.S. v. McVeigh." <P>

Just how the prosecution pares down its case could be a crucial tactical move, experts say. Because the severance has in effect given Nichols full discovery through watching the McVeigh trial, prosecutors may try to hold back evidence that does incriminate McVeigh, but is more important to the case against Nichols. <P>

Such a move could help counter the advantage the Nichols defense gets by being able to see how the judge and jury react to certain arguments, as well as seeing how witnesses come across on the stand. <P>

"[The prosecutors] have to be very cautious to walk a fine line and seek to admit into evidence only that evidence they need to convict McVeigh, and nothing more," says D.C. defense lawyer Asbill. "They don't want to give Nichols any more of a preview of the case than is necessary." <P>

The prosecution, however, points out that, by trying McVeigh first, it too will learn what works and what doesn't.  <P>

"The truth of the matter is that we're watching the same preview as well," says Mackey, the prosecutor. <P>

'ELEMENT OF SURPRISE' <BR>
Instead of watching a preview, McVeigh is the preview. And his lawyer contends that this actually gives him the upper hand.  <P>

"I would much prefer to go first; we have the element of surprise," says Jones. "Number two, the government would be trying the case for the first time, and [won't be able] to recoup from mistakes that might or will be made."  <P>

Some observers, however, point out one significant disadvantage to the McVeigh team stemming from its position in the starting gate: the possibility of a Nichols plea bargain. <P>

"One thing about a separation like this is it puts some distance between the two defendants," says Saltzburg of George Washington. "[Nichols] now has this card of 'I could save you a second trial,' and if you combine that with 'I can save you a second trial and I can testify in the first trial'-that can be the single most valuable thing he can trade." <P>

Prosecutors decline comment on the possibility of plea discussions. Ronald Woods, an appointed counsel for Nichols, dismisses the idea. <P>

"The option of a plea has never arisen and so it's not something we're considering," says Woods. <P>

Of much more concern to Nichols' lawyers now is how McVeigh's trial will affect their client-particularly if it will be possible to find a jury untainted by the media attention. (The trial will not be televised.) <P>

"Based on what happens in the trial and based on whether we feel we can get a fair and impartial jury, we may be forced to file a motion for a change of venue," says Woods. "It depends on what happens. The government's case against Nichols is very weak, and it may show during that trial how weak, so we might not need a change." <P>

Of course, two faster trials will likely still take more time than one single trial. The added expense to taxpayers will be considerable: Hundreds of expected witnesses, many on the government payroll, must testify twice. The government is also paying for McVeigh's and Nichols' defenses.  <P>

Then there is the human cost. More than 2,000 victims and family members are looking for the trial to bring them closure. <P>

"I'm a little bit disappointed because of the enormous expense and the inconvenience to witnesses and victims of doing this trial twice," says William Pizzi, a professor of law at University of Colorado School of Law who teaches criminal procedure. "I'm not criticizing [Matsch's] decision, I just feel this is a weakness in our system." <P>

At first, many of the crime victims and family members were also disappointed in the severance ruling, says Paul Heath, president of the OK City Murrah Building Survivors Association. Heath notes, however, that prosecutors have since met with the victims in Oklahoma City and calmed some of their concerns. <P>

"The prosecution has assured us that the trials won't be much longer than if they have them together," says Heath. "Most everybody is willing to accept severance because there will be less chance of an appeal." <P>

<I>Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
