<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>

<H2>No Media Blitz for McVeigh</H2>



By Robert Schmidt <BR>

<I>Legal Times</I><BR>

October 7, 1996 <P>



DENVER--Accused Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh will not be going on a media blitz before his trial. <P>



Chief U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch, ruling from the bench on Oct. 4, denied McVeigh's motion to be allowed to conduct a series of interviews with hand-picked television and print reporters. <P>



Matsch avoided First Amendment questions in his ruling, finding that the interviews would violate a protective order he issued in June that prohibits discussing evidence in the case. McVeigh's interviews, the judge said, would constitute potential character evidence.  <P>



"It is an inappropriate pretrial dissemination of evidence," Matsch said. "The denial of this motion is consistent with the jurisdiction [of the court]." <P>



Matsch noted that McVeigh still has access to reporters by mail and telephone. Prosecutor Joseph Hartzler said in court that McVeigh has reporters on his telephone list. <P>



"I am reassured that Mr. McVeigh and [co-defendant Terry] Nichols are not being held incommunicado," Matsch said.  <P>



Media groups are expected to appeal the ruling. Last week, ABC, CBS, and NBC filed an amicus brief in support of McVeigh. Matsch refused to give permission to the media organizations' attorney, Floyd Abrams of New York's Cahill Gordon & Reindel, to argue in court. <P>



McVeigh's attorney, Stephen Jones, had wanted to use the interviews to counter what he called the "demonization" of McVeigh by the media. Because McVeigh is a pretrial detainee, federal law requires him to get permission from the court before giving interviews. <P>



Prosecutors argued against the motion, claiming that it would be tantamount to allowing McVeigh to produce "an infomercial." <P>



Hartzler, a special attorney to the U.S. attorney general, told the court that McVeigh could use the voir dire process to counter pretrial publicity. Nichols also opposed the motion.  <P>



Arguing in support of his motion, Jones lashed out at some of the victims organizations that have been very public in their criticism of McVeigh. In widely disseminated comments, victims and family members have told reporters outside the courthouse that they want to "claw his eyes out" or kill him themselves. <P>



"There is an organized public effort to use every vehicle in the media to convict my client before a jury has been empanelled," Jones said. He also told Matsch that he wished the protective order could be extended to victims and their associations. <P>



Outside the courtroom, victims and their family members hailed the judge's ruling and sharply criticized Jones. <P>



"I know who blew up the building and it was not me, it was not the survivors association, and it was not the families," said Paul Heath, president of the OK City Murrah Building Survivors Association. "If you participate in a crime, you give up the opportunity to participate in a media circus." <P>



<I>Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>

