<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<H2>Bomb Defendants Want Separate Trials Severance Payoff</H2><P><P>

By Robert Schmidt <BR>
<I>Legal Times</I><BR>
September 30, 1996<P>

With the start of the Oklahoma City bombing trial still months away, prosecutors are facing their most serious challenge to date as they try to fend off the defendants' push for separate trials. <P>

Defense lawyers -- apparently sensing that severance may be their best chance to win acquittals for accused bombers Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols -- are treating the motions like the capstone of their cases. <P>

Nichols is fighting the hardest for a separate trial. The 41-year-old Kansan wasn't in Oklahoma City the day of the blast, and his lawyers are concerned that he could be tarred by the greater notoriety of his co-defendant. <P>

McVeigh, for his part, is worried that nine hours of statements Nichols made to the FBI could unfairly prejudice the jury against McVeigh, even though they are inadmissible against him. <P>

Because of these divergent interests, and because each man's life is at stake, animosity has erupted between the two former Army buddies. <P>

RULING NOT PREDICTABLE <BR>
Chief U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch is not taking the issue lightly either. He has scheduled oral arguments on the severance issue starting Oct. 2 and will rule sometime after that.  <P>

In making this potentially pivotal decision, Matsch does not have to fully grant or deny the severance motions. Some courtroom observers say Matsch might solve the trickiest problem -- Nichols' statements to the FBI--by empaneling two juries to hear the case, one of which would step out during that part of the testimony. Another possible scenario: Matsch could order separate penalty phases for the defendants if they are convicted. The judge could sever any time during a joint trial as well. <P>

The filing of severance motions by defense lawyers -- and their subsequent denial -- has become almost perfunctory in multidefendant criminal trials. Attorneys often believe that a separate trial makes it easier for any given defendant to blame, and distance himself from, the others. <P>

But the bombing case is not an ordinary prosecution, and experts say Matsch's decision could go either way.  <P>

"There is a 50-50 chance that the judge may say, 'We're going to have separate trials,' " says former Colorado state court judge Frank Jamison. "This will be the most significant decision in all the pretrial motions." <P>

The defense lawyers are certainly treating it as such. In early September, McVeigh's lead attorney, Stephen Jones, and Nichols' counsel, Michael Tigar, each filed 100-plus-page motions arguing for severance. (Significant parts of the briefs were filed under seal, per the court's order not to disclose sensitive discovery material.) <P>

"It is the only way to get a fair trial," Jones said in an interview. "As a practical matter, if there is no severance there is a substantial likelihood of Mr. McVeigh's conviction." <P>

Some criminal procedure scholars say Jones is not overstating his case. "The single most important thing a defendant can do in a conspiracy case is get severance," says Ira Robbins, a professor at American University's Washington College of Law. <P>

But McVeigh and Nichols have an uphill battle to win separate trials. <P>

The U.S. Supreme Court and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 10th Circuit, which includes Denver, prefer that defendants charged with the same crime be tried together, since that route is more efficient and prevents the problem of inconsistent verdicts. <P>

Experts agree that under the relevant case law, district courts grant severance only when there is a "serious risk" that a joint trial will compromise the rights of one of the defendants or will prevent the jury from making a reliable decision about guilt or innocence. <P>

But a number of criminal procedure experts say that the facts in the bombing case may satisfy the criteria set forth for severance, and that a joint trial for McVeigh and Nichols would be rife with constitutional pitfalls. <P>

For instance, Nichols' statements to the FBI, which have been ruled as inadmissible against McVeigh, contain 67 mentions of McVeigh and will likely be highly prejudicial. Some of that will probably seep into the court record, but McVeigh's attorneys cannot cross-examine Nichols (except in the unlikely event that Nichols testifies). This could compromise McVeigh's Sixth Amendment right to cross-examination, as well as his Fifth Amendment right to due process. <P>

FINGER-POINTING STRATEGIES<BR>
Another potential problem is that the defense strategies pit the accused against each other -- each defendant will likely try to blame the other and in effect become a second prosecutor against his co-defendant. This could be especially damaging should the trial reach a capital sentencing phase, where less culpability in the crime becomes a factor that mitigates against death.  <P>

"Indeed, the prosecution could simply take a seat during this aspect of the case, as the emperors of Rome did in ancient times, and let the gladiators slay each other," the McVeigh defense team argues in its severance brief. <P>

As a result, severance is shaping up to be the most disputed aspect so far in the case, not only pitting the prosecutors against the defense, but also bringing to the surface bitter differences between the two defendants and former Army buddies. <P>

While some of the rhetoric being bandied about is no doubt meant to convince the judge that McVeigh and Nichols have antagonistic defenses and thus a factor for severance, it is apparent that the interests of the two defendants have in fact diverged. In their severance briefs, they waste no opportunity to blame the other. <P>

"In the present posture of this case, Mr. Nichols stands in serious risk of being found guilty by mass application," argues Tigar. "It would be fully consistent for one jury to conclude that Mr. McVeigh, who is directly linked to the scene of the crime itself and who described his plans and intentions with respect to the bombing to others in detail, is guilty, while another jury found Mr. Nichols -- who the government agrees was not at the scene, and against whom there is no remotely similar evidence of participation or intention -- to be innocent." <P>

McVeigh's attorneys, of course, offer the opposite viewpoint. <P>

"[T]he substantial weight of the evidence of guilt, as reflected in the government's own investigative memoranda, its examination of the physical evidence, and the documents it has gathered is against Terry Nichols, not Timothy McVeigh," Jones contends in a 49-page supplement to his 93-page severance brief. "Accordingly, even if Mr. McVeigh is found guilty along with Mr. Nichols, the evidence will point to a more significant and far greater -- and more blameworthy -- involvement in the crime by Mr. Nichols." <P>

As the defendants point to each other, prosecutors are adamantly opposing separate trials. <P>

Led by Special Attorney to the U.S. Attorney General Joseph Hartzler, the prosecution argues that co-conspirators should be tried together and that any prejudice from a joint trial could be cured through careful instructions to the jury. Further, prosecutors say, two trials would overburden judicial resources and the hundreds of witness involved. <P>

"[A] second trial would repeat almost the same evidence, through almost the same witnesses, heard in the first trial," prosecutors argued in a 77-page brief filed Sept. 25. "This overlap of proof greatly reduces any risk of 'spillover' prejudice and suggests that defendants' respective litigation strategies are unlikely to be as antagonistic as they would have the court believe." <P>

The prosecution is also loath to give up the significant courtroom advantage it can gain by painting McVeigh and Nichols with the same broad brush of guilt. This is especially true in a case like the Oklahoma City bombing where the defendants are charged with a conspiracy, because the jury can use the actions and words of one defendant to consider the guilt of the other. <P>

"If [the prosecution] can keep the two of them together, then they have a much stronger case," says Jamison, the former Colorado state judge, who is now a professor at University of Denver College of Law. "They've got a much better case against McVeigh, and if some of that can be lapped over to Nichols -- that's why they want to try it together." <P>

The prosecution can take some comfort in the fact that federal judges grant separate trials only in the rarest of circumstances. <P>

"Judges do not want to try the same case twice," says George Washington University Law School professor Stephen Saltzburg, a former deputy assistant attorney general in the Justice Department's Criminal Division. "They don't want to use scarce judicial resources to do the same thing over again, nor do they want to burden witnesses more than necessary." <P>

Underscoring that point, one federal judge -- U.S. District Judge William Terrell Hodges of the Middle District of Florida -- admonished a class of new federal judges in Washington earlier this year to "never sever" before trial. <P>

Matsch, however, is not one to favor efficiency or tradition over a defendant's constitutional rights, say courtroom observers, pointing to his controversial decision to move the trial to Denver. <P>

"I'm absolutely confident that if any judge would grant a severance in a case like this if the law demanded it, then Matsch is the one," says criminal defense lawyer Henry Asbill, a partner in D.C.'s Asbill, Junkin & Moffitt. "Matsch is as independent a judge as I've run across." <P>

Another factor that could be weighing on Matsch's mind is the appeals court. In a high-profile death penalty case that promises to feature hundreds of witnesses and complex jury instructions, there is a strong possibility for reversible error  throughout the trial, say criminal law experts. So why ask for trouble during the pretrial stages? <P>

"Simply denying the motion to sever immediately raises an appellate issue before the trial has even started," says American University's Robbins. "District judges do have a lot of leeway [on severance], but they also have to respect the Bill of Rights and provide a trial with due process." <P>

<I>Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
Copyright  1996 American Lawyer Media </I><P>

