<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV News</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<h2>McVeigh's Media Bid Tests Inmate Rights</h2>
<P>Robert Schmidt <br><i>
Legal Times<br></i>
Sept. 9, 1996</p>


<P>Over the last several months, accused Oklahoma City bomber
Timothy McVeigh has held off-the-record interviews with some of
the luminaries in the national press corps. But in a move that
turns the tables on such well-known reporters as Barbara
Walters, Tom Brokaw, and Diane Sawyer, McVeigh has also been
asking the questions--auditioning media heavyweights for the
chance to interview him. </P>

<P>The result of this beauty contest, if McVeigh and his attorney
Stephen Jones have their way, would be a series of interviews
with hand-picked reporters that would serve to soften the image
of McVeigh, whom many Americans believe is a right-wing zealot
guilty of the most heinous act of domestic terrorism in U.S.
history. </P>

<P>In a 21-page brief filed late last month, Jones asked Chief
Judge Richard Matsch, who is presiding over the case in U.S.
District Court in Denver, to grant his incarcerated client
permission to proceed with his media strategy--and argued that
refusal to do so would infringe on McVeigh's constitutional
rights. </P>

<P>"There is not in the United States of America in the year 1996
one First Amendment for the Department of Justice, the
survivors, and the media, and another for Timothy McVeigh,"
Jones wrote. "McVeigh's limited, restrained responses in the
requested interviews would not even begin to bring the scales
into balance." </P>

<P>The brief provides an unusual look at a carefully crafted public
relations campaign designed to paint a new picture of a high-
profile, much vilified client. But the filing is not just a
media strategy. It also raises provocative legal questions about
jailed defendants, the First Amendment rights of pretrial
detainees, and the role of the press in the trial process. </P>



<P>These issues are not exclusive to the Oklahoma City case. In the
last few months, about a half-dozen states have enacted, or are
considering, restrictions on some face-to-face prisoner
interviews. The Justice Department issued regulations that would
silence federal prisoners who pose a terrorism threat. And the
judge in the O.J. Simpson civil trial issued an unusually strict
gag order on all participants. </P>



<P>"A lot of people in the legal establishment are raising doubts
and uncertainties about the sweep of the First Amendment, which
we've always accepted, in the trial area," says William Pizzi, a
professor at University of Colorado School of Law. </P>

<P>The practice of trying the case in the media "is not the way
trials should be conducted: They should be litigated and
[participants] questioned from the witness stand, under oath,"
adds Pizzi, who expresses reservations about McVeigh's motion,
but thinks it is legally sound and should be granted. </P>

MATSCH LIMITING PUBLICITY <BR>

<P>Publicity has always been a major issue in the Oklahoma City
case, and Judge Matsch has taken steps to reduce its effect. </P>

<P>In February, the proceedings were moved to Denver from
Oklahoma--in a bid to find a jury pool less affected by the
bombing and the media swirl surrounding it. And in June, the
judge ordered attorneys, supervising officials, and support
personnel involved in the case to restrict their statements,
explicitly prohibiting public discussion of discovery material
and voicing opinions about the defendants' guilt or innocence. </P>

<P>McVeigh has already granted four limited interviews to print
media, and has allowed CBS and NBC to film him talking with
Jones. The strict rules followed by the two networks included no
questions and no shots of McVeigh's handcuffs. While there was
little reaction to his previous interviews, Jones' motion to
increase his client's media exposure has provoked an outcry. </P>

<P>On Aug. 29, the prosecution filed an objection to McVeigh's
request, calling it "an extraordinary attempt to manipulate the
news media to produce a favorable impact on the potential jury
pool." </P>

<P>Terry Nichols, McVeigh's co-defendant, also filed comments
claiming that the interviews could infringe on his rights to a
fair trial. Nichols threatened to hold his own media blitz if
the request is granted. </P>

<P>So far, media representatives have not voiced their views on the
issue. </P>

<P>Matsch is expected to rule on the matter in the next few weeks
because it is time-sensitive. In his motion, Jones asked
permission for a BBC camera crew to film in the prison during
the week of Oct. 7, and for an unspecified major American TV
network crew to come sometime during the month of October. </P>

<P>The American network televised interview, which will likely be
22 minutes long and run during the November sweeps period, is
the centerpiece of Jones' strategy. </P>

<P>In his motion, Jones wrote that McVeigh would choose among
Walters of ABC, Sawyer of ABC, NBC's Brokaw, Dan Rather of CBS,
Susan Candiotti of CNN, and Jack Bowen of Fox Television for the
interview. (Jones is also asking permission for shorter
interviews with a national newspaper, a wire service, and local
television and print media in Denver and the Southwest.) </P>

<P>Jones contends that the interviews are necessary to counter a
"juggernaut of guilt" perpetuated against McVeigh that Jones
says has hampered efforts to hire expert witnesses and find
witnesses willing to testify on behalf of his client--making it
impossible for him to receive a fair trial. </P>

<P>(The request was first filed by Jones ex parte and under seal,
but when the judge ordered him to demonstrate why opposing
counsel could not see the brief, it was withdrawn. Jones then
filed a public request late last month.) </P>

'UNUSUAL' DEFENSE STRATEGY <BR>


<P>Jones' strategy is also noteworthy because it turns general
wisdom about trial strategy upside down. Since anything
defendants say publicly can be used to cross-examine witnesses
in court, defense attorneys almost never advise their clients to
speak with reporters until the trial is over. </P>

<P>"I discourage clients from giving interviews during the pendency
of the case, particularly when the case is going to be
litigated," says noted defense lawyer Plato Cacheris of D.C.'s
Cacheris & Treanor, whose high-profile clients have included CIA
spy Aldrich Ames (who spoke with the press after pleading guilty
to espionage charges) and Fawn Hall, Oliver North's former
secretary during the Iran-Contra affair. "Not being critical of
Mr. Jones, it is an unusual step." </P>

<P>Indeed, Jones' request is so unusual that there is precious
little case law on the subject in the federal courts. </P>

<P>Statutes and case law provide guidelines on an attorney's right
to speak to the press, the right of the press to seek interviews
in prisons, and authorities' power to restrict a prisoner's
direct access to the press. </P>

<P>But McVeigh's case presents the issue of the right of a prisoner
who has not been convicted to get his story out. The novel
defense strategy has First Amendment and media law specialists
sharply divided in their opinions of the request. </P>



<P>"I think it is absolutely an absurd motion--it takes my breath
away," says Jerome Barron, an expert in media law at George
Washington University Law School. "The whole idea is that we
want to try the accused with all the protections of the
Constitution, but that [does not include] an effort toward
further manipulation of the media." </P>



<P>However, David Cole, a professor at Georgetown University Law
Center who specializes in the First Amendment, says the judge
should grant the motion. </P>



<P>"The law gives the courts a fair amount of discretion in
attempting to balance fair trial rights versus free press
rights," says Cole. "But I think you have to have a very strong
concern for tainting a trial before you cut off the defendant's
ability to speak to the press." (Cole writes a monthly column
for Legal Times.) </P>

<P>Matsch does have a lot of latitude to deny McVeigh's motion, say
several criminal procedure experts. Matsch could determine that
the interviews would unfairly prejudice the prosecution's case
or would make jury selection too difficult. </P>

<P>"I understand why a court would want to restrict it, but
[McVeigh] has strong arguments," says University of Colorado's
Pizzi. </P>

<P>The strongest of those, experts say, is the First Amendment
right to freedom of speech. </P>

<P>"First Amendment rights do not stop at the jailhouse door," says
Cole. "You can imagine many totalitarian governments which take
people into custody and hold them incommunicado. . . . That's
not consistent with our notion of a free and open government." </P>

NEW RULES GAG PRISONERS <BR>


<P>Yet even in the United States, the pendulum has been swinging
against the free speech rights of inmates. </P>

<P>In fact, the Justice Department can stop McVeigh on its own if
it wishes. The department quietly issued new Bureau of Prisons
regulations this past May that were created to silence inmates
who may incite, promote, or plot terrorist attacks. Those
regulations are currently in effect on an interim basis. (See
"Silencing Suspected Terrorists Behind Bars," June 10, 1996,
Page 1.) </P>

<P>The rules allow the bureau, after being advised by the attorney
general, to keep an inmate from conducting interviews, using the
phone, and corresponding with reporters by mail. </P>



<P>In June, BOP General Counsel Wallace Cheney said that the
Oklahoma City bombing and the 1993 World Trade Center blast
provided a final impetus for implementation of the new
procedures--though they were not designed with any particular
case in mind. </P>



<P>Justice has not invoked the regulations in the Oklahoma City
case. </P>



<P>The issue of media access to prisoners has also been percolating
through a number of states in the last few months, including
South Carolina, California, Illinois, and Indiana. The trend in
the states, say advocates for prisoners and the press, has been
to limit severely or to ban face-to-face interviews with some
inmates, such as those on death row. While the advocates decry
such bans, they say a legal challenge to them would probably
prove futile. </P>

<P>"We would like to think that the courts will be independent
arbiters and protectors of the Constitution," says Jane Kirtley,
who is the executive director of the Arlington, Va.-based
Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press. "But the track
record, from the Supreme Court on down, has been to show great
deference to prison authorities." </P>

<P>The rules in the state courts were spurred mainly by concerns
that inmates were becoming media stars. That is not the case
with McVeigh. Jones stresses in his brief that the interviews
are important because McVeigh has become a television demon, not
a star. </P>

<P>"Timothy McVeigh has the right to appear in court as an accused
defendant in something other than sackcloth and ashes," Jones
argues. </P>

<P><i>Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<br>
Copyright 1996, American Lawyer Media</i></P>
