<H2>Low Key, High Pressure</H2>







By Robert Schmidt<BR>

<I>Legal Times </I><BR>

September 2, 1996



<P>Of all the thousands of veteran federal prosecutors in the nation,

Joseph Hartzler, an assistant U.S. attorney in Springfield, Ill.,

seems one of the least likely to have been placed in charge of the

massive Oklahoma City bombing case.</P>



<P>As head of the government's trial team, Hartzler faces the challenge

of managing one of the largest and most complicated federal

prosecutions ever staged, complete with untested statutes, more than

21,000 witness statements, and 4,000 pieces of physical evidence.</P>



<P>He also has to contend with two star defense attorneys, Stephen Jones

and Michael Tigar, who are pursuing a scorched-earth litigation

strategy that tries to poke holes in even the most minute aspects of

the government's case.</P>



<P>Although he once was a hotshot prosecutor in Chicago, Hartzler has not

tried many complex cases in the past few years. He has no ties with

Oklahoma City, where 168 people were killed in the bombing last year,

or with Denver, where the trial will be held. He is not especially

well-connected at Main Justice. And in 1991, having been diagnosed

with multiple sclerosis, Hartzler left a demanding law-firm

partnership in Chicago and took the prosecutor job in Springfield.</P>



<P>Yet, as the case winds its way through pretrial hearings in U.S.

District Court in Denver, Hartzler has held his own against the

onslaught of motions from the defense, and according to courtroom

observers and his supervisors in Washington, he has molded a diverse

group of 10 lawyers into a top-notch legal team.</P>



<P>Last month, the prosecution won an important victory when Chief Judge

Richard Matsch denied defense lawyers' attempts to suppress key

evidence against their clients, accused bombers Timothy McVeigh and

Terry Nichols. Beginning this month, Hartzler faces an even greater

challenge as Tigar and Jones argue for separate trials.</P>



MAN OF MYSTERY <BR>

<P>In leading the government's charge, though, Hartzler

remains a bit of an enigma.</P>



<P>Through an important series of pretrial hearings, he has not gone head

to head against Jones and Tigar, choosing instead to let his deputies

take the lead in court. Hartzler has also shied away from the

intensive media attention, generally refusing to grant interviews and

rarely stopping outside the courthouse to make statements for the

expectant press pool.</P>



<P>"I don't understand where they found him or why they chose him," says

Michael Deutsch, who as an attorney in Chicago defended a Puerto Rican

terrorist in a 1985 bombing case prosecuted by Hartzler, a successful

prosecution that is often cited as one of the reasons Hartzler got the

Oklahoma City job.</P>



<P>In fact, the selection of the low-profile Hartzler may be part of the

government's strategy in the bombing case.</P>



<P>Some attorneys who follow the bombing case speculate that the

government may have preferred an unobtrusive lead lawyer who would

toil in the background, letting his superiors in Washington call the

shots. After all, the bombing has become an important political symbol

that has been used to promote issues as diverse as the war on domestic

terrorism, victims' rights, and gun control.</P>



<P>Another theory -- so delicate that none of the three lawyers who

suggested it wish to be quoted on the record -- is that Hartzler's MS

helped land him the appointment. Having a lead prosecutor who

maneuvers around the courtroom in a motorized scooter, some say, is a

good tactic for gaining sympathy with a jury -- especially in a case

where more than 500 people were injured.  (Justice Department

officials say Hartzler's disability played no role in his selection.)</P>



<P>According to friends, Hartzler, 45, was more than willing to endure

the physical discomfort and long hours necessary to try the case,

because he felt so strongly about bringing the bombers to justice. In

fact, Hartzler went out of his way to volunteer his services after

hearing on his car radio about the carnage in Oklahoma City.</P>



<P>"I thought I had some skills that I could contribute," says Hartzler.</P>



<P>And his supporters caution against underestimating the unassuming

Midwesterner.</P>



<P>Justice Department officials who hired Hartzler are quick to praise

him as a sharp trial lawyer with a quick mind who stays calm in the

face of intense pressure.</P>



<P>And defense lawyers who have faced Hartzler in court -- usually losing

-- say he is a very aggressive prosecutor with a healthy ego who has

trouble letting go of a case. They also laud his trial skills, his

fairness, and his ethics.</P>



<P>"Joe is the consummate professional prosecutor," says Springfield,

Ill., attorney Michael Metnick. "In the courtroom, he's very

methodical and forceful, not flashy, although he certainly can be

emotional."</P>



<P>Hartzler's biggest test so far in the bombing case will come in the

next few weeks as the defendants prepare to argue for separate trials.

Should their severance motions be granted, the prosecution's already

daunting task will become much harder.</P>



WHO'S IN CHARGE?<BR>

<P>The pressure on Hartzler to win is, of course,

enormous. A loss would be a devastating blow to federal law

enforcement. His marching orders were set before he took the job in

May 1995: Both President Bill Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno

told a national television audience that the bombers, if convicted,

would face the death penalty.</P>



<P>Accordingly, each decision Hartzler makes is being scrutinized by the

public, the press, and his superiors in Washington. His decision to

remain mostly silent in court so far has provoked speculation that he

may not be directing the case.</P>



<P>Aside from introducing his legal team to the court at the beginning of

each session, Hartzler has generally remained mum during important

pretrial hearings on defense motions to change venue, rule out the

death penalty, and suppress evidence.</P>



<P>"I don't think that Joe is in charge of the prosecution team. The

shots are called by [Deputy Attorney General] Jamie Gorelick and [her

top aide] Merrick Garland," claims defense counsel Stephen Jones.

"This case's backdrop is clearly presidential politics, so Clinton can

say he's tough on crime."</P>



<P>Justice Department officials scoff at such a notion, pointing out that

they are too far away and too busy to micro-manage the trial team.

Hartzler, they say, is firmly in charge.</P>



<P>Hartzler's low profile in court has also formed a marked contrast with

the image projected by defense attorneys Jones and Tigar. Both are

larger-than-life figures prone to using sweeping rhetoric in the

courtroom, and they have delegated little to the other lawyers on

their legal teams.</P>



<P>Indeed, it is quite unusual for a lead prosecutor -- especially in

such an important case -- to stay so far out of the spotlight.</P>



<P>But according to Hartzler, that has been the plan. Each of his

deputies handles a different area of the case, and when something that

pertains to their specialty comes up, they take charge in court.</P>



<P>"Our team will be a lot different than the defense. Ours is much, much

more of a team effort," says Hartzler.</P>



<P>Although Hartzler may not be as flamboyant as Jones and Tigar, lawyers

who have worked with him say he can more than hold his own against

them.</P>



<P>"He's clearly a formidable foe for the defense lawyers in this case,"

says his former boss, Dan Webb, who was U.S. attorney in Chicago when

Hartzler worked in the office.</P>



<P>Hartzler will not remain close-mouthed in court for long -- he is

slated to be a main voice in court once the case goes to trial,

probably early next year -- but his willingness to let others share

the glory helps explain his management style and his approach to the

prosecution of two of the most notorious defendants in history.</P>



<P>Moreover, the prosecution doesn't believe it needs a celebrity lawyer

or courtroom theatrics in a case that centers around the mass murder

of 168 people, 19 of them children.</P>



<P>"My style is to recognize the strengths in others," says Hartzler.

"You'll see no grandstanding by any of us."</P>



<P>Hartzler's wide smile, clean-cut looks, and evenhanded demeanor should

play well to the jury. Lawyers who have worked with him in court say

jurors often see Hartzler in the same way they do Peter Jennings or

Tom Brokaw -- as an impartial presenter of facts.</P>



<P>"He's not overly theatric or flamboyant, and that gains him a lot of

credibility," says Vincent Connelly, a partner at Chicago's Mayer,

Brown & Platt, who worked with Hartzler in the Chicago U.S. attorney's

office. "Although he's an advocate in many respects, he comes across

as a newscaster."</P>



<P>Defense attorneys, however, say Hartzler is not always Mr. Nice Guy in

the courtroom -- especially when he ends up on the losing side of a

case.</P>



<P>"Mr. Hartzler was a very aggressive prosecutor," says Chicago defense

lawyer Philip Parenti, who faced Hartzler in 1986. Parenti's client,

an alcoholic attorney charged with swindling some of his clients, got

off without jail time.</P>



<P>"He was very vocal in his disagreement with the federal judge's

decision, and several months later, he found a way to try to revoke

[the client's] probation, but the judge would have none of it," says

Parenti.</P>



<P>Hartzler's aggressiveness, however, is rarely apparent outside the

courtroom. In person he comes across as an all-American boy, a

straight-shooter.</P>



HOMETOWN HERO<BR>

<P>Hartzler even has some credentials to back up his image:

In 1987, before he developed MS, he was named a "hero" by the city of

Chicago for chasing after and helping to subdue a pickpocket on the

elevated train. Hartzler, who is 5 feet, 9 inches tall, put the much

larger man in a headlock on the subway platform.</P>



<P>Born and raised in Ohio, Hartzler attended Amherst College and

American University's Washington College of Law (graduating first in

his class in 1978), but returned to the Midwest to settle down.</P>



<P>Hartzler met his wife, because the alphabet fatefully put them next to

each other in law school; they now have three sons, age 11, nine, and

five.</P>



<P>Shortly before being appointed lead prosecutor in the bombing case,

Hartzler was honored as the 1995 MS Father of the Year by the National

Multiple Sclerosis Society. President Clinton presented the award to

Hartzler as his family looked on.</P>



<P>The society noted Hartzler's devotion to his sons and in a news

release talked of the children's favorite father-son activities,

including playing "Monster," "wrestling buddies," "basement ball," and

listening to a bedtime story series invented by Hartzler called "Magic

Yellow Sweatshirt." The group also noted that Hartzler coached youth

baseball and named his team the Mighty Skunks, a twist on the initials

MS.</P>



<P>Hartzler is not shy about acknowledging his illness, a degenerative

neurological disorder. But he prefers to dwell on other aspects of his

life.</P>



<P>Hartzler says his three boys are his main focus. He left a partnership

at Chicago's Rudnick & Wolfe after only two years and moved to

Springfield because an hour-long commute from the suburbs would take

away too much time from his family life, he says.</P>



<P>"If I stayed in Chicago, I probably could not have ever coached Little

League again in my life -- and that was just not acceptable," says

Hartzler.</P>



<P>Working in the U.S. attorney's office in Springfield, Hartzler has a

12-minute commute if he hits all the lights. Coaching Little League,

however, is on hold until the bombing trial is over.</P>



<P>Hartzler is also a small-stakes poker player and has hosted a social

game in Springfield frequented mainly by other lawyers. Before he

developed MS, Hartzler was a tennis player, and he says, poker has

become a new way to get together with his male friends.</P>



<P>Even the years he spent living in the city didn't rob him of his

boy-next-door demeanor, according to those who know him in

Springfield.</P>



<P>"For somebody coming from Chicago, he is pretty down to earth," says

Brian Otwell, chief public defender for Sangamon County, Ill. "He

isn't above having a few beers."</P>



<P>Hartzler's laid-back style, according to Justice Department officials,

was one of the reasons he was selected to head the bombing prosecution

team. His long career as a prosecutor and the legal challenges he

faced also played a big role.</P>



<P>In particular, Justice sought candidates who could deal with

complicated factual matters, wide-ranging forensic evidence, and

complex records, including phone records. Officials also wanted a

prosecutor who had experience with terrorism or bombing cases, could

work closely with investigators, and had managed and supervised a

large trial team.</P>



<P>Hartzler fit the bill. Before moving to Springfield, Hartzler spent 10

years in the Chicago U.S. attorney's office, heading both the Civil

and Criminal divisions. During that time he prosecuted a case against

Puerto Rican nationalists who were making bombs to blow up a number of

buildings in Chicago.</P>



<P>"Joe is an outstanding trial lawyer. His mind works very quickly,"

says former U.S. attorney Webb, who was Hartzler's supervisor from

1981 to 1985. "He's known as tough but fair-minded."</P>



<P>Webb, now a partner at Chicago's Winston & Strawn, says Hartzler

usually handled the bigger prosecutions in the office, including major

fraud, political corruption, and judicial bribery trials, and was

acclaimed for his extraordinarily thorough case preparation.</P>



<P>Another area where Hartzler excelled, says Webb, was in his dealings

with investigators, a skill that should help him in the Oklahoma City

case.</P>



<P>"Joe always got along well with the FBI," says Webb. "Sometimes

prosecutors get their nose up in the air and believe they're better

than investigative officers, but Joe's attitude was to roll up his

sleeves and work with [them]."</P>



<P>In fact, one of the reasons Hartzler says he has remained a prosecutor

is because he enjoys the investigations so much.</P>



<P>"Defense lawyers have to be much more reactive," says Hartzler. "As a

prosecutor, [you have] a search and discover mission."</P>



<P>One case where Hartzler coordinated the investigation with the FBI and

numerous other law enforcement agencies was his 1985 prosecution of

four members of the Puerto Rican nationalist group known as the FALN.

The group, which believes in independence for Puerto Rico and

socialism for America, claimed responsibility for more than 100

bombings or planned bombings in New York and Chicago.</P>



<P>In Hartzler's case, the four defendants were charged with plotting to

bomb a Marine Corps Reserve training center and an Army Reserve center

in Chicago. They were also charged with maintaining safe houses for

storing weapons and explosives, and planning a robbery of a Chicago

Transit Authority money collector to support their activities.</P>



<P>Although Oklahoma City is a larger and more complex case, the FALN

trial had a number of similarities, says former Assistant U.S.

Attorney James Ferguson, a partner at Chicago's Sonnenschein Nath &

Rosenthal, who tried the case with Hartzler.</P>



<P>Like Oklahoma City, the FALN case had an enormous amount of evidence,

it involved terrorism statutes rarely used, and had political

undertones. A lot of pressure was put on the prosecutors; the U.S.

attorney's office received death threats during the investigation.</P>



<P>Yet there were also some big differences between the two cases. Unlike

Oklahoma City where the evidence is mainly circumstantial, the

prosecution in the FALN case had videotapes of three of the defendants

building bombs. If that wasn't enough, those three defendants refused

appointed counsel and would not recognize the court's jurisdiction,

declaring themselves prisoners of war.</P>



<P>While the three defendants without lawyers were sentenced to 35 years

in jail, the one defendant with a counsel got off with probation. His

attorney, Michael Deutsch, says the case was hardly a test for

Hartzler.</P>



<P>"It was a slam dunk," says Deutsch, now legal director for the Center

for Constitutional Rights in New York. "It was not too difficult a

case for the government. Three of the defendants were on a videotape,

sitting at a table making bombs."</P>



<P>Deutsch says he was surprised that when Hartzler was appointed lead

counsel in the Oklahoma City bombing trial, the FALN case was being

cited as his big terrorism case.</P>



<P>"[The FALN trial] didn't put you to the test on how skillful you are,"

says Deutsch. "We stayed away from bomb evidence. There was no tight

cross of expert witnesses."</P>



<P>But Ferguson, the former prosecutor, says Hartzler learned important

lessons during the FALN case, including how to investigate terrorist

organizations and how to choreograph the presentation of evidence.</P>



<P>To show the jury the potential harm the group could inflict, Hartzler

had some of the confiscated bombs set off and videotaped. Hartzler

also created an enormous bulletin board on which he mounted all the

weapons found in the group's safe house.</P>



<P>"It was pretty chilling, and needless to say it really dominated the

courtroom," says Ferguson.</P>



<P>From his perspective, Ferguson says, the government's decision to

bring in Hartzler for the Oklahoma City trials was "inspired."</P>



<P>Justice officials, too, say they are confident they chose the right

lead prosecutor.</P>



<P>"He's shown good judgment in the midst of a media storm," says Merrick

Garland, principal associate deputy attorney general, who is

supervising this case and other major terrorism cases for the

department. "He's got his head down and is getting the case ready for

trial."</P>



<P>Hartzler, meanwhile, is not trying to parlay the case into a lucrative

partnership in a private law firm, nor is he trying to move up the

Justice Department's ranks.</P>



<P>When the trial is over, Hartzler plans to head back to Springfield,

Ill., and resume his work as an assistant U.S. attorney.</P>



<P>"Where else would I go but back to Springfield?" says Hartzler. "I'm

very comfortable with what I do."</P>



<<I>Legal Times</I> is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>

