<H2>DOJ deploys Its Own 'Dream Team'</H2><p>





By Robert Schmidt<BR>

<I>Legal Times</I> <BR>

September 2, 1996



<P>The government's trial team in the Oklahoma City case was put together

by lead prosecutor Joseph Hartzler and by senior officials in the

Justice Department.</P>



<P>The six main lawyers, not including Hartzler, cover all the bases: Two

are from Oklahoma City, one is an appellate expert on loan from Main

Justice, one is based in the Justice Department's Terrorism and

Violent Crime Division, and two are assistant U.S. attorneys known as

fierce litigators.</P>



<P>While Hartzler has not yet taken an active role in court, his deputies

have all made appearances and are spearheading the legal work in

specific areas. Despite facing off against high-profile defense

attorneys Michael Tigar and Stephen Jones, the prosecutors have held

their own, say courtroom observers.</P>



<P>"The government has some pretty good lawyers. It's not a terrible

mismatch," says Oklahoma City defense lawyer John Coyle III, who

provides commentary on the trial for local television news. "What

they've said in court for the most part seems to have been effective."</P>



<P>Rounding out the prosecution team are:</P>



<P>* Sean Connelly, on detail from the Justice Department, where he

handles appellate work in the Criminal Division. Connelly has been the

most public face in court for the prosecution. Thus far, he has taken

the lead on the prosecution's replies to defense challenges to the

death penalty and motions to suppress evidence. He also writes most of

the government's legal briefs.</P>



<P>Connelly, who without notes gave the prosecution's closing argument in

the suppression hearings in July, has argued more than 60 cases in

nearly every federal circuit.  Before joining the Justice Department,

Connelly was in private practice at the D.C. firms of Zuckerman,

Spaeder, Goldstein, Taylor & Kolker and Brand & Lowell.</P>



<P>In court, Connelly sometimes speaks so quickly that the court reporter

asks him to slow down.</P>



<P>* Beth Wilkinson, principal deputy chief of the Criminal Division's

Terrorism and Violent Crime Section. Wilkinson is spearheading the

Prosecution's efforts on discovery and expert witnesses.</P>



<P>Wilkinson began her legal career in the U.S. Army, where  she worked

on the prosecution of Manuel Noriega. In that case, she specialized in

handling issues related to the use of classified information. As an

assistant U.S. attorney in the Eastern District of New York, Wilkinson

successfully prosecuted a terrorist charged with the bombing of an

Avianca Airlines plane.</P>



<P>* Patrick Ryan, the U.S. attorney in Oklahoma City, who joined the

team shortly after he was appointed by President Clinton in the weeks

following the bombing. Ryan has done a significant amount of work with

the crime victims, including handling motions to ensure that they have

seating in the courtroom. Ryan also worked on venue motions, which

were argued in Oklahoma.</P>



<P>* Vicki Zemp Behenna, an assistant U.S. attorney in Oklahoma City.

Behenna, who argued the Prosecution's closed-circuit television

motion, is the only attorney on the team who has worked on the case

since the investigation began.</P>



<P>* Scott Mendeloff, an assistant U.S. attorney in Chicago. Brought in

by Hartzler, Mendeloff, the deputy chief of the office's Special

Prosecutions Division, has handled more than 35 federal prosecutions.

In the Oklahoma City case, Mendeloff cross-examined several of

defendant Terry Nichols' witnesses during the suppression hearings.

Mendeloff has a reputation for being a no-holds-barred litigator.</P>



<P>* Larry Mackey, chief of the Appellate Division in the U.S. attorney's

office in Indianapolis. Mackey, who had been a runner up for the lead

prosecutor's job, was brought on by Hartzler, who knew him largely by

reputation. Mackey had been the first assistant in the Springfield,

Ill., U.S. attorney's office before Hartzler arrived.</P>



<P>Mackey had the delicate task of cross-examining Nichols' wife, Marife.

He pulled no punches -- hammering at her for lying about her age and

skeptically questioning her version of her dealings with the Federal

Bureau of Investigation.</P>



<P>While Hartzler may be known as a tenacious litigator, he "is Lassie

compared to Mackey," says one Springfield, Ill., defense lawyer.</P>



<I>Legal Times</I> is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>

