<H2>More Power to the Bureau?</H2><p>

By Robert Schmidt <br>
<i>Legal Times</I><br>
August 5, 1996<p>

On April 21, 1995, the Federal Bureau of Investigation, furiously pursuing leads in the Oklahoma City bombing, descended on a small police station in Kansas where Terry Nichols had taken his family. The agents promptly took Nichols to the basement and grilled him for nine hours. <p>

Shortly into the interrogation, the agents presented Nichols with a waiver of his Miranda rights, which he refused to sign. Although the FBI obtained a warrant for his arrest a few hours into the questioning, it was not served until the end of the interview. <p>

Attorneys for accused bomber Nichols are arguing that the FBI, in its zeal to solve the murder of 168 people in Oklahoma, ignored the protections of the Constitution. They are trying to get their client's statements and other evidence thrown out, citing these and other alleged abuses. <p>

Few experts think that Nichols' lawyers, Ronald Woods and Michael Tigar, will succeed. Still, the testimony about police behavior in the Oklahoma City case has troubled many civil libertarians, scholars, and defense lawyers, who warn that if the FBI played it too close to the line in the Oklahoma City probe, this may be merely a taste of things to come. <p>

Particularly now, as the nation confronts what may be a growing problem of domestic terrorism in the wake of the explosion of TWA Flight 800 and the bombing at the Olympics, people who worry about police abuses see troubling warning signs emerging from the Oklahoma City trial. <p>

"When you see a major shift of power from one agency to another, you have to be very careful that it doesn't go to the head of those who obtain it," says Nicholas Kittrie, an expert on terrorism and professor at American University's Washington College of Law. "Any agency that gains that additional power wants to show they are successful, and there is a great danger that they will look for some shortcuts." <p>

Last week, President Bill Clinton and lawmakers met to begin negotiations on an anti-terrorism bill that would grant new, widespread wiretapping authority to the bureau. Other proposals are currently being floated to increase the FBI's budget and the size of its work force. <p>

Even without additional powers and resources, the profile of the FBI has been changing. As both Democrats and Republicans have tried to show they are tough on crime, they have hiked the FBI's budget for hiring agents, some of whom are not up to the bureau's previously high standards, according to some critics. <p>

"A new breed of agent is [working now], and there are a lot less checks and balances," says Nancy Luque, a white collar criminal defense partner at the D.C. office of Reed Smith Shaw & McClay. "There is no bright line these days, and the courts don't do anything to deter bad cops anymore." <p>

Testimony earlier this summer in pretrial hearings on defense motions to suppress evidence in the Oklahoma City case certainly shows that there is no strict guideline for agents to follow in investigating a high-profile, fast-moving case. <p>

And just last week in Atlanta, the bureau was strongly criticized for allegedly leaking the fact that it had begun to consider Richard Jewell, the security guard who found the bomb in Centennial Olympic Park, a prime suspect in the crime. <p>

"In these high-profile cases, where the public is outraged, the FBI as a matter of public relations wants to satisfy the thirsts of the crowd," says Gerald Shargel, a prominent New York criminal defense attorney. <p>

The FBI has plenty of defenders, who say the bureau does -- and can be expected to continue to do -- an excellent job of solving crimes while still safeguarding the rights of citizens. <p>

"I think the FBI is still the world's best investigative agency that operates within the framework of a written constitution," says Joseph diGenova, a former U.S. attorney and a partner in D.C.'s diGenova & Toensing. <p>

At a congressional hearing Aug. 1, FBI Director Louis Freeh said publicity like that about Jewell is an unfortunate consequence of many major investigations. <p>

"We regret many times in these investigations that people's names surface as suspects who are later proven not to be connected," Freeh testified. <p>

The Atlanta probe is only in its earliest stages. But the year-old Nichols matter, which is now pending before Chief U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch in Denver, may become a touchstone for how far the FBI can go to obtain evidence and make its case. <p>

"The FBI cut every corner, broke every rule," claims Ronald Woods, a former U.S. attorney in Houston and former FBI agent who serves as appointed counsel for Nichols. "I think this was just a big case to them. The bigger the case, the looser the rules become." <p>

In addition to his concerns about the nine-hour interrogation of Nichols and the alleged disregard of his Miranda rights, Woods says the FBI's treatment of Nichols' Filipino wife, Marife, was particularly egregious. <p>

WIFE ALLEGES MISTREATMENT <br>
Marife Nichols, who was 21, pregnant, and still nursing their young daughter, was interviewed at the police station in Kansas and then taken by the FBI to a nearby hotel after she was told it wasn't safe to go back home. With her husband in jail, she remained for 37 days under the watchful eye of FBI agents, who took her to eight different cities. During this time, she gave consent for 13 searches of the Nichols' property. <p>

Judge Matsch is expected to rule shortly on the motion by Woods and lead counsel Tigar to suppress the evidence acquired as a result of these and other searches. <p>

Maureen Cain, a Denver solo practitioner who represents Marife Nichols, says she is considering filing suit against the FBI for its treatment of her client. <p>

Tigar and Woods also cite other alleged FBI abuses in their treatment of Terry and Marife Nichols: <p>

*A Filipino resident alien, Marife testified that she was never told by the FBI that she had the right to speak with a lawyer, and also testified that she didn't understand she could refuse consent for the searches. <p>

*The FBI seized $5,000 in cash, nine gold coins, and three silver coins that belonged to Marife. She repeatedly asked for the money back but was told it was being tested to see if bombing defendant Timothy McVeigh's fingerprints were on any of the bills. Shortly after Marife spoke with her husband's attorneys, the FBI returned $4,800 of her money. <p>

*Five days after Terry Nichols was arrested, the FBI told his wife that they would arrange for her to telephone him. An agent asked Marife if they could tape the call, and Marife testified that she felt the taping was a condition of making the call. <p>

*Agents were not wholly truthful with Terry Nichols before he was arrested. When he asked why his name was on television and radio, Special Agent Stephen Smith told Nichols that he didn't know. Smith also agreed to give Terry a copy of any notes the agents made during their interview. During the pretrial suppression hearings, Smith testified that he was not planning to hand over the notes but that he hadn't lied because he knew Nichols could get them during discovery. <p>

*Terry Nichols was told three times he was "free to leave" the police station. But, shortly after he came in for questioning, the FBI secured his home and pickup truck. <p>

Was the bureau conducting a "military-style operation reminiscent of Ruby Ridge and Waco," as Nichols' lawyers say? Or, as federal prosecutors contend in a brief in the Nichols case, was the FBI "acting with remarkable diligence and in a manner that honored the Constitution"? <p>

Both sides are partly right, according to experts in criminal procedure and others who study the FBI. (FBI General Counsel Howard Shapiro declines comment, citing a protective order issued by Judge Matsch.) <p>

"The FBI probably should not have come this close to jeopardizing their case," says Paul Rothstein, a professor at Georgetown University Law Center and an expert on criminal procedure. "But I think legally they are just within the bounds of the law." <p>

Adds James X. Dempsey, who handled FBI oversight for 10 years as a House Judiciary Committee staffer and is now deputy director of the Center for National Security Studies: "The FBI, maybe more than any other agency, understands the power of the concepts of consent and waiver, and they work very hard to keep people away from lawyers, but they do it within parameters that have been upheld by the courts." <p>

EXCEPTIONS EXPLOITED <br>
These parameters have been set in the last 25 years by the Supreme Court under conservative Chief Justices Warren Burger and William Rehnquist. <p>

While courts have always been loath to suppress evidence, the Supreme Court in recent years has generally limited the scope of the protections against coercive interrogations and illegal searches granted defendants during the tenure of Chief Justice Earl Warren. <p>

Although the Court has kept in place the essence of the landmark Warren-era decisions, such as suspects' rights to counsel and to remain silent, it has created a number of exceptions to the rules. <p>

In response, the FBI has shown that it is not only willing to take advantage of these exceptions, it trains agents to exploit them. That training seemed to be on display in the Oklahoma City bombing probe. <p>

"Search and seizure law has changed dramatically in the last 15 years," says diGenova, the former U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia. "[Agents] receive regular training on what the law is, they know how far they can go, and we expect them to know what those limits are." <p>

The limits, however, are not always clearly defined. <p>

"Courts usually don't give [law enforcement officers] advisory opinions--they tell them whether it will fly or not," says E. Lawrence Barcella Jr., a former prosecutor and partner in the D.C. office of Los Angeles' Paul, Hastings, Janofsky & Walker. <p>

Barcella says in a case he was arguing, a judge once explained it this way: "In suppression cases, we treat our police the way we train dogs," the judge said. "We don't tell them how to do it right. We wait until they do it wrong and then hit them on nose with a rolled-up newspaper." <p>

The FBI's defenders point out that the bureau must be doing a good job since the evidence it gathers is rarely suppressed. And if controversial investigatory tactics have been upheld by the courts, FBI agents shouldn't come under fire for using them. <p>

For example, says journalist and longtime FBI observer Ronald Kessler, courts have said it is permissible for agents to lie in the course of interrogating a person in order to get them to confess. So the FBI follows that guideline. <p>

"They are aggressive, and they do go as far as they can go legally. It's an agency that is very conscious of obeying the law," says Kessler, author of The FBI: Inside the World's Most Powerful Law Enforcement Agency. "I think they've really done a superb job of catching criminals and staying within the law and the Constitution." <p>

As a practical matter, the law seems to bend a little when law enforcement officers are hurriedly investigating a major crime. Domestic terrorism--like the Oklahoma City bombing, where 168 people were killed and more than 500 injured--is an area where courts are more willing to give the benefit of the doubt to police. <p>

For instance, the FBI agents on the scene in Kansas were worried that Terry Nichols may have been planning another bombing or that his house was rigged with explosives. Any evaluation of the bureau's treatment of Nichols should be made with the exigent circumstances in mind, say criminal procedure experts. <p>

"It was two days after the bombing, and [agents] were working under incredible pressure," says William Pizzi, who teaches criminal procedure at the University of Colorado School of Law. "This is a very tough world, pressure is brought on suspects, and that is what it's like when you have a very serious crime like this." <p>

However, allowing the FBI or other law enforcement agencies to push defendants a little more than necessary in perilous or fast-moving cases sets a dangerous precedent, say some critics. Once the courts have approved the FBI's behavior, they say, the agency doesn't hesitate to act that way again. <p>

"We shouldn't be trusting anybody with these powers, even if all FBI agents were as upright as Eliot Ness," says Arthur Spitzer, legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union of the National Capital Area. <p>

These expansions of police power flourished in the war on drugs and now can be seen in domestic terrorism cases such as Oklahoma City and Atlanta. <p>

Many law enforcement standards, such as the length of time police wait before breaking a door down or the degree of suspicion they need to search a car, fell by the wayside in drug cases because drugs are so easy to get rid of or hide, explains Barbara Allen Babcock, a professor at Stanford Law School. <p>

"What's really eroding [the Fourth Amendment] is the war on drugs. Put it together with the fear of domestic terrorism, and it really can be a powerful hydraulic force that undermines all of our liberty," says Babcock. <p>

Critics fear that if the court in Denver admits the evidence obtained with Marife Nichols' consent, the FBI may in the future keep another suspect's wife for 37 days or, more generally, take additional bites out of the Fourth Amendment. <p>

"Once some kind of method is upheld, it applies to everybody," says Babcock, who used to head the Public Defender Service in Washington. "Criminal defendants are the representatives of all of us. They are ones whose cases decide the rights that apply to all of us." <p>

(<i>Legal Times</I> is an affiliate of Court TV.)<br>
