<H2>Fine-Tuning TV Coverage</H2>

<P>By Robert Schmidt<BR>
Legal Times<BR>
July 22, 1996</P>

<P>DENVER--In permitting a closed-circuit broadcast of the Oklahoma City bombing trial last week, Chief U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch managed both to satisfy a congressional mandate that the trial be televised and to address defense attorneys' vocal concerns for their clients' right to a fair trial.</P>

<P>Matsch's July 15 bench ruling focused solely on whether it was constitutional for Congress to order the broadcast in the 1996 anti-terrorism law--but left open some tricky issues relating to the logistics of setting up the coverage.</P>

<P>And although the ruling significantly increases the chances that the telecast will occur, a number of pitfalls remain. Matsch will make a final decision on the matter after an upcoming hearing on how to establish the coverage and protect the feed from people who might pirate the signal.</P>

<P>There are a lot of problems . . . about the terms and conditions," Matsch said from the bench. "These problems may be insurmountable."</P>

<P>While Congress ordered Matsch to allow the camera in his courtroom so victims' families could watch the trial in Oklahoma City, lawmakers also allowed him to control the coverage. The judge's comments indicated that he will narrowly interpret the new law and keep a close watch over the broadcast.</P>

<P>The closed-circuit law, signed by President Bill Clinton in April, was tailor-made for the Oklahoma City case. The measure states that if a trial is moved from its original location out of state and more than 350 miles away, "the trial court shall order closed-circuit televising of the proceedings to that location, for viewing by such persons the court determines have a compelling interest in doing so and are otherwise unable to do so by reason of the inconvenience and expenses caused by the change of venue."</P>

<P>Several Colorado attorneys who know Matsch said he has been adamantly opposed to cameras in federal trials. They say his narrow reading of the law was his attempt to make the best of this situation.</P>

<P>"The dignity of the federal courts is something he would never tamper with," says Larry Pozner of Denver's Pozner & Kaplan. "That camera is going to disappear in that courtroom, and if it doesn't disappear, he's going to make it disappear."</P>

<P>Indeed, Matsch went out of his way to respond to concerns about possible interference with the defendants' rights to a fair trial--concerns that were raised vehemently by lawyers Michael Tigar and Stephen Jones in oral argument at last week's hearing.</P>

<P>"Counsel for the accused have presented this possible parade of horribles about what can happen at a trial with television cameras and microphones and directors and zoom lenses and all of those things," Matsch said. "Well, that's not going to happen."</P>

<P>As Matsch envisioned the broadcast, a feed would go exclusively to a courtroom in Oklahoma City, where seating would be limited and judicial officers would watch over the proceedings. In the Denver courtroom, the one camera would be tucked into the wall. Matsch would have a kill switch and said he would not hesitate to use it should a problem crop up. Jurors would be asked during voir dire whether the camera would affect their impartiality.</P>

<P>"I am much relieved at how he plans to do it," says Jones, who represents accused bomber Timothy McVeigh. "If he follows through on what he said he will do, I don't see how the defendants will be prejudiced."</P>

<P>Jones says he is most worried about victims who are "on a juggernaut to convict my client and Mr. Nichols" holding curbside press conferences in Oklahoma during the proceedings. However, Jones says, Judge Matsch may limit those as well.</P>

<P>One victim, during court hearings last month, announced outside of court that she wanted to climb into the well of the courtroom and claw McVeigh's eyes out. Her comments were widely shown on the evening news.</P>

<P>Tigar, who represents defendant Terry Nichols, said he may raise the issue should there be an appeal, but said he would not bother to mandamus the judge over the closed-circuit broadcast.</P>

<P>"We think it is raisable in the event of an appeal," Tigar told reporters after the hearing. "The government won a temporary tactical advantage that could put the whole [case] at risk."</P>

<P>One thing is certain: The broadcast, as described by Matsch, will not be winning any Emmy awards.</P>

<P>"To my mind, that means a fixed focus--a panoramic view, if you will: a view of the well of the court, not the jury, probably, and no movement of the camera, no focusing on speakers, or witnesses, or anybody else," Matsch said.</P>

<P>At his post-hearing press conference, Tigar noted that the judge's description would produce boring television.</P>

<P>"It's a little bit like watching your ant farm, I think," he said.</P>

<P>Despite the likelihood that the coverage will not be stimulating to watch, victims' family members and survivors of the blast hailed the ruling.</P>

<P>"We're delighted that the judge allowed the closed-circuit television, even though there will be a panoramic view with no zoom-in capacity and you won't be able to see the jury," says Paul Heath, president of the OK City Murrah Building Survivors Association, who was at work in the building at the time of the bombing. "Many of the survivors and family members who work and the injured who are still being treated by doctors will have the opportunity to attend the trial."</P>

<P>STOKING VICTIMS<BR>
The impact of the closed-circuit television decision and other legal issues involving crime victims in the Oklahoma City bombing trial is reverberating in Washington and across the country.</P>

<P>National victims' rights groups have been paying attention to the case and are now using it to propel the movement for a constitutional amendment to protect victims' rights.</P>

<P>"We are continually citing this case for why you need a constitutional amendment," says David Beatty, acting director of the National Victim Center in Arlington, Va. "It is a perfect illustration of how victims are not a party to these cases, and how sometimes victims have fewer rights than the average citizen."</P>

<P>A number of Judge Richard Matsch's decisions have infuriated the victims' family members and survivors who have been attending the pretrial hearings.</P>

<P>In particular, the family members were outraged over Matsch's decision to exclude all people from the proceedings who planned to make victim-impact statements during the penalty phase of the trial. In making his decision, Matsch invoked Rule 615 of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, which allows witnesses to be barred from trial proceedings so their testimony is not influenced by other witnesses.</P>

<P>Other rulings that have angered victims include Matsch's decisions not to guarantee them seats in the courtroom and forbidding them from wearing jewelry, including religious objects, that brings back the memories of their dead loved ones.</P>

<P>The judge's decision excluding witnesses wanting to make victim-impact statements may have gone too far, say several legal experts.</P>

<P>"The only thing the victims are going to be testifying about is what the loss of their loved ones means to them, and the danger of shaping testimony is very limited," says William Pizzi, a professor at University of Colorado School of Law who teaches criminal procedure. "I think the ruling was too sweeping, too strong, and it is unfair to the victims."</P>

<P>Peter Goldberger, a criminal defense lawyer in Ardmore, Pa., and an expert on the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, says the rule Matsch relied on to exclude the victims applies only to the guilt-or-innocence phase of trial. The victims would be making their statements in the sentencing phase.</P>

<P>"I'm not saying it's a bad ruling or wrong ruling, but Rule 615 does not apply to sentencing," Goldberger says.</P>

<P>That decision, which was issued from the bench in June at the start of a hearing, took the prosecutors and about 30 family members and survivors who traveled from Oklahoma completely by surprise. It forced the victims to decide during a recess if they wanted to forfeit their seats in the courtroom. More than half the family members decided to watch the proceedings.</P>

<P>Editor's note: The transcript of Judge Matsch's ruling on closed-circuit television is available on Counsel Connect in the Court Systems section of the Library.</P>

<P>BAR BASH<BR>
Apparently Judge Richard Matsch has better things to do than glad-hand lawyers in sunny climes--or maybe he is tired of listening to Terry Nichols' defense lawyer, Michael Tigar.</P>

<P>During a courtroom discussion on scheduling last week, Tigar noted that he would be unavailable the first week in August because he was giving a speech at the American Bar Association meeting in Orlando.</P>

<P>"I don't know if the court intends to be there," Tigar said. "I've been invited to give a talk there, and I intend to do it."</P>

<P>Matsch shot back: "I don't intend to be there, for your talk or any other."</P>

<P>Not missing a beat, Tigar replied: "I wanted to warn you in case you were going there. But it's in Orlando and my daughter voted that I go there, and so therefore there will be two Mickey Mouse events--my talk and then our visit."</P>

<P>ODDS AND ENDS<BR>
* For reporters covering the bombing case, one constant has been press conferences by McVeigh attorney Stephen Jones outside the courthouse during breaks in the pretrial hearings. Nichols' lawyer, Michael Tigar, and lead prosecutor Joseph Hartzler, on the other hand, have merely waved to reporters as they hustled back to their offices. Not only have the two refused to talk, but they have damned Jones for his cozy relationship with reporters and subtly accused him of leaking discovery material. So imagine Jones' surprise during the June and July pretrial hearings, when he was forced to wait in line for a chance to speak in front of the courthouse--behind both Hartzler and Tigar. "Imitation is the sincerest form of flattery," says Jones with a smirk. "I now have to fight my way to the microphones."</P>

<P>* Oklahoma City U.S. Attorney Patrick Ryan, a member of the prosecution team, missed last week's hearing after falling out of a tree and shattering his hip. Ryan, who was helping his father with yard work, underwent surgery this week and is recovering quickly, according to a prosecution spokeswoman.</P>

<P>* Michael Tigar hasn't let his pro bono work slide during the Oklahoma City case. He's representing Maj. Deborah Meeks, an Air Force officer in San Antonio accused of pulling a gun on her housemate. After Meeks refused to plead guilty at a nonjudicial proceeding, a separate charge of engaging in consensual sodomy with the same woman was added by the Air Force. Meeks faces a general court-martial on Aug. 12.</P>

<P><A HREF="mailto:rob.schmidt@counsel.com">Robert Schmidt's e-mail address is rob.schmidt@counsel.com</A>.</P>

<P><I>Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV. Copyright 1996, American Lawyer Media</I></P>

