<h2>Bombing Case Lawyer Redraws Map</h2>
<P>Robert Schmidt <br><i>
Legal Times<br></i>
June 18, 1996</p>

<P>Look in any road atlas, and you'll find that Denver is 609 miles from Oklahoma City. But don't tell that to defense lawyer Michael Tigar, who managed to shave more than 300 miles off that distance in a recent court filing in the Oklahoma City bombing case.</P>

<P>Tigar, who represents defendant Terry Nichols, indulged in some creative math and used some novel legal reasoning to argue that a closed-circuit broadcast should not be permitted in the bombing trial. The defense team representing co-defendant Timothy McVeigh also opposed the coverage.</P>

<P>At issue is a new federal law requiring the U.S. District Court in Denver to provide a television feed of the trial solely for the victims and their families to watch back in Oklahoma City.</P>

<P>Members of the Oklahoma congressional delegation tacked the requirement onto the anti-terrorism law, which was passed in April. In May, the federal prosecution team asked the presiding judge, Richard Matsch, to set up the broadcast. Prosecutors wrote in their brief that the coverage "will simply expand the courtroom to people who would have observed the trial in person had the venue not been changed." Matsch has not yet ruled on the issue.</P>

<P>This potential electronic expansion of the courtroom is hailed by victim advocates, but worries some litigators and constitutional experts, who say it could violate the rights both of defendants and of people who want to watch the trial.</P>

<P>The new law states that the court shall establish the broadcast "in cases where the venue of the trial is changed out of the state in which the case was initially brought; and more than 350 miles from the location in which those proceedings originally would have taken place." But Tigar, a professor at the University of Texas School of Law, claimed in his brief that a literal reading of the law shows that it does not apply to the bombing trial that it was intended to reach.</P>

<P>Building his argument around the words "location" and "venue," Tigar says that the trial was actually moved to the federal district of Colorado and not specifically to Denver. And the distance from Oklahoma City to the Colorado state border is less than 300 miles--which would fall below the 350-mile threshold established in the legislation.</P>

<P>"The venue of the trial has been changed [from Oklahoma City or Lawton, Okla.] out of the state where the case was originally brought and [a certain distance] from the location where those proceedings would originally have taken place," Tigar wrote.</P>

<P>"The new venue is Colorado, a judicial district comprising the entire state. We must therefore ask whether it is more than 350 miles from Oklahoma City (or Lawton) to the Colorado state line." In case that argument doesn't work, Tigar also contended that the closed-circuit requirement was an unconstitutional usurpation of the judiciary's powers and that the prosecutors failed to show that the bombing case met the proper requirements for a broadcast.</P>

<P>Timothy McVeigh's legal team, headed by Enid, Okla., lawyer Stephen Jones, also argued that the broadcast was unconstitutional. In a more conventional brief, the team claims that the closed-circuit law violates the separation of powers doctrine, as well as McVeigh's Sixth Amendment guarantee of a fair trial and his rights to due process and equal protection of the laws.</P>

<P>Most important, McVeigh's attorneys note, Congress went too far when it imposed this requirement on the judiciary.</P>

<P>"This statute ties the judge's hands," says McVeigh lawyer Randall Coyne, a professor on leave from the University of Oklahoma College of Law. "The court's responsibility is not to provide comfort for victims, but to provide a fair trial for defendants." </P>

<P><i>Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<br>
Copyright 1996, American Lawyer Media</i></P>
