<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<h2>The NRA Under the Gun</h2>

<P>Naftali Bendavid<BR>
<I>Legal Times</I><BR>
May 1, 1995</P>

<P>At a turbulent convention 18 years ago in Cincinnati, a group of
insurgent National Rifle Association members revolted against their
leaders, setting what had been a moderate sporting organization on a
path of hard-line political activism and harsh anti-government
rhetoric.</P>

<P>The reconstituted NRA, some say, ultimately laid the philosophical
groundwork for the rise of paramilitary groups like the Michigan
Militia. And the Oklahoma City tragedy now confronts the gun lobby
and its supporters with a wrenching question: Should they seek to
distance themselves from the militias and retreat from their longtime
strategy of demonizing government to justify gun ownership?</P>

<P>Wayne LaPierre, NRA executive vice president, says the group is not
considering a change in approach. "It doesn't accomplish anything to
lower the rhetoric if the abuses don't stop," LaPierre says,
referring to government raids he considers overzealous. "If the NRA
is beaten into lowering its rhetoric, will the African-American
community be beaten into lowering its rhetoric when a police abuse
occurs?" </P>

<P>But some NRA-watchers, including allies, say NRA leaders disagree on
what message the group should send now. Sorting out how -- if at all
-- the group should alter its strategy in the aftermath of the
bombing is likely to be a heated topic at the NRA's upcoming
convention May 20 in Phoenix. </P>

<P>"There are differences of opinion within the NRA itself on how they
are going to come down," says Lawrence Pratt, executive director of
Gun Owners of America. "It's something they'll have to thrash out.
You have quite a range of opinion on the NRA board." </P>

<P>Gun-control activists already are doing their best to use the bombing
to embarrass the NRA -- and goad the group into moderation -- by
shining a hot light on its connections with the militias. </P>

<P>"As the NRA has found itself in increasingly difficult battles, they
have been willing to reach out to the further fringes of American gun
society," says Josh Sugarmann, executive director of the
Washington-based Violence Policy Center, which researches firearms
violence. "The NRA's problem is that they don't differentiate anymore
between your run-of-the-mill gun nuts and your real nuts with guns."</P>

<P>Some of the connections between NRA leaders and militias are
relatively direct. Robert Brown, a member of the NRA executive
committee, is also publisher of Soldier of Fortune magazine, which
ran articles in its April and May issues supporting militias (along
with a much shorter one questioning them). </P>

<P>And earlier this year, NRA lobbyists rode to the rescue when they
heard rumors that the feds were about to raid certain militia groups.
Thomas Wyld, director of public relations and communications for the
NRA, wrote to the Treasury Department's Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms to express concern and seek information about any such
raid. </P>

<P>The membership of the militias and the NRA also overlaps, at least
somewhat. "Quite a few of us are members of the NRA," says Neil Watt,
regimental commander of the Texas Light Infantry, whose members dress
like soldiers and conduct military-style maneuvers. </P>

<P>But there is a more fundamental connection between the NRA and the
fatigue-clad weekend warriors. The NRA for years has pushed a
philosophy that justifies -- almost demands -- the militias'
existence: Citizens need guns to protect themselves against
tyrannical government, and parts of the U.S. government have become
fascistic. </P>

<P>A host of NRA literature -- assembled by groups like the Violence
Policy Center and Handgun Control Inc. -- illustrates the fever pitch
NRA leaders can hit when preaching to the faithful. </P>

<P>"Not too long ago, it was unthinkable for federal agents wearing nazi
bucket helmets and black storm-trooper uniforms to attack law-abiding
citizens," says a recent mailing appeal signed by LaPierre. "Not
today, not with Clinton." </P>

<P>The June 1994 issue of American Rifleman, the NRA magazine, includes
a special report apocalyptically titled, "The Final War Has Begun."
The article cites an alleged government plan to deglamorize guns and
reduce gun owners to a "manageable" number. "That's the fascist
language of Stalin, Hitler, Castro and Saddam Hussein," the article
says. "How many is 'manageable'? Who's going to 'manage' you and how
-- with fines and jail, or with tanks and clubs like Tiananmen
Square?" </P>

<P>Meanwhile, a newspaper column written last December by NRA executive
committee member Neal Knox suggests the assassinations of President
John F. Kennedy and Martin Luther King Jr. were part of a conspiracy
to enact gun control. "Is it possible that some of those incidents
could have been created for the purpose of disarming the people of
the free world?" Knox writes. "It's possible." </P>

<P>The sharpest NRA rhetoric, though, is reserved for the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the agency that enforces federal gun
laws. Agents' recent confrontations with the Branch Davidians in
Waco, Texas, and with white supremacist Randy Weaver at Ruby Ridge,
Idaho, are frequently cited as examples of ATF horrors. </P>

<P>Sometimes, ATF agents are likened to Nazis. </P>

<P>Jeff Cooper, an NRA board member in Arizona, in comments made on a
computer bulletin board that are being publicized by the Violence
Policy Center, even suggested that the agents are worse than Nazis.</P>

<P>"The Nazis are long ago and far away, whereas the ninja in the U.S.
are right now in full cry and apparently without fear of any sort of
control. They move mainly at night. They conceal their faces. They
use overwhelming firepower and they make almost no effort to identify
their targets. They are scarier than the Nazis, who at least never
concealed their faces." </P>

<P>SECOND AMENDMENT THEORY <BR>
At the same time, the NRA promotes a theory that the Second Amendment
to the Constitution, which guarantees the right to bear arms, is
intended to ensure that citizens can resist a tyrannical government.</P>

<P>There is an element of self-fulfilling prophecy in this thinking,
gun-control activists say. If the very act of enforcing gun laws
makes government agents into fascists -- and the only way to prepare
for a fascist attack is to stockpile weapons -- then armed
confrontation seems inevitable. </P>

<P>The harsh language used by the NRA and its supporters has led some
critics to suggest that the group's rhetoric contributed to the April
19 carnage in Oklahoma City. </P>

<P>"I am certain the NRA had nothing to do with Oklahoma," says Victor
Oboyski, president of the 10,000-member Federal Law Enforcement
Officers Association, which includes more than 600 ATF agents. "But
their heated rhetoric and full-page ads in The Washington Post and
USA Today showing ATF agents as Darth Vaders does feed the flames of
the paranoia that resulted in Oklahoma." </P>

<P>NRA leaders counter that it is ridiculous to link the NRA to the
militias or to the Oklahoma bombing. "Do they blame the automakers
for automobile accidents?" asks NRA board member Edie Reynolds, a
homemaker from Raleigh, N.C. "It's just incredible what people will
come up with to make a connection with something that really
shouldn't be connected." </P>

<P>BACKING AWAY FROM MILITIAS <BR>
The NRA's adversaries predict the group will increasingly begin
stressing its differences from the militias. "Clearly the NRA is in a
position where they will try to distance themselves from these
groups," says Robert Walker, legislative director of Handgun Control.</P>

<P>But LaPierre says the NRA already distanced itself -- 31 years ago.
He cites a January 1964 NRA statement that disavowed any connection
with groups that organize for violence, advocate the overthrow of the
government, or take on responsibilities that properly belong to the
police or military. </P>

<P>NRA leaders also expressed their attitude toward militias more
recently. Last November, the organization issued a statement saying,
in part, "Although the NRA has not been involved in the formation of
any citizen militia units, neither has the NRA discouraged, nor would
the NRA contemplate discouraging, exercise of any constitutional
right." And in a telephone interview last week, LaPierre hastened to
point out that not all militias are violent, anti-government groups.</P>

<P>The NRA does take particular care to distance itself from one of the
militias' central purposes. Many of the militias were formed because
the Constitution seems to guarantee gun ownership to militia members:
"A well regulated Militia, being necessary to the security of a free
State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be
infringed." But the NRA states emphatically that the right to gun
ownership does not depend on militia membership. </P>

<P>NRA board member Wayne Anthony Ross, writing in the April issue of
Soldier of Fortune, goes further in questioning the militias, saying
that under the Constitution, militias are to be organized by the
states. So militias that appoint officers and conduct training
without state authority are unconstitutional, Ross says. </P>

<P>NEW POLITICAL CLIMATE<BR>
Whether it is fair to link the NRA to the militias -- or the militias
to the bombing -- the political climate surrounding gun control
clearly has changed since the Oklahoma City tragedy. </P>

<P>Before April 19, the gun lobby was on a roll. Many NRA-backers won
congressional seats in the November elections, and the gun lobby and
its allies were marshaling forces to repeal the assault-weapons ban
and roll back the Brady law, which imposed a five-day waiting period
on those seeking to buy handguns. </P>

<P>Suddenly, all that has changed. House hearings on repealing the
assault-weapons ban and on abuses by ATF agents have been delayed.
And the House vote on repealing the ban, scheduled for May 18, has
been postponed. </P>

<P>"Given the fact that there are some politicians and groups that are
somehow demagoguing the issue and trying to blame gun owners or the
NRA, it's in everybody's interest to move that legislation to a
slower track," LaPierre says, "but not take it off the track. It will
be coming up again." </P>

<P>NRA opponents, of course, are doing all they can to make sure it does
not come up again. The Coalition to Stop Gun Violence has issued a
statement calling on House Speaker Newt Gingrich to abandon the move
to repeal the assault-weapons ban in the wake of the Oklahoma blast.
Handgun Control is also using the bombing to argue against the
repeal. </P>

<P>Oboyski, chief of the Federal Law Enforcement Officers Association,
predicts that the lawmakers who have been loudly attacking the ATF
and gun control will be on the defensive. "They're going to back off
100 percent," Oboyski says. "I think people on the Hill should be
held accountable, like the NRA, for the outrageous things they've
said on the floor of the House or Senate." </P>

<P>Steve Weidman, projects director for the Citizens Committee for the
Right to Keep and Bear Arms, warns that if the gun lobby lies low too
long, it risks ceding the field. "[Senate Majority Leader] Bob Dole
was going to lead the charge, but how much stomach he has for that
now, I wonder," Weidman says. "I don't think we should let them
regain the initiative. I think we should keep the momentum going."</P>

<P><i>Legal Times is an affiliate publication of Court TV.<br>
Copyright  1996, American Lawyer Media</i></P>
