<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<h2>Representing the Accused Bomber</h2>

<P>Robert Schmidt<BR>
<I>Legal Times</i><BR>
May 22, 1995</P>

<P>ENID, OKLA. -- When defense lawyer Stephen Jones got a message on May
5 to call David Russell at home, his first thought was that the judge
must have wanted another basset hound. </P>

<P>Jones and Russell, chief judge of the U.S. District Court for the
Western District of Oklahoma, have known each other for nearly 30
years, and they got their dogs from the same breeder. </P>

<P>But Russell wasn't making a social call. He wanted to know if Jones
would agree to be the court-appointed lawyer for one of the suspects
in the April 19 Oklahoma City bombing that claimed 167 lives. Russell
declined to name the suspect, saying only that it was someone who had
been or would be charged. </P>

<P>Jones told the judge he needed a day to think about it and to get
some advice. He consulted his wife and their four children; the
lawyers and staffers at his firm; and local business and political
leaders. He even reached out, through an intermediary, to a friend
and sometime client Frank Keating, the Republican governor of
Oklahoma. It was only after Jones accepted the assignment that
Russell told him he would be representing the main suspect, Timothy
McVeigh. </P>

<P>Russell knew that other suspects were likely, and had called four or
five other lawyers to see if they were available. Meanwhile, court
officials were scrambling to find counsel for McVeigh, whose original
appointed lawyers had declared a conflict and were trying to get out
of the case. </P>

<P>"I think I took a deep breath, and I said, 'Yes, sir,' " says Jones,
who concedes his first thought on learning his client's identity was,
"Oh, shit." </P>

<P>Jones was right to be a little nervous. </P>

<P>With that one decision, the life and practice of the 54-year-old
self-described "county seat lawyer" would change dramatically. </P>

<P>THREATS, CALLS, AND TV SHOWS <BR>
Jones quickly hired security for his home and office. Already, he has
received one telephoned death threat, an intruder has tried to break
into his home, and two men in a pickup truck pulled up one night to
the front gate of his house on the outskirts of town, demanding to
speak to him. They only left after being threatened with arrest. </P>

<P>Then there's the media. Reporters have flooded his office and home,
which is listed in the Enid phone book, with phone calls. Knowing his
client needs all the good press he can get, Jones has done his best
to respond to press inquiries. On May 16, Jones' day began with a
5:30 a.m. interview on NBC, which was followed by a 6:15 appearance
on ABC's "Good Morning America." </P>

<P>During a subsequent interview, conducted at his 11th floor offices in
the Broadway Tower professional building in Enid, Jones supervised
preparation of a brief seeking to delay the demolition of the Murrah
federal building. He also fielded several important phone calls,
including one from his son who needed money for a haircut. </P>

<P>"The judge asked me if he could do anything for me, and I said, 'Yes,
you could enter an order extending the 24-hour day to 60 hours,' "
says Jones. </P>

<P>Jones, who heads Enid's six-lawyer Jones &Wyatt, is finding out he
needs more than 60-hour days to defend a client who might be the most
hated man in America. Jones will have to tap every bit of skill he
has gleaned during a 30-year career as a litigator and political
player. </P>

<P>UNPOPULAR CLIENTS <BR>
He has taken on unpopular causesbefore -- the case of a man arrested
for unfurling a Viet Cong flag in 1970, state prisoners fighting for
better treatment, and numerous murderers and other criminal
defendants. He has handled close to 25 death penalty cases and has
never lost a client to the execution chamber. Currently, Jones is
trying to spare the life of Oklahoma condemned prisoner Roger Dale
Stafford, scheduled to die July 1 for killing a Texas family in 1978.</P>


<P>He is also no stranger to politically charged situations. A former
counsel to the Republican Party in Oklahoma, Jones was a young
assistant in New York to Richard Nixon in 1964. His political career
came to an end, he says, in 1990, when he was trounced as the GOP
candidate running against Democratic Sen. David Boren. </P>

<P>"They may not have discovered a cure for AIDS, but I will tell you, I
discovered a cure for politics. Try it. Run,'' says Jones. </P>

<P>Today, Jones is a full-time litigator with a prominent statewide
practice. He is well-known in the courthouses in Oklahoma City,
although he lives and practices about 80 miles north of the capital,
in Enid (population 50,000). And despite his small-town address,
Jones says he is no "aw-shucks" lawyer. </P>

<P>His practice is split 50-50 between criminal and civil litigation, in
both federal and state courts. His clients have ranged from the Shell
Oil Co. and Sears & Roebuck to 1960s radical Abbie Hoffman to Gov.
Keating to local farmers and to cop killers. </P>

<P>"Stephen is a very, very fine lawyer; he really has ability," says
litigator James Paul Linn, of Oklahoma City's Linn & Neville. He says
Jones is probably one of the top five criminal lawyers in the state.</P>


<P>Linn and eight other lawyers who know Jones say they are not
surprised that he took on the McVeigh case. </P>

<P>"I question his judgment sometimes, as to what he takes for cases,"
adds Linn. "He's the only one of the five, if you'd pick them, that
would take the [bombing] case." </P>

<P>OFFICER OF THE COURT <BR>
Jones says he has a very simple reason for agreeing to represent
McVeigh: He's an officer of the court, and had no disqualifying
conflict of interest. </P>

<P>"We shouldn't let just left-wing lawyers defend left-wing cases and
right-wing defend right, or traditional criminal defense lawyers do
criminal work," says Jones. "It keeps the bar independent if you
involve everybody." </P>

<P>Jones is a trial lawyer from the old school -- when law was a
profession, not a business. In the vein of the late Edward Bennett
Williams, whom Jones admires, he goes into the courtroom looking to
win at almost any cost -- as long as it is ethical. </P>

<P>Jones takes on seemingly impossible cases, several Oklahoma lawyers
say, because he thrives on the challenge. And like most top-notch
litigators, these lawyers say, Jones has a healthy ego. </P>

<P>He also has not shied away from controversial causes he believes in,
even if there is a price to pay. </P>

<P>PROTECTING FIRST AMENDMENT <BR>
During the Watergate scandal, Jones split with the Oklahoma Civil
Liberties Union, for whom he worked as general counsel. Nixon was one
of Jones' heroes. When the organization called for Nixon's
impeachment, and refused to let Jones formally dissent in the group's
newsletter, Jones says he felt he had no choice but to resign his
post. </P>

<P>"I thought we were an organization devoted to the protection of the
First Amendment, and we don't even practice it internally," Jones
recalls thinking at the time. </P>

<P>Then there is the Viet Cong flag incident, which happened precisely
25 years before the call came from Judge Russell. </P>

<P>On May 5, 1970, the day after four student protesters at Kent State
University were shot dead by the National Guard, a student at the
University of Oklahoma was arrested for carrying a Viet Cong flag in
a campus protest. Jones, a young lawyer practicing at a venerable
Enid firm called Otjen & Carter, agreed to represent the student. </P>

<P>"I was young and full of piss and vinegar," says Jones. "I walked out
of the courtroom and there were a couple of reporters there and they
said, 'What are you going to do now?' and I said, 'By God, I'll take
this case all the way to federal court.' " </P>

<P>The case was the lead story in the local paper. The older partners at
the firm, which is now defunct, were horrified at the political
stance of Jones' client. </P>

<P>Name partner Frank Carter, the former mayor of Enid, "blew a
gasket,'' Jones recalls. Carter ordered him to drop the case or leave
the firm. Jones told him he felt bound by the lawyers code of ethics
and could not withdraw. </P>

<P>Shortly thereafter, Jones was driving home from an amusement park
with his son and heard on the car radio that he had been fired. Then
Carter sent out about 5,000 letters to firm clients, local country
club members, the media, and other lawyers, telling them Jones had
"resigned." </P>

<P>"That was my position," says Jones, who promptly opened his own shop.
"I paid a price, politically and socially. But I thought I was right,
and I continued to take unpopular cases." </P>

<P>The flag case, Jones says, made it impossible for him not to take
McVeigh on as a client. </P>

<P>"When Judge Russell called me, what could I say? That my life had
been a living lie for 25 years, and I was older now and wiser, and I
wouldn't make that mistake a second time?" Jones says. </P>

<P>Thus far, Jones says he has not been given the cold shoulder by the
Oklahoma establishment for taking on McVeigh. </P>

<P>DOESN'T SEEK SPOTLIGHT <BR>
He concedes that he considered his own interests, but says he doesn't
need the national spotlight to build his practice. </P>

<P>"I'm a county seat lawyer before this happened, and when it's over
with, I will go back to being a county seat lawyer," he says. "I
don't want clients in New York or St. Paul or Atlanta or Timbuktu. I
live very well. I have a very nice income, a very nice home." </P>

<P>Early in his career, Jones, who was born in Lafayette, La., and
raised in Texas, was on the way to becoming a Washington political
insider. Ultimately, he decided to settle in Enid instead. </P>

<P>Jones' first brush with national politics came in 1964, when he was a
law student at the University of Oklahoma Law School. One day, Jones
returned from class to find a letter from Nixon, who was then a
partner at New York's Nixon Mudge Rose Guthrie Alexander & Mitchell,
the firm now known as Mudge Rose Guthrie Alexander & Ferdon. Nixon,
who had lost the California gubernatorial race in 1962, asked Jones
to come to New York and be his assistant. </P>

<P>Jones had caught Nixon's eye with an essay Jones wrote in college,
claiming that because of ballot irregularities Nixon had actually
beaten John F. Kennedy in Texas during the 1960 presidential
election. Jones, politically savvy at an early age, sent Nixon a copy
of his paper and a letter about himself. </P>

<P>After getting the job offer and a free plane ticket from Nixon, Jones
put law school on hold and flew to New York City. Jones' main job was
to help Nixon prepare a number of articles he was commissioned to
write. </P>

<P>"I had $25 in my pocket, which showed you how naive I was," says
Jones. </P>

<P>TURNED DOWN WHITEHOUSE JOB <BR>
Jones worked for Nixon from January 1964 until the Republican
convention that summer, when Barry Goldwater was nominated. Although
Nixon offered to get Jones a job with the presidential candidate,
Jones opted to head back to law school. </P>

<P>Jones graduated in 1966 with thoughts of running for office. Through
a friend, he was introduced to Rep. Paul Findley, a Republican from
Illinois. Findley hired Jones to be his administrative assistant in
Washington. </P>

<P>He worked for Findley for three years, until 1969, the year Nixon
became president. Although Nixon offered Jones a chance to work in
the White House, Jones turned him down, he says, because he wanted to
go back home and settle down. </P>

<P>"There are just times in life where you have to decide what to do,
and I wanted to live out here," says Jones. "And I never regretted it
for a day." </P>

<P>RUNNING AND WALKING <BR>
Although he left Washington, Jones did not put aside his political
aspirations. He ran for Congress in 1976 and 1980, losing both times
in the Republican primary. He also lost a bid for state attorney
general in 1974. </P>

<P>His most prominent campaign was the 1990 Senate race, when he
garnered a mere 17 percent of the vote against the Democratic
incumbent, David Boren. </P>

<P>A Boren campaign official who watched Jones carefully throughout the
election says that Jones was a gentlemanly campaigner but never
received support from Republicans -- especially because of his track
record in the courtroom. </P>

<P>"He was pleasant, he was smart, and he was courteous as an opponent,"
this official says. "He just wasn't the kind of candidate who was
going to capture the excitement of the Republican Party. Boren was
more conservative." </P>

<P>Jones says he was just overpowered by Boren, a law school classmate
and one of Oklahoma's favorite sons. </P>

<P>"I didn't so much run for that as I walked," says Jones. "I was just
glad they counted my votes." </P>

<P>Five years later, Jones says he harbors no further political plans
but that he is now firmly conservative. </P>

<P>Formerly a self-styled liberal Republican in the tradition of Nelson
Rockefeller and Wendell Willkie, Jones traces his political evolution
to two events: the election of Ronald Reagan and, more important, the
confirmation hearings of Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas. </P>

<P>"As those hearings went on, I said, 'Boy what a bunch of hypocrites,'
" says Jones, referring to members of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
"The more I listened, the madder I got." </P>

<P>"When Clarence Thomas came on and said, 'This is a high-tech lynching
of an uppity black,' I thought, 'By God, that's right,' " Jones says.
"This is politics. It's about Roe v. Wade. From that day forward, I
kind of re-examined some of my basic beliefs." </P>

<P>Nevertheless, Jones insists he is no right-winger, and says he
remains tolerant and committed to defending people from the left, as
he has in the past. </P>

<P>"I'm a traditional conservative," says Jones. "I believe in the Bill
of Rights, and vigorous defense, and the exclusionary rule. I support
the Miranda decision." </P>

<P>Most of his cases are local. He says 90 percent of his clients are
within 60 miles of his office in Enid. "You don't have to live in New
York or Washington to have the interesting cases," says Jones. "There
are challenges everywhere." </P>

<P>Some of his biggest challenges have come in representing defendants
facing the death penalty. Of the 20 to 25 capital defendants he's
represented, Jones says, only five have been sentenced to death. Four
of the five sentences were vacated on appeal; the fifth case, which
is no longer being handled by Jones, is still on appeal. </P>

<P>Jones' clients have run the gamut from '60s radicals to establishment
politicians. Jones does some legal work for Oklahoma Gov. Keating.
The governor turned to Jones in a dispute involving J.C. Watts' seat
on the Oklahoma Corporation Commission, which regulates oil and gas
industries in the state. (Watts is now a member of the U.S. House).</P>


<P>Watts, a Republican, was forced to give up his post after being
elected to Congress last November. He waited until Keating was
inaugurated on Jan. 9, so outgoing Gov. David Walters, a Democrat,
could not make the appointment. </P>

<P>Walters, however, appointed his own candidate, contending that Watts
became a member of Congress when the body convened on Jan. 3. Watts
argued that he became a member on Jan. 9, when he took the oath of
office. Jones argued the case before the Oklahoma Supreme Court in
February. </P>

<P>Asked if his representation of Gov. Keating -- who will help pilot
the Oklahoma City cleanup -- conflicts at all with his representation
of McVeigh, Jones says his research indicates there's no problem. </P>

<P>ABBIE HOFFMAN'S LAWYER <BR>
Abbie Hoffman first appeared in Jones' life about 25 years ago.
Students at Oklahoma State University had asked Hoffman to speak at
the school, but were overruled by the school's board of regents. The
student senate turned to Jones to challenge the regents' control over
students' choice of speakers. </P>

<P>Jones took the case to federal court, but it was mooted when the
regents dropped their policy. Hoffman spoke at the school, and Jones
introduced him from the stage. </P>

<P>While at the school, Hoffman "got some students riled up at four in
the morning," says Jones, and was later arraigned in U.S. District
Court for the District of Columbia on charges of violating the
interstate commerce clause by inciting a riot. </P>

<P>William Kunstler recommended Jones to Hoffman's attorney, criminal
defender Gerald Lefcourt, who hired Jones to handle the Oklahoma part
of the case. The government later dropped the prosecution after the
judge required them to reveal information about their surveillance.
Jones says he later found out that he was the target of the bugging.</P>


<P>In 1972, Jones took on a landmark civil rights case in Oklahoma,
Battle v. Anderson. </P>

<P>Jones' client, Bobby Battle, an inmate at the Oklahoma State
Penitentiary in McAlester, sued the state over a litany of alleged
unconstitutional conditions at the prison -- including racial
segregation, overcrowding, and disparate punishments. Joined by the
U.S. Justice Department, Jones won the case and the state prison
system was taken over by the court until 1984. </P>

<P>McVeigh's is not the first bombing case Jones has handled. In the
mid-1970s, Jones represented Harawese Moore, who was convicted of
planting an incendiary device outside the U.S. Courthouse and Federal
Building in Oklahoma City. The prosecutor in the case was then U.S.
Attorney David Russell -- who went on to become the chief judge who
appointed Jones to represent McVeigh. </P>

<P>Jones' career has crossed the paths of several other players involved
in the current Oklahoma City bombing case. </P>

<P>Arlene Joplin, the Oklahoma City prosecutor involved in the matter,
began her legal career in private practice working for Jones. Merrick
Garland, the Justice Department's principal associate deputy attorney
general, who is coordinating the investigation for the department, is
a former partner at D.C.'s Arnold & Porter -- the firm Jones works
with when he has legal work in the District. Arnold & Porter has also
used Jones as a local counsel in Oklahoma. And Jones and Michael
Tigar -- the University of Texas law professor who is representing
another Oklahoma City bombing suspect, Terry Nichols -- have worked
together before, defending a controversial Oklahoma City
psychotherapist. </P>

<P>Despite the high-profile nature of the bombing case, Jones is trying
not to let it take over his whole law practice. </P>

<P>Last week, for instance, Jones met with two clients in other cases.
Jones says he expects the other five lawyers at his firm to work on
the McVeigh case with him, but they will also handle other matters.
(Federal law provides for at least two paid defenders for McVeigh,
but Jones can bring in as much unpaid help as he likes -- or petition
the court for further paid assistance.) </P>

<P>"I think it's important to keep some balance and perspective," says
Jones. </P>

<P>Nevertheless, Jones' time is certainly consumed by McVeigh and the
investigation. </P>

<P>To start with, he's been playing catch-up. Jones was handed the case
slightly more than two weeks after the blast. McVeigh's former
lawyers -- John Coyle III of Oklahoma City's Coyle & McCoy, and
Oklahoma City Federal Public Defender Susan Otto -- were recused
because they knew a number of people killed in the bombing. </P>

<P>Worried that his client was being hurt by so much negative press,
Jones took to the airwaves shortly after his appointment. One of his
first stops was CNN's "Larry King Live." </P>

<P>Jones is also trying to develop a good working relationship with
McVeigh, which he concedes has not been easy, largely because of
logistics. Any visit to see him takes at least two-and-a-half hours,
taking into account the drive to the federal prison in El Reno,
Okla., and the time it takes to get inside the prison once he's on
site. Last week, Jones says, it took him 45 minutes just to pass
through security. </P>

<P>At Jones' request, the court has appointed Assistant Federal Public
Defender Robert Nigh in Lincoln, Neb., to assist Jones in the
defense. Nigh used to work for Jones in private practice. Jones says
he also expects the court to appoint another lawyer to his team, but
he wouldn't disclose who it was. </P>

<P>Jones, who will be paid $125 an hour, also has been busy hiring
experts, conducting interviews with witnesses, inspecting the blast
site, and researching the law. In one area, Jones is heading into
uncharted waters: Federal death penalty trials are rare, and McVeigh
will be one of the first defendants tried under federal death penalty
provisions enacted last year. </P>

<P>Jones is also planning on having McVeigh tested by a psychiatrist to
see if he is mentally competent, which he says he does in all murder
cases he handles. </P>

<P>Another large part of his job right now, Jones says, is "correcting
some of the very wrong, misleading information about tips,'' in the
media -- from McVeigh's possible paramilitary connections to the many
sightings of John Doe No. 2. Jones has already told reporters that
published accounts citing sources who claim McVeigh confessed to the
crime were false. </P>

<P>Despite the daunting task in front of him, Jones is confident. </P>

<P>"I'm beginning to think what they've basically got is a guy whose
motives indicate that he doesn't like the federal government, but
what they're short on is forensic proof,'' says Jones. "Very few
people ever got convicted for their motives. While they'd like you to
think it's all buttoned up, and it may be, I suspect they've got some
legal nightmares." </P>

<P><i>Legal Times is an affiliate publication of Court TV.<br>
Copyright  1996, American Lawyer Media</i></P>
