<h2>Scrambling to Find a Defender</h2>

<P>Richard Barbieri<BR>
<I>Legal Times</I><BR>
May 1, 1995</P>

<P>When 27-year-old Timothy James McVeigh went before a federal
magistrate April 27 for a hearing on allegations that he was
responsible for the most grotesque act of domestic terrorism in U.S.
history, he was represented by attorneys who didn't even want to be
involved in the case. </P>

<P>His appointed lawyers, Oklahoma City criminal defenders John Coyle
III and Susan Otto, by their own admission were laboring under a
sharp conflict of interest that cast serious doubt on whether they
could vigorously defend McVeigh. Both lawyers lost friends or
acquaintances in the massive April 19 bombing of an Oklahoma City
federal building that claimed more than 110 lives -- and both had
already unsuccessfully sought to be removed from the case. </P>

<P>The court's failure last week to move more quickly to remove lawyers
with such an obvious conflict left McVeigh in a vacuum at a crucial
time -- the first days of an investigation when permanent legal
counsel can be vital to developing a defense strategy and protecting
a defendant's constitutional rights. </P>

<P>"If they are going to replace someone, they want to do it early,"
says John Copacino, director of Georgetown University Law Center's
D.C. Criminal Justice Clinic. "You are leaving lawyers on the case
who are telling you they can't represent him zealously." </P>

<P>The lawyers had wasted no time trying to get out of the case,
petitioning U.S. Magistrate Judge Ronald Howland within a few days of
being tapped to represent McVeigh. </P>

<P>"[E]veryone in our city has been impacted by the explosion, and
counsel is no exception," Coyle wrote in an April 24 motion. "The
enormous impact of this tragedy . . . has caused doubt as to my
ability to give Timothy McVeigh the absolutely unbiased and objective
representation that everyone accused in our country deserves." </P>

<P>Despite their pleas, Coyle and Otto were left on the case, at least
as of April 28. </P>

<P>Fourteen criminal practitioners and professors interviewed for this
story sympathized with the difficult situation facing Coyle and Otto.
But some criticized Coyle for drawing unnecessary attention to the
conflict by talking about it publicly. </P>

<P>"I do question Coyle going on 'Larry King Live,' " says Elisabeth
Semel, a San Diego criminal defense attorney and co-chair of the
legislative committee of the National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers. "The optimum would have been for Coyle to go to the judge
and say, 'I have a conflict,' and, once it was done, to have issued a
statement." </P>

<P>Throughout the week, court officials in Oklahoma City and in
Washington scrambled to find a way around a high-stakes dilemma. </P>

<P>Leaving Coyle and Otto on the case despite their conflict set up a
situation where McVeigh could later argue that he was denied his
Sixth Amendment right to competent counsel, some observers say. At
the same time, removing the appointed lawyers before substitute
counsel were found could have left McVeigh with no representation at
all -- a scenario fraught with problems of its own. </P>

<P>But at the bottom of it all, last week's struggle to sort out legal
representation for McVeigh was driven by a confluence of
extraordinary -- and mostly unavoidable -- factors stemming from the
unprecedented nature of the case. </P>

<P>From the outset, Attorney General Janet Reno's decision to seek the
federal death penalty against the perpetrators -- announced just
hours after the blast and more than a day before McVeigh's arrest on
charges that he destroyed a federal building with a bomb -- upped the
ante for finding counsel. </P>

<P>In capital-punishment cases, federal law requires that courts move
swiftly to appoint at least two lawyers for defendants who request
counsel. (Most criminal defendants who can't afford a lawyer are
represented by a single deputy public defender.) And in capital
cases, at least one of the two appointed lawyers must be skilled in
death-penalty law. </P>

<P>The search for counsel was complicated by the rarity of federal
death-penalty cases: There are no regional defense resource centers
with standing lists of experienced lawyers to jump into emergencies,
as there are for state capital cases. </P>

<P>The U.S. government last executed a prisoner in 1963; federal
prosecutors haven't even filed capital charges in Oklahoma City in
many decades. Nationwide, there have been only 46 prosecutions
approved by the attorney general since 1988 -- a period when states
have brought thousands of death cases. The law McVeigh is being
charged under, a provision of the 1994 Omnibus Crime Control Act that
added some 50 new death penalties to federal law, has been invoked in
only a handful of previous cases throughout the country. </P>

<P>It didn't take long for the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts
to get involved in the search for lawyers. The federal death-penalty
statute says that federal public defenders should put together a list
of qualified counsel for judges to appoint. But owing to Otto's
declaration of a conflict in this case -- and her claim that the
entire public defender's staff had been affected by the blast -- the
Administrative Office stepped in to help prepare a list. </P>

<P>The Administrative Office declines to discuss the case in any detail.
Spokeswoman Karen Redmond confirms that the AO helped with the search
and that this was the first time the office had been called on for
such a task. </P>

<P>An experienced capital litigator, who asked not to be identified,
says judicial officials were forced to cast a wide net because most
other qualified Oklahoma practitioners would probably suffer the same
conflicts cited by Otto and Coyle. </P>

<P>"There was a fairly wide-ranging -- informal but fairly wide-ranging
-- canvas for ideas," this lawyer says. </P>

<P>Indeed, prospective lawyers would likely have to come from elsewhere
because the blast had such an enormous impact on the relatively small
legal community in Oklahoma City. </P>

<P>"Just about every lawyer here has friends who were injured or killed,
or knows people who do," says Oklahoma City's William Devinney,
president of the 300-member Oklahoma Criminal Defense Lawyers
Association." There's no way out of it." </P>

<P>THE PERFECT FIT? <BR>
In most cases, Coyle and Otto would be logical choices to handle
Oklahoma City's first federal death-penalty case in years. </P>

<P>But United States v. McVeigh isn't most cases. </P>

<P>The 47-year-old Coyle is an experienced defense specialist, a name
partner in four-lawyer Coyle & McCoy, an active participant in local
trial bars, and a member of the National Association of Criminal
Defense Lawyers. </P>

<P>"John Coyle is one of the leading criminal defense lawyers in
Oklahoma City," says Devinney. </P>

<P>Coyle's partner, Gloyd McCoy, goes a step further. "John Coyle is the
best trial lawyer in Oklahoma," says McCoy, a former deputy state
public defender who joined Coyle's firm a little more than two years
ago. </P>

<P>Coyle did not return phone calls seeking comment for this article.</P>

<P>As the federal public defender for the Western District of Oklahoma,
Otto also seemed well-suited for the case. She has worked in the
federal public defender's office since the late 1980s, and served as
first assistant in the office before taking over the top job in 1993,
according to Devinney. </P>

<P>Otto, who did not return phone calls, apparently sought out Coyle to
represent McVeigh because Coyle had experience representing
defendants in state death-penalty trials. </P>

<P>But almost immediately after being appointed, both lawyers took steps
to get removed from the case. Each filed a motion April 24, seeking
to withdraw. </P>

<P>Both said they had been personally affected by the blast. </P>

<P>Coyle was in the Oklahoma County Courthouse when the 4,800-pound
fertilizer bomb, allegedly delivered by his would-be client,
exploded. Coyle then headed for the nearby federal office building,
witnessing the "the terror and carnage at the scene." At his law
office, four blocks away, his employees were "emotionally shaken" and
"terrified." </P>

<P>Coyle said he was friends with several government employees who were
slain. </P>

<P>In a similar motion, Otto said that her office had been badly damaged
by the blast and that she and her staff were lucky to be alive. </P>

<P>"This was a terrifying experience for every person in the Federal
Public Defender's office," she wrote. "It was immediately clear to
all of us that we were spared from injury and personal loss by pure
good fortune." </P>

<P>EASY CALL <BR>
Given their palpable conflict of interest, the lawyers' decision was
appropriate ethical conduct, according to the consensus of criminal
practitioners and professors interviewed for this article. </P>

<P>Many conflicts fall into gray areas. But not the one faced by Coyle
and Otto, the lawyers and ethics experts say. Many instead faulted
the court for not immediately disqualifying Coyle and Otto. </P>

<P>"This is one of the most critical times [in the case] because it sets
the foundation for everything that is to follow," says Ira Robbins, a
professor at American University's Washington College of Law. </P>

<P>"This [decision] was such an easy call," Robbins adds. "How often do
lawyers publicly state that they have a personal interest and as a
result cannot represent the client objectively?" </P>

<P>While not faulting Coyle and Otto for declaring a conflict, a few
lawyers and professors question at least some of Coyle's public
statements about the issue. </P>

<P>"When I saw the people hollering at [McVeigh], I thought that I had
never seen anyone that needed a lawyer more than he did at that time.
So when they asked me if I would help that evening, I agreed to do
it," Coyle said on "Larry King Live," a Cable News Network call-in
program. At another point, while resisting many of King's attempts to
get him to reveal details about his conversations with McVeigh, Coyle
said he had had "mixed emotion[s]" when he first met McVeigh. </P>

<P>Some defense lawyers say Coyle's comments could further prejudice an
already outraged public. </P>

<P>"To air this in a public setting really damaged the guy," says
Michael Burt, a deputy public defender in San Francisco. </P>

<P>"It really creates the impression that no one will touch this guy,
that even the lawyers think he's guilty," says Burt, whose
high-profile clients have included Lyle Menendez, one of the two
Beverly Hills brothers accused of the 1991 slaying of their parents,
and Richard Ramirez, the Los Angeles "Night Stalker" who was
convicted in 1989 of 13 murders. </P>

<P>But most observers say that Coyle didn't cross the line. One lawyer
who was sympathetic to Coyle's position was Avraham Moskowitz, a
partner in New York's Anderson Kill Olick & Oshinsky. </P>

<P>In February, Moskowitz was briefly appointed counsel for Ramzi Ahmed
Yousef, a member of a radical Islamic group, who is accused of
planning the 1993 Word Trade Center bombing. Moskowitz got out of the
case when a federal judge in New York decided that the appearance of
a conflict between the lawyer, a Jew, and his client was too great.</P>

<P>"I don't think it damages the client's presumption of innocence,"
Moskowitz says of Coyle's statement that McVeigh needed a lawyer. </P>

<P>"He needs a lawyer really badly because he is accused of the crime of
the century. Anybody with any sophistication would understand that,"
Moskowitz says. </P>

<P>Coyle's partner, McCoy, says Coyle's critics misunderstood the
lawyer's public statements. </P>

<P>"He didn't say, 'I never saw anyone more guilty,' " McCoy says. Coyle
was merely reacting to the public anger his client faces. </P>

<P>"I was a block away when that thing blew up. I know the impact,"
McCoy says. "These are very troubled people and were expressing their
opinions." </P>

<P><i>Legal Times is an affiliate publication of Court TV.<br>
Copyright  1996, American Lawyer Media</i></P>
