<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Alaska v. LaParle (3/96)</H2>

<P>Gerard LaParle and Dennis Bump were no strangers to the courtroom.</P>

<P>LaParle was a prominent divorce attorney and Bump was a trial lawyer specializing in defense insurance cases and a partner in one of the Alaska's largest firms.</P>

<P>But the two found themselves in different roles when prosecutors charged LaParle with perjury, fraud and theft for hiding more than $77,000 from Bump's estranged wife during divorce negotiations in 1992. Bump also was charged but eventually pleaded no contest to one charge of fraud and agreed to testify against LaParle.</P>

<P>Bump testified that he first contacted LaParle in the late 1980s when his marriage was in trouble.  At the time, LaParle told Bump that he could take a large retainer, put it into a trust account that would never have to be disclosed to his wife, and return the unused portion.
 
But Bump and his wife would reconcile for a year. During that time, Bump opened four bank accounts in his name and began building assets because he was not sure about the future.</P>

<P>Bump's wife filed for divorce in 1992, and he hired LaParle. LaParle advised him to close an account with $77,856 and give him the money to deposit in a trust account. LaParle also told Bump to tell his wife about the other three accounts, which contained more than $100,000. </P>

<P>As the divorce settlement progressed, Bump signed sworn statements declaring that he had disclosed all assets, including bank accounts, to his wife. He testified that LaParle helped prepare and reviewed the documents before they were filed with the court.</P>

<P>Once the divorce was finalized, LaParle returned nearly $68,000 to Bump.</P>

<P>The defense contended that LaParle wanted  a large retainer because it appeared the Bumps faced a lengthy and bitter divorce fight. The defense also accused Bump of implicating LaParle in order to protect himself.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
LaParle was found guilty of first-degree theft, perjury and scheme to defraud. He was acquitted of one perjury count.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
