<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: >Arizona v. Ring</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif"
ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR>

<H2>Arizona v. Ring</H2>

<P>Timothy Ring, a former Arizona corrections officer and a self-described
bounty hunter, was one of three men accused of killing an armored van driver
and stealing more than $800,000. </P>

<P>The state claimed that on Nov. 28, 1994, Ring, along with two other former
law enforcement officials -- James Greenham and William Ferguson II -- shot and
killed 61-year-old John Magoch, the driver of a Wells Fargo armored van, as
Mogoch stopped to pick up a deposit at a Glendale, Arizona mall.</P>

<P>The three men allegedly stole $562,877 in cash and $270,921 in checks,
bringing Wells Fargo's total estimated loss to $833,798. Ring was the first of
the three men to be tried.</P>

<P>Witnesses reported seeing the white armored carrier van being driven by two
men and followed by a third in a small, red pick-up truck. Five hours later,
Magoch's body was found inside the van in a church parking lot with one hole in
his head. No bullet was found.</P>

<P><B>The Prosecution's Case:</B> About a month after the crime, Judy Espinoza,
Greenham's former girlfriend, identified Greenham as a potential suspect. She
thought another man she knew only as "Tim" was involved in the crime. She
believed Tim was a bond recovery agent who also worked for an FBI agent. </P>

<P>Shortly after, the FBI and Glendale police tapped the suspects' phones. In
conversations, the three men allegedly discussed the crime, sometimes spoke in
code, the state maintained.</P>

<P>In a search of Ring's home, police found $270,000 in cash, the barrel of a
.22 caliber rifle, a silencer, and a piece of paper containing what the state
says is a division of money under the initials F, Y and T. The state said that
"F" is for Ferguson; "T" is for (Timothy) Ring; and "Y" is for Greenham, who is
allegedly nicknamed "Yoda." The series of numbers under the three initials
totals $575,955, about $13,000 more than the amount of cash Wells Fargo
estimates was stolen</P>

<P>The state argued the silencer was used to shoot Magoch at midday in the
shopping center, which would explain why no witnesses heard a gunshot. The
state said that the .22 caliber weapon barrel is relevant because the victim
was shot with a small caliber weapon. But because the fatal bullet was not
recovered, it was not possible to prove that the gun was the murder weapon.</P>

<P>Investigators identified two other men -- Michael Sanders and Brian Robbins
-- as potential co-conspirators. Both reportedly cooperated with the police and
admitted to plotting with Ring and Greenham. But their testimony was not heard
because immunity deals could not be worked out.</P>

<P><B>Spending Sprees:</B> According to the state, the three men spent money
freely in the months between the robbery and the arrests. Prosecutor Alfred
Fenzel detailed the suspects' spending habits. Fenzel said Ring paid $7,495 in
cash on Christmas Eve 1994 for two all-terrain vehicles and six days later paid
$1,100 cash for a trailer. Fenzel said Ring also bought a motorcycle for $7,300
cash and placed $1,000 down on a new car for his wife.</P>

<P><B>The Defense's Case:</B> Ring denied all charges. His lawyer, Greg Clark,
theorized that Greenham, Robbins and Sanders may have committed the crime.
Greenham moved into Ring's house temporarily after the incident, Clark claimed.
Some of Greenham's belongings were stored in Ring's garage and were found
during the police search. Clark said some of the state's evidence against Ring
actually belonged to Greenham.</P>

<P>Ring had a weapon barrel, a silencer and a large amount of cash in his home
because he was a bounty hunter who occasionally works for the FBI, Clark
said.</P>

<P><B>The Charges:</B> Ring was charged with first-degree murder, armed
robbery, first-degree burglary, theft and conspiracy to commit murder -- or in
the alternative, conspiracy to commit armed robbery or conspiracy to commit
burglary.</P>

<P>Under Arizona law, Ring can only be convicted of one count of conspiracy.
For example, he could be found guilty of conspiracy to commit murder and
murder, but not conspiracy to commit murder and conspiracy to commit burglary.
Because of this, the state has charged him with alternative theories of
conspiracy to try to cover all their bases.</P>

<P><B>Legal Terms:</B>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><B>First-degree murder:</B> Premeditated killing. In Arizona, a
conviction on this charge carries a minimum sentenced of life imprisonment with
no possibility of release for 25 years. It could also mean the death penalty.

	<LI><B>First-degree burglary:</B> entering or remaining unlawfully in a
nonresidential structure with the intent to commit any felony while in the
knowing possession of a deadly weapon (Arizona Law).

	<LI><B>Accomplice:</B> a person with the intent to promote or facilitate
the commission of an offense (Arizona Law).
</UL>


<P><B>The Judge:</B> Greg Martin has served as a superior court judge since
1989. He was previously a criminal defense lawyer in private practice for 13
years.</P>

<P><B>The Prosecution:</B> Alfred Fenzel joined the county district attorney's
office in 1988, after several years in private practice. From 1974 to 1985, he
was an assistant district attorney in Westchester County, New York He has
prosecuted two defendants who are currently on Arizona's death row.</P>

<P><B>The Defense:</B> Greg Clark was appointed to the case after Ring was
declared indigent. Clark, a sole practitioner, has 14 years of experience in
criminal defense, defending in 21 capital cases.</P>

<P><B>The Verdict:</B> On Dec. 6, 1996, the jury found Ring guilty of first-degree murder, conspiracy to commit armed robbery, burglary in the first-degree and theft. He will be sentenced Feb. 21, 1996 and faces either death by lethal injection or life in prison with the possibility of parole after 25 years. </P>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American
Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
