<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Boydston v. Link Management (3/96)</H2>

<P>Several days after Thanksgiving 1992, members of the Boydston family got together for a reunion. That night they went to a concert at Billy Bob's Texas in Ft. Worth, which bills itself as the largest honky tonk in the world.</P>

<P>The seven family members claimed they were accosted by bouncers as they were leaving the Sawyer Brown concert. Who started the altercation was unclear, but angry words were exchanged, punches were thrown and a nasty fight followed.</P>

<P>The Boydstons sued for assault and battery, intentional infliction of emotional distress and negligence, claiming that Link Management was negligent in the hiring, training and supervision of the bouncers.</P>

<P>Here's the plaintiffs' version of what happened.</P>

<P>They were leaving the November 27, 1992, concert when bouncer William Loffland grabbed Tammy Boydston by the arm and accused her of throwing a drink at an usher. Tammy said she didn't throw a drink but Loffland wouldn't let go of her arm. Tammy's sister Gaylene then threw her hands up in Loffland's face and said, "we didn't do anything." Loffland pushed her away but she came back at him. Gaylene said Loffland then pushed her to the ground.</P>

<P>When Gayle's husband Stewart said, "let's get my wife," several Boydston men tried to intervene but the bouncers allegedly jumped Danny Boydston and began beating him up.  His brother Travis tried to help but also was beaten up. The fight finally ended when the bouncers hauled Travis to an alleyway outside the club and left him on the ground. Several days later, Travis had emergency surgery for a blood clot on his brain which he claimed was related to the fight.</P>

<P>The defense claimed the Boydstons started the fight by attacking the bouncers. It also said the Boydstons had been drinking and may have been drunk at the time of the altercation.</P>

<P>The defense version of events was that Gaylene had been arguing with the usher during the concert because she wanted to sit in the reserved section even though she only had a standing room only ticket.  The usher claimed she called security to deal with the situation and to make sure the Boydstons did not get out of control.</P>

<P>At this time, someone threw a drink on the usher. The defense claimed that Gaylene rushed Loffland, and that Danny threw the first punch. </P>

<P>The defense claimed Billy Bob's has extensive training for bouncers, who start out by checking IDs at the door. They then work the floor for several months with a more experienced person before being allowed to work alone.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
After several days of testimony, an out-of-court settlement was reached on March 27, 1996. The settlement was not disclosed.<!--- full_end---></P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
