<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<p><h2>California v. Bardo (10/91)</h2>
There was no doubt that Robert John Bardo fatally shot actress Rebecca Schaeffer on July 18, 1989. But was it a premeditated act of an obsessed fan, or the result of Bardo's irrational  perceptions about the actress?<p>

During the trial, prosecutors contended that Bardo tracked Schaeffer with help from a private investigator after a number of visits to Los Angeles, where he unsuccessfully tried to meet her. Bardo is from Arizona.<p>

On the day of the shooting, Bardo went to Schaeffer's apartment once and spoke briefly with her before returning about an hour later and killing her, the state argued. The prosecution claimed Bardo grew to hate Schaeffer when she neglected to answer all but the first of almost 40 letters he sent the co- star of the television series, ''My Sister Sam.''<p>

The defense argued that Bardo planned to kill Schaeffer only before their meeting. When he returned later to speak again to Schaeffer, Bardo believed her behavior was arrogant and like a little brat, and those irrational perceptions triggered an intent to kill, the defense argued.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
A judge found Bardo guilty of first-degree murder. He was sentenced to life in prison without parole.<p>
<p>
