<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>California v. Marks (12/95)</H2>

<P>For several decades, Laura Marks and other women of the Gypsy family offered their psychic services to the people of San Diego. </P>

<P>But San Diego authorities filed criminal charges against six members of the Marks family, charging them with bilking customers of hundreds of thousands of dollars with phony promises about curing headaches and mending broken love  lives. The prosecution alleged that the Marks women illegally took money from their customers with promises they knew they could not fulfill.</P>

<P>One customer claimed he paid the women $675,000 over 11 years to reinvigorate his love life.  None of the predictions came true and he eventually complained to authorities.</P>

<P>The defense contended that Laura Marks, the first family member to stand trial, and the others did not commit grand theft. The attorneys raised concerns about  freedom of religion, the 1st Amendment and the need for society to respect cultural diversity.</P>

<P>The defense argued that the prayers and ceremonies used by the Marks women deserved the same protection as more widespread religions. They noted that the alleged victims voluntarily sought out the Marks' services which included chanting, candle lightings and exorcisms in addition to the more traditional psychic services of palm and card readings.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b> <br>
The trial ended in a hung jury on December 15, 1995.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
