<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>California v. Palm (6/96)</H2>

<P>A retired Navy commander was charged with murder in the shooting of a neighborhood bully.</P>

<P>Prosecutors claimed Daniel Palm was obsessed with ridding the Dictionary Hill community of John Harper that he took the law into his own hands. He was so obsessed that he kept diaries detailing Harper's activities in addition to taking surveillance photographs of Harper outside his house and around the neighborhood.</P>

<P>The state claimed Palm fired 13 shots into an unarmed Harper on November 28, 1995. </P>

<P>The defense contended that Palm acted in self-defense. </P>

<P>Palm testified that he remembered everything up until the time he pulled the trigger for the first time but did not remember anything after that.</P>

<P>What happened before the shooting, Palm said, terrified him. He said he saw Harper drive past his home and was afraid that Harper was coming to seek revenge because he had testified against Harper in a deadly assault trial. (The jury in the trial deadlocked and prosecutors decided to strike a deal with Harper. He  pleaded guilty to reckless driving, a misdemeanor with no jail time. Harper was ordered to pay a $500 fine and placed on probation.)</P>

<P>Palm said a neighbor called to warn him that Harper was driving up the hill toward Palm's house. Palm said he was afraid Harper would burn his house down by throwing a Molotov cocktail. He said he immediately grabbed his .45 semiautomatic, put on some pants and went outside. He said he saw Harper slowly drive down the hill towards another home. Palm feared Harper would harm someone else in the neighborhood. </P>

<P>Palm said he was in a state of panic. He got in his car and drove towards Harper. Then, Harper said he waved at Harper, signaling him to come down the road. Palm said he was terrified but drove up to Harper and decided to try to scare him by brandishing his weapon. He said he flashed his gun at Harper and then Harper said, "you and your family are good as dead."After that, Palm said, he did not remember anything.</P>

<P>He said several things contributed to his growing fear of Harper:  that he had testified against him at the assault trial and he feared Harper wanted to retaliate; that Harper had terrorized Palm and the entire neighborhood; that he believed Harper was a suspect in a suspicious fire that left Harper's wife dead; and that Harper had threatened to burn down other people's houses.</P>

<P>But the prosecution pointed out that Palm pursued Harper and that Harper did not pose a deadly threat to Palm at the time of the shooting. </P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On June 5, 1996, Palm was found guilty of second-degree murder.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
