<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>California v. Simpson (10/95)</H2>

<P>O.J. Simpson, a former football player and celebrity, was accused of stabbing to death his ex-wife Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend, Ronald Goldman. Prosecutors said that after years of abusing his wife, Simpson surprised her at her home on June 12, 1994, overpowered her and slit her throat. Goldman, a waiter, had stopped by to return the eye glasses that her mother had left at a restaurant that evening. He unwittingly interrupted Simpson and was killed, prosecutors said.</P>

<P>No one witnessed the murders, but prosecutors said that blood evidence found at the crime scene, in Simpson's car, and his home, proved that he was the killer. Simpson claimed he was at home when the incident occurred, preparing for a business trip to Chicago. His lawyers said that racist police planted evidence. At the trial, they succeeded in producing witnesses and a taped interview that showed police detective Mark Fuhrman had a deep disdain for African-Americans and that he had lied about it on the witness stand. On the night of the murder, Fuhrman scaled the wall at Simpson's estate and found the bloody glove that was the centerpiece of the prosecution's case. Prosecutors claimed that hair, fiber, footprints and other circumstantial evidence all pointed to Simpson's guilt. But the defense maintained that police contaminated key evidence and rendered it unreliable.</P>

<P><b>Verdict:</b><br>
After nine months of testimony, the jury deliberated for about three hours and acquitted Simpson on October 2, 1995.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
