<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>California v. Tudor and Hookano (8/95)</H2>

<P>The trial of Joseph Tudor and Lance Hookano was more than a routine assault case. It offered a glimpse into the world of competitive surfing and the rivalries between local surfers and competitors and between Malibu surf locals and outsiders. </P>

<P>The incident took place on September 27, 1994, during the Oxbow Longboard World Championship in Malibu. The professional contest actually began a week earlier but was postponed for several days because of poor waves.</P>

<P>Also on the beach that day were numerous non-competitors. The local recreational surfers were aware of the competition. As the competition was preparing to begin, event organizers began making announcements to clear the waters.</P>

<P>Richard Ernsdorf said he had finished a morning of surfing and was drifting south intending to get out of the water. But some people on shore thought he was taking his time and intentionally blocking the start of the competition. Joel Tudor was among the first competitors and soon his father, Joseph, was paddling out in an apparent effort to remove Ernsdorf.</P>

<P>What happened next was in dispute.</P>

<P>Ernsdorf, 44, claimed he was attacked, first by the elder Tudor, 44, and then by Hookano, a 34-year-old world class professional. A videotape showed both men paddling out to Ernsdorf and delivering a series of punches. </P>

<P>But the defense presented witnesses in an attempt to prove self-defense. They suggested that Ernsdorf lashed out first, with one of his swim fins he had taken off his foot, or his hands, after he was asked to leave the water. </P>

<P>Ernsdorf suffered a dislocated shoulder and facial cuts that took 15 stitches to close.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On August 16, 1995, after two days of deliberations, the jury found the defendants guilty of battery and assault with great bodily harm. Tudor and Hookano each were sentenced to three years probation and ordered to perform 300 hours of community service.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
