<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>

<P><H2>DiPaolo v. New York Blood Center and Golinko (12/95)</H2>
In 1984, four-year-old Joey DiPaolo underwent heart surgery and contracted
the AIDS virus as a result of a blood transfusion. At that time, a test to
screen blood for the AIDS virus was several months away from FDA approval. </P></P>

<P>The DiPaolo family sued the New York Blood Center and Dr. Richard Golinko,
their cardiologist. They claimed that the blood center knew the disease posed
a threat to the blood supply but did not properly screen donors or take other
precautions to reduce the risk of providing tainted blood. They also claimed
that Dr. Golinko did not inform them of the benefit of delaying the surgery
until the blood screening test was available.</P></P>

<P>The doctor and the blood center maintained that they were following the
accepted medical standards at the time. </P></P>

<P>The DiPaolos also sued the Downstate Medical Center, where the surgery was
performed, and two other doctors. The medical center and the doctors settled
out of court in 1993, agreeing to pay the DiPaolo family $1.6 million.</P></P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On December 19, 1995, a jury found the New York Blood Center 100% liable for
providing the tainted blood, absolving the three doctors and the medical
center. The DiPaolo family was awarded $1.5 million for pain and suffering to
date; future pain and suffering; loss of earning capacity; and future medical
expenses.</P></P>

<P>After the verdict, lawyers for the defendants argued that under New York
state law, the DiPaolos would not get any of the money awarded to them. They
said that the $1.5 million was offset by the money paid to the family in the
out of court settlement.</P></P>

<P>The DiPaolos' lawyer claimed that the award would come on top of the previous
settlement. Judge Alice Schlesinger said she would hear motions on the
matter.</P></P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
