<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<p><H2>Florida v. Bowles  (7/96)</H2>

A jury in Jacksonville, Florida, had to decide whether Gary Bowles should be sentenced to life in prison without parole or death for the murder of his roommate.<p>

Bowles admitted killing Walter Jammel Hinton in November 1994 by slamming a 40-pound stepping stone onto his head as he slept. The blow didn't kill Hinton, who woke up and struggled for his life. Bowles eventually strangled Hinton, then stuffed toilet paper and a rag into a throat to make sure he was dead.<p>

The state claimed that once Hinton, 42, was dead, Bowles stole his fake Rolex watch, his stereo equipment and his Cadillac. Bowles even had the audacity to bring a woman to sleep at the trailer the next two nights, telling her to be extra quiet because his roommate was asleep in the other room.<p>

The state said Bowles killed Hinton for several reasons: Hinton was gay and Bowles didn't like homosexuals; Bowles was in danger of being kicked out of Hinton's home and he didn't want to go back to living on the streets; and because he needed money and a car.<p>

Although Bowles was a hustler who made money by agreeing to have sex with gay men in return for cash and a place to live, he actually hated homosexuals and blamed them for his problems with women and for an abortion that terminated a former girlfriend's pregnancy in 1985. Prosecutors said two women in the past broke up with Bowles because of his repeated hustling of gay men, so Bowles thought gays were responsible for all of his problems with women.<p>

The defense  contended Bowles was on drugs and drunk at the time of the murder. In his confession, the defendant said, "something just snapped."<p>

Defense attorneys said Bowles started drinking and sniffing glue when he was 10 years old. He ran away from home several years later and his family had not seen much of him in the past 20 years. The defense presented evidence that Bowles had an exceptionally difficult childhood that was full of beatings at the hands of two different stepfathers. <p>

The defense won a major pretrial ruling when the judge ruled the state could not present allegations that Bowles was suspected of the murders of six gay men in Florida, Georgia and Maryland.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
The jury recommended that Bowles be sentenced to death.<p>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
