<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Florida v. Gayle (1/96)</H2>

<P>Audrey Gayle was fatally shot as she and her husband were driving home from a prayer meeting on April 13, 1995.</P>

<P>Matthew Gayle told police that an unidentified robber with a gun forced him to stop the car and hand over his wallet. The robber, he said, then shot his wife. </P>

<P>Police, however, were skeptical of Gayle's story. And, a few days later, began receiving information that Gayle had been looking for several months for someone to help him kill his wife. Gayle was eventually arrested and charged with first-degree murder. </P>

<P>During the trial, the prosecution contended that Gayle wanted his wife dead so he could pursue an old love interest and collect on a $150,000 life insurance policy. The state said Gayle did not want to divorce his wife because child support for the couple's two young children would cost too much money. Gayle already was paying $300 a month to his former wife for child support. </P>

<P>One of the state's main witnesses was Eugene Johnson, a former roommate of Gayle's brother. Johnson testified that Gayle asked him numerous times to kill his wife. Johnson also said Gayle told him that he was getting a life insurance policy for $100,000 and would give $10,000 to Johnson. </P>

<P>The defense countered that Gayle was only friends with his old girlfriend, and that Johnson owed Gayle money and wanted him dead. </P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On January 12, 1996, a jury convicted Gayle of first-degree murder and conspiracy to commit murder. He was sentenced to life in prison.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
