<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Florida v. Puzio</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Florida v. Puzio (Penalty Phase)</H2>

<P>David Puzio, a tattoo artist, was convicted of first-degree murder in the
deaths of Kelly Rae Cahill and Marleen Chillemi. The two women, who
were thinking of getting tattoos, met Puzio and four friends, crammed
into Chillemi's car and drove to Pompano Beach to purchase marijuana.
On their way, Puzio told Cahill to pull over. Puzio claimed that he did not
remember what happened after they pulled over. One of the passengers,
Elias Nieves, testified that Puzio pulled out a pistol, shot Chillemi and
Cahill and left the women on the ground and sped off. The prosecution
claimed that Puzio killed the women because he wanted to rob them. The
defense claimed it was Nieves who shot the women. </P>

<P>In the penalty phase of the trial, the prosecution argued that Puzio should face the death penalty because the murders were committed during a robbery. Out for financial gain, Puzio killed in cold blood, prosecutor Brian Cavanagh said. The defense focused on Puzio's age. He was only 16 years old, lawyer Steven Hammer said. A psychologist testified that Puzio suffered from emotional problems, related to depression, being abused as a child and his parents' alcoholism and divorce. </P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><BR>
On Dec. 18, 1996, Judge Paul Backman accepted the jury's recommendation that Puzio be sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole. </P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
