<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Florida v. Trice (6/95)</H2>

<P>Charles Trice Jr., a former Florida state trooper, was charged with murder in the shooting death of his estranged wife, Darla, on April 24, 1994.</P>

<P>The prosecution presented numerous witnesses to show that Darla Trice feared her husband and who said that she told them many times that he threatened to kill her. Trice had been previously arrested for spousal abuse but was free after posting $30,000 bail. The murder occurred while he was out on bail.</P>

<P>Trice contended that he shot his wife after she attacked him with a knife and defense attorneys argued that he be acquitted on grounds of self-defense. Trice told detectives that he was on his knees hiding inside a closet when he grabbed his gun and shot his wife as she attempted to stab him again.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><BR>
On June 27, 1995, a jury found Trice guilty of first-degree murder, burglary with an assault or battery on a person and violation of a domestic violence injunction. He received a  mandatory life sentence, eligible for parole after 25 years.</P>
