<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Georgia v. Blackwell (6/95)</H2>

<P>Ronald Blackwell, a paramedic captain in DeKalb County, Georgia, 
was charged with involuntary manslaughter, aggravated assault, 
reckless conduct and simple battery for hastening the death of a 
patient.</P>

<P>Blackwell led an emergency medical service team early in the 
morning hours of September 4, 1994, to the home of David Chen, 
who was accidentally shot in the head by his wife at close range 
with a high-powered hunting rifle.  Determining that Chen would 
not survive, Blackwell ordered CPR stopped, and in full view of 
witnesses, allegedly covered Chen's mouth and nose. Chen died
minutes later.</P>

<P>Blackwell denied facilitating Chen's death, claiming he used his 
hands to determine whether Chen was breathing.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><br> 
On June 16, 1995, a jury acquitted Blackwell.</P>
