<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Georgia v. Carrizales (11/94)</H2>

<P>Dr. Eva Carrizales was charged with hastening the death of terminally ill Omar Jimenez by holding the 39-day-old baby's mouth shut to smother him and pressing on the carotid artery to cut off blood flow to his brain.</P>

<P>The state argued that Carrizales was frustrated that she couldn't save the baby's life but could control the time of death. Several nurses testified to seeing Carrizales hold the child's mouth closed on October 16, 1993.</P>

<P>Carrizales did not assert a mercy-killing defense, and denied doing anything to speed the child's death. She insisted the nurses misinterpreted her actions as she cradled the infant in the hours before she pronounced his death.  Carrizlaes said she was checking for a pulse when a nurse saw her place her fingers on the baby's neck.  Several defense experts claimed Carrizales' care of  the infant was entirely proper, and that the child was clinically dead when the alleged smothering and pressure on the artery were said to have occurred. </P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On November 4, 1994, the jury announced it was hopelessly deadlocked --  seven in favor of acquittal and five in favor of conviction.</P>
