<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Georgia v. Chapel (9/95)</H2>

<P>Michael Chapel, a former Gwinnett County police officer, was charged with the April 15, 1993 murder of Emogene Thompson.</P>

<P>The state charged Chapel killed Thompson after luring her to a muffler shop to rob her of $7,000 in cash. Police never found Thompson's purse and money, nor the .38-caliber gun used to kill her.</P>

<P>Chapel had met Thompson several weeks earlier when she called police to report that $7,000 had been stolen from her trailer park in Sugar Hill. Thompson, a grandmother in her early 50s, had inherited $14,000 from the proceeds of a friend's life insurance policy. She hid the money in her home.</P>

<P>Chapel responded to the burglary call. He met with Thompson and allegedly concurred in her assessment that her son may have been responsible for the theft. Chapel, however, did not log the call or file a report . The state alleged that Chapel intentionally failed to document the robbery because he was planning to steal the remainder of Thompson's money.</P>

<P>On April 15, 1993, Chapel told Thompson that he had recovered some of the money. He asked her to meet him and bring the remaining money so he could compare serial numbers.</P>

<P>During the trial, DNA experts testified that a bloodstain on the seat of Chapel's squad car matched Thompson's blood. A DNA defense expert countered that the tests could not be interpreted.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><BR>
On September 8, 1995, a jury convicted Chapel of one count each of murder, felony murder, armed robbery and possession of a firearm during the commission of a felony. He was sentenced to two consecutive life terms in prison plus five years -- the maximum sentence allowed by law short of the death penalty.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
