<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<P><h2>Georgia v. Joyner (8/96)</h2>

Georgia businessman <a href=/report/joyner2.html>Lewis Joyner</a> was accused of murder in the deaths of wife and mistress.<p>

Joyner admitted killing his wife of 15 years in November 1995, but claimed it was self-defense. He said Ruby Joyner killed the other woman and then attacked him after learning about his alleged affair with Halima Jones.<p>

Lewis and Ruby Joyner had been married for about 15 years at the time of her death. In the early 1990s, the Joyners moved from New York to the Atlanta area. They purchased and operated the successful Gooch Moving and Storage Service. The Joyners and their business were the subject of a Black Enterprise magazine article in February 1994. <p>

"Our slogan is Pamper Plus -- going the extra mile to satisfy our customers," Joyner told the magazine. <p>

Several months later, however, they sold the business. Later that year, Joyner was in bankruptcy court and faced lawsuits claiming he owed more than $60,000 in credit card and business debts. He also was arrested on drug charges later that year.<p>

There were no assertions that the Joyners had any marital problems --other that the defense's claim that Joyner was having an affair with Jones, a school administrator and teacher.<p>

Jones was separated from the father of her two children. Shortly before her death, she and the children moved out of the apartment of her former boyfriend John Dunbar. Officials said they were told that Jones quit living with Dunbar because of domestic problems. <p>

<b>The Women Disappear</b><br>
The two women were last seen alive on November 15, 1995, after telling friends they were going shopping.<p>

The day after the killings, Joyner called Dunbar to ask him if he had seen his wife. Dunbar then started looking for Jones, and reported her missing that same day. Dunbar told police that he repeatedly urged Joyner to call the police to report his wife missing.<p>

Authorities became suspicious of Joyner when they discovered he had flown to New York City a fews days later without contacting police about his wife's disappearance.<p>

While in New York, Joyner called the Atlanta police several times and promised to return. Published reports credited Joyner's attorney, Steven Sadow, with saying that Joyner left Atlanta because he was afraid that if he went to the police he would have to reveal information implicating himself in drug activity.<p>

After arrest warrants were issued for Joyner in connection with the deaths, several Atlanta area police officers went to New York City to search for him.<p>

Police also searched Joyner's Peachtree City home and a rented storage space at least three times while he was in New York City, and after he returned home. The police seized cocaine, scales, packing supplies, substances used to dilute cocaine, ledgers and computers. The searches resulted in charges against Joyner of two counts of possession of cocaine with intent to distribute and one count of possession of marijuana with intent to distribute. Police have speculated that the proceeds from his drug sales were intended to be used to pay off Joyner's debts. (The trial judge barred the prosecution from introducing the drug evidence during the murder trial.)<p>

<b>Bodies Found at Airport</b><br>
The two bodies were found on November 21, 1995, in Jones' mini-van, which was parked in a long-term lot at Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport. A security guard making a routine check of the lot spotted the bodies on the floor in the back of the van. The back seats had been removed.<p>

Jones had been shot once in the head (neither the bullet nor the gun that killed her has been recovered). Ruby Joyner had been beaten about the head -- possibly with a blunt object -- and strangled. Both bodies were covered with a black comforter.<p>

After the bodies were discovered, police went to talk to Joyner's Atlanta friend Jeffrey Lester. Lester said he had received a call from Joyner in New York on November 20, 1996. Joyner allegedly asked Lester to meet him in Newark, New Jersey, which Lester did that night. Joyner told Lester he would return to Atlanta in a couple of days, but he was so upset about his wife's disappearance that he wanted to be near his family.<p>

Lester claimed Joyner told him what happened on the day of the shootings.<p>

Jones and Ruby Joyner -- who had been using cocaine -- called Joyner and asked him to go for a drive with them near the airport. Ruby Joyner found out about here husband's affair with Jones and she shot Jones in the van. Joyner jumped out of the parked van, and thought his wife was going to shoot him. They fought over the gun and he shot her. <p>

Lester said Joyner asked him to go to the crime scene because he had left his hat and beeper and his wife's jacket in the area, along the Camp Creek Parkway. Joyner also allegedly told Lester that he had put the gun someplace where no one would find it.<p>

Joyner was arrested on November 29, 1995, after a roof-top struggle with New York City housing police. He eventually waived extradition to Georgia, and pleaded not guilty to the murder charges.<P>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
On August 28, 1996, an Atlanta jury returned a split verdict. Joyner was convicted of murder, felony murder and aggravated murder in the death of his wife. He was acquitted of charges that he killed Jones. Joyner was sentenced to life in prison.
<p>

<p>
