<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<P><H2>Georgia v. Smith(7/96)</H2>

Sexual assault in America is reaching epidemic levels.<p>

There are more than 100,000 rapes each year -- one every five minutes, according to the FBI. And that figure is misleadingly low. Many rapes and assaults go unreported because the victims are too traumatized, afraid or humiliated to reveal what happened to them. And those who do come forward often are reluctant to have their faces shown on camera or have their names revealed.<p>

But in Atlanta, four women went public. They met each other in the aftermath of the attacks. Three of the women claimed a man broke into their homes late at night and either tried or succeeded in raping them. A fourth woman said she was dragged into an abandoned home and raped.<p>

Anton Jermaine Smith, 23, was charged with the rapes of Kay Cross, Andrea Goode, and Lynda Denham, and the burglary of Lavon Skyers.

The prosecution contended that Smith's first victim was Cross, who was allegedly raped on May 15, 1995. Smith allegedly raped Goode on June 10, 1995. Just hours later Smith was arrested, accused of climbing into a window at Skyers' home. Skyers says she was able to fight him off because she woke up before her attacker got a weapon.<p>

Smith was mistakenly released from jail on October 19, 1995. During a hearing in September, prosecutors failed to inform the judge of the rape charges Smith faced -- the judge just was told about the burglary case. Smith was released on $10,000 bond. Less than three weeks later, he was arrested for the rape of Denham.<p>

During the trial, the victims identified Smith as their assailant. Prosecutors also introduced DNA evidence linking Smith to some of the crimes.<p>

The defense contended the victims were mistaken about their identifications of Smith and challenged the accuracy of the scientific evidence. But the defense did not try to explain why Smith admitted having contact with three of the four women on the nights they claimed he assaulted them. Smith claimed he sold drugs and read the Bible with Cross on the night she was attacked. He admitted being in Skyers' house, but he told police he didn't know what he was doing there. He also admitted having sex with Denham, but claimed he paid her $20.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
Smith was found guilty on July 12, 1996. He was sentenced to three consecutive life terms.<p>
<p>
