<H2>Georgia v. Strickland (5/96)</H2>

<P>In a pre-trial hearing, a special jury was asked to determine whether Danny Strickland was competent to stand trial for the murder of his father.</P>

<P>Police found the decomposing corpse of Willis Daniel Strickland Sr. in his Savannah home on October 31, 1994. On searching the house, police found handwritten notes, purportedly made by Danny Strickland, that prosecutors contended reflected plans to dispose of the body.</P>

<P>After his arrest, Strickland was ordered to undergo psychiatric testing. Dr. Donald Gibson of the Central State Hospital determined that he was incompetent to stand trial and was not responsible at the time of the murder.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On May 2, 1996, the jury determined that Strickland was not competent to stand trial.</P>
