<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Hansen v. Curaflex Health Services (6/95)</H2>

<P>Marc Hansen, a former employee of Curaflex Health Services Inc., sued the company for employment discrimination, saying he was fired because general manager Daniel Skidmore learned he was HIV positive. Hansen was hired in September 1992 as an office manager in Curaflex's Fort Lauderdale office and fired seven weeks later.</P>

<P>Witnesses offered conflicting testimony during the three-day trial, and frequently contradicted their own depositions and affidavits, leaving jurors wondering whom to believe.</P>

<P>Hansen's lawyer, William Porter, argued that Curaflex had a history of discrimination. Curaflex's lawyer, Ronald Rosengarten argued that Hansen was fired because he wasn't cut out for a high-profile sales position. He stressed employee comments that Hansen was "unpolished" and "loud" around the office.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
A Broward County jury ruled on June 16, 1995, that Curaflex Health Services did not discriminate against Hansen.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
