<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<p><h2>In Re Custody of Hennessy Children (5/95)</h2>
In one of the first cases of its kind in the country, a  homosexual sought custody of her deceased partner's three children. The case involved Pamela Hennessy against the children's grandmother Patricia Bartel.<p>

The boys' mother Michelle Notz Hennessy was fatally stabbed in April of 1994 in her Buffalo, New York, home. The home was heavily damaged by a fire that probably was set to cover the attack. The murder never was solved.<p>

Several weeks later, after a judge learned that Pamela Hennessy was a suspect in the murder, he ordered the boys placed in their grandmother's custody. <p>

The custody battle soon began.<p>

It was while Pamela Hennessy was living with the boys' mother that the children were conceived through artificial insemination. The two women also went through a marriage ceremony several years earlier, and Michelle changed her name from Notz to Hennessy.<p>

The relationship ended in 1990 but Pamela Hennessy maintained her involvement with the children and occasionally provided financial help to their mother as well as moving the family into a home she owned.<p>

Pamela Hennessy, who operated a lesbian bar, said during the trial that if she was given custody of the boys, she would sell the bar, move to the suburbs and open a different type of business.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
Under a settlement,  Patricia Bartel and Pamela Hennessy agreed to be co-guardians of the children. The children will live mainly with their grandmother, and with Hennessy on alternate weekends and Wednesdays, holidays and during summer vacation. <p>
<p>
