<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Jocius v. Jocius (6/96)</H2>

<P>In January, three Milwaukee children took the unusual step of writing to the family court judge who had granted their parents' divorce. They asked the judge to sever their ties to their abusive father.</P>

<P>"We have come to a decision about our father and would like to know if you can help," the letter began. "Since the divorce in 1990 alot has happened. Our father has been back in prison several times and using drugs, alcohol and just being stupid.</P>

<P>"He has lived with us several times since the divorce. We have all tried to make things work, but nothing changes him. Our mother has been diagnosed with panic disorder, agoraphobia, depression, and too much stress. She feels like she has to keep trying to work things out with dad because she is afraid of him. He was abusive toward all of us during the marriage, more mentally than physically, but now we are all paying for it," the children wrote. "Us kids have decided that we don't want anything to do with our dad and we want to know if his rights can be taken away? We are 16, 14 and 7 now and we feel very clear about the decision."</P>

<P>Perhaps sensing the children's urgency, frustration and fear, Judge Dominic Amato acted quickly. (The judge who handled the divorce had died and the case was assigned to Judge Amato). He appointed a "guardian ad litem," attorney Hazel Washington, to investigate the allegations of physical and mental abuse reported by the children and, if substantiated, to represent the children's interests in a court proceeding.</P>

<P>Washington's investigation revealed that there, in fact, existed a history of abuse by Mark Jocius of his children, Matthew, Jennifer and Bryan, and ex-wife Victoria. There was the time Mark took his 16-year-old Matthew to a bar and smoked marijuana with him. He also taken his 7-year-old Bryan to a bar and has reportedly threatened to kill his ex-wife and the children.</P>

<P>Judge Amato issued a temporary restraining order and ordered Jocius to stay away from his former wife and  children. However, at a subsequent hearing, Victoria Jocius testified that he had made threatening phone calls to her and the children from jail in violation of the temporary restraining order. The judge then ordered a permanent injunction which will remain in effect for two years.</P>

<P>Jocius has been in and out of jail through the years (including as recently as early April, 1996) for forgery and writing bad checks as well as parole violations.</P>

<P>During a hearing in April, he said, "There was a lot of dysfunction because of alcohol abuse, but I've never left them. I've tried numerous alcoholic treatment programs without success. I never turned my back on them. I love them. I'm proud of them for stepping forward to protect themselves. I still love them. I will always love them. I don't want to lose them."</P>

<P>Washington, the children's guardian, then took an unusual and unprecedented step in this case.</P>

<P>Rather than terminate Mark Jocius's parental rights outright  (something that is not unheard of), the children wanted to terminate Jocius's visitation rights but not his obligation to pay child support. The children also did not want to lose inheritance rights. (Under current law, when parental rights are terminated, the slate is wiped clean. Not only are there no visitation rights but there is also no obligation to pay child support and the child loses inheritance rights.)</P>

<P>During the trial, Josius testified about his life and feelings towards his children. He said he only wanted what is best for his children, and praised his former wife for doing everything she could to help the children and his relationship with her. He told the court that he was abused as a child and  admitted having an alcohol and drug problem. But he said he never physically abused his own children.</P>

<P>A court-appointed psychologist who examined the children said it would be detrimental for them to have contact with their father "under circumstances where his behavior can not be modified."</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
The judge severed the ties between Jocius and the two older children. For the youngest child, now eight years old, the split was indefinite. The decision means no visitation or any other rights that go along with fatherhood. Jocius, however, must support his children until they are 18 years old.</P>
