<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Johnson v. New York Health & Hospitals Corp. (2/96)</H2>

<P>When a pregnant doctor was found raped and murdered in a New York City hospital on January 8, 1989, then-Mayor Edward Koch called the death, "the number one case to be solved in New York."</P>

<P>Authorities quickly arrested Steven Smith for the murder of Dr. Kathryn Hinnant Johnson.  Smith, a homeless man with a history of psychiatric problems, was convicted and eventually sentenced to life in prison.</P>

<P>Dr. Hinnant's estate then sued the hospital where she worked for wrongful death and negligence. </P>

<P>Smith was a patient at Bellevue Hospital in the weeks before Dr. Hinnant's death. He was released on December 27, 1988. But instead of leaving, he made himself a home in the hospital.</P>

<P>He stole surgical clothes, a stethoscope and employee identification cards, which enabled him to roam the facility. He even had started sleeping on the 22nd floor of Bellevue behind some machinery in an engineering closet that was not monitored by hospital security.</P>

<P>The plaintiffs accused the New York City Health and Hospitals Corp., which operates Bellevue, of failing to keep the premises safe and secure. They maintained that the corporation had actual and constructive knowledge of Smith's whereabouts because he kept showing up at the hospital. He even was arrested for stealing a hypodermic needle and quartz clock from a 17th floor doctor's office just eight days before the murder. (The charges were later dropped.) They also contended that the hospital was negligent for releasing Smith.</P>

<P>The defense argued the hospital corporation was not liable because it was not responsible for Smith's actions after he was discharged from the hospital. Defense attorney Joshua Pollack contended the hospital properly treated and released Smith in December 1988. Pollack maintained Smith did not exhibit any homicidal tendencies during his treatment. </P>

<P>The hospital contended that it was not practical to expect Bellevue Hospital security to apprehend every potentially dangerous person who enters the facility.  The defense maintained that hospital security was adequate, not perfect.</P>

<P>The case took nearly six years to come to trial because the hospital initially claimed that Dr. Hinnant was an employee of the Health and Hospitals Corp.  If that was the case, civil litigation would have been limited to a workers' compensation claim. The plaintiffs claimed the doctor was an employee of  New York University Medical Center who worked at Bellevue Hospital. Dr. Hinnant was an assistant professor pathology at the  university. A New York appeals court ruled Dr. Hinnant was not an employee of Bellevue.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On February 26, 1996, a jury found that the hospital was not responsible for Dr. Hinnant's death.</P>
