<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Judge Vaughn Competency Hearing (5/95)</H2>

<P>Fulton (Georgia) State Court Judge Dorothy Vaughn faced 
disciplinary hearings based on five complaints filed with the 
Judicial Qualifications Commission.
The complaints -- four filed by attorneys and one by a litigant -- alleged professional 
incompetence, rude and hostile conduct toward those appearing 
before her, and absenteeism from the bench.
According to the 
complaints, Judge Vaughn acted incompetently by forfeiting bonds, 
issuing bench warrants and having defendants jailed, failing to 
grant jury trials upon request, and in one case forcing a 
defendant to plead guilty without the presence of his attorney.</P>

<P>The judge maintained she had acted properly and did not violate 
any judicial canons. She did acknowledge that her mannerisms and 
facial expressions might have inadvertently conveyed hostility.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><br>
The Judicial Qualifications Commission unanimously recommended 
that Judge Vaughn immediately be removed from office, calling her 
abusive and incompetent. In a harshly worded 37-page report, 
issued on May 26, 1995, the commission found that Judge Vaughn 
had violated the Canons of Judicial Ethics and was unfit to hold 
office.</P>

<P>The commission wrote that Judge Vaughn's "proven conduct can only be
described as a flagrant abuse and/or misuse of the power and prestige of
judicial office in a (sic) unsuccessful attempt to mask a professional
incompetence rarely seen in judges of her age and experience."</P>

<P>The Georgia Supreme Court accepted the commission's recommendation. Judge Vaughn was removed from office in October 1995.</P>
