<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Kurgan v. Rollerblade Inc. (12/95)</H2>

<P>In 1991, Kenneth Kurgan, 19, was skating to the Paradise Valley Mall in Phoenix on his new pair of Rollerblade in-line skates. He stumbled over a gravel median, flipped over the curb and slammed headfirst into an oncoming truck. He was not wearing a helmet or any other protective equipment.</P>

<P>Kurgan suffered an open skull fracture and is permanently brain damaged. Paralyzed on one side, he is barely able to carry on a conversation and doctors say he will require constant medical supervision for the rest of his life.</P>

<P>Kurgan's parents say that at the time of the injury Rollerblade literature did not adequately warn users to wear a helmet and other protective gear. While the product handbook included the admonition to "wear protective safety equipment," other Rollerblade promotional material represented that the product could be safely used by persons of all ages without the use of a helmet, Kurgan's lawyers allege. </P>

<P>Kurgan's lawyers also claimed that the skates their son purchased were defective and unreasonably dangerous.</P>

<P>The Kurgans sued for monetary damages to provide for their son's needs for the rest of his life.</P>

<P>Rollerblade denied it was liable for Kurgan's accident. It maintained that the skates are responsibly marketed with adequate warnings and are not defective. Company lawyers said Kurgan freely chose to skate without such equipment and bears responsibility for his own injuries.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On December 6, 1995, a jury found in favor of the defendants.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
