<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Mahlum v. Dow Chemical (10/95)</H2>

<P>Like thousands of women, Charlotte Mahlum claimed her health problems were due to faulty silicone breast implants. Mahlum received the implants in 1985 after undergoing a double mastectomy. When a surgeon removed them several years later, she claimed the devices had ruptured and a surgeon was unable to remove all the silicone that had seeped into surrounding tissue.<br></P>
Mahlum, a 46-year-old resident of Nevada, sued Dow Chemical and Dow Corning in 1993, alleging the implants caused serious health problems including neurological diseases.</P>

<P>But by the time the case went to trial, Dow Corning was no longer a defendant. The company sought bankruptcy protection in May 1995, saying it lacked the resources to fight litigation filed on behalf of thousands of women who blame implants for health problems. Dow Corning is co-owned by Dow Chemical, based in Midland, Mich., and Corning Inc. of Corning, N.Y.</P>

<P>A federal judge ruled in September 1995 that the cases against Dow Chemical and Corning could proceed despite the Chapter 11 filing.</P>

<P>Dow Chemical is the defendant or co-defendant in more than 13,000 breast implant lawsuits. But before this case, the only other claim against it to reach trial was in Texas, where a jury ordered the company to pay 20 percent of a $5.2 million damage award to a woman who claimed injury from breast implants. But that decision was thrown out by the trial judge.</P>

<P>During the trial, the lawyers for Mahlum and her husband, Marvin, contended that Dow Chemical was as responsible for the safety of implants as Dow Corning, because the company performed studies on silicone for Dow Corning. They also said that Dow Chemical scientists were aware of the potential dangers of silicone.</P>

<P>Dow Chemical lawyers argued that the company never made or distributed silicone breast implants. They claimed they were made by Dow Corning, and Dow Chemical couldn't be held responsible for the actions of another company.</P>

<P>The company also presented evidence of recent statistical studies that failed to provide a link between silicone implants and immune system illnesses. Mahlum's lawyers questioned the methodology of the studies.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On October 29, 1995, a jury found for Charlotte Mahlum and ordered Dow Chemical to pay her $3.9 million in compensatory damages. The jury also awarded $200,000 in compensatory damages to Marvin Mahlum.</P>

<P>The jury found that Dow Chemical "fraudulently concealed" the dangers of silicone and "substantially assisted" Dow Corning Inc. in testing materials used in breast implants.</P>

<P>The jury subsequently ordered Dow Chemical to pay $10 million in punitive damages, bringing the total damages to $14.1 million.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
