<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Massachusetts v. McIntyre (6/96)</H2>

<P>On the evening of January 10, 1995, John McIntyre brought his girlfriend, bleeding from a chest wound to the hospital. When police and hospital personnel asked Meredith Coppola whether her boyfriend had stabbed her, she said no.</P>

<P>She died 20 minutes later.</P>

<P>McIntyre, 25, told police at the hospital that he and Coppola, 18, were together in his car before she was stabbed but that he was not  responsible for her death. He told police he left his car to buy some marijuana. And when he returned, he found Coppola bleeding.</P>

<P>But <A href=/report/coppola.html>prosecutors</A> contended McIntyre was lying, and charged him with first-degree murder.</P>

<P>During the trial, several witnesses testified that McIntyre and Coppola got into a fight shortly before her death. McIntyre also went to a friend's house and washed blood off a knife shortly after the murder. An expert witness testified that fibers found on a knife police said was the murder weapon were consistent with fibers from a sweater Coppola was wearing when she was stabbed. The defense argued that Coppola's dying declaration cleared McIntytre.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On June 26, 1996, a jury found McIntyre guilty of first-degree murder. He faces a mandatory life sentence.</P>
