<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Michigan v. Price (2/96)</H2>

<P>Detroit police officer Glenn Price was charged with second-degree murder and a felony weapons charge in connection with the July 22, 1994, shooting death of 10-year-old Freddie Vela.</P>

<P>The shooting occurred after Price -- who was off-duty at the time -- was drinking with a friend David Kennedy at a topless bar. Price left the bar with the understanding that Kennedy would follow him home. But while leaving, Price crashed his truck into a utility pole. Unable to pry the truck loose,  Price transferred the items from his truck to Kennedy's, then returned to the bar. He then went back to his truck and accidentally set off the alarm.</P>

<P>At this point, John Collins, a resident of the neighborhood who admittedly had been drinking, went over to Price's truck and tried to disconnect the blaring alarm. Price and Collins got into an argument and    Price drew his department-issued weapon. </P>

<P>Price said the weapon accidentally fired, killing Vela who was standing about 20 yards away.</P>

<P>There was no doubt that Price did not intent to shoot Vela. But the prosecution claimed that Price, an eight-year police veteran who was trained in the use of firearms, knew that pulling his gun and firing it in a residential neighborhood was extremely dangerous. The state argued he was guilty of second-murder for willfully and wantonly creating a situation likely to result in death or great bodily harm.</P>

<P>The defense argued that no laws were broken because the shooting clearly was accidental. In addition, the defense said Price was right to draw his weapon because he had a legal duty to try and stop Collins from committing a crime or potential crime with the truck.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On February 7, 1996, a jury found Price guilty of second-degree murder. Price was sentenced to 10-15 years in prison. He also was sentenced to a mandatory two years in prison for using a firearm during the commission of a felony.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
