<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Michigan v. Welch (4/96)</H2>

<P>The incident stunned a nation. A woman plunges to her death in the Detroit River as a crowd of onlookers stands idly by as she is attacked.</P>

<P>Martell Welch was charged with murder in the August 19, 1995, drowning death of Deletha Word, who drowned after jumping into the river after Welch beat her up following a traffic accident.</P>

<P>The altercation began when Welch and Word were involved in a minor fender bender in the early morning hours while driving back from Belle Isle, a popular island park in the river between the United States and Canada.  Just before they got to the bridge to return to the mainland, Word's car hit Welch. </P>

<P>Several witnesses described a brutal beating that ended with Welch threatening Word with a tire jack and saying he was going to use it to "beat her brains out."</P>

<P>Prosecutors argued that Welch was guilty of  murder even though he did not push Word from the bridge and was standing several feet away when she jumped. They contended Word was so scared of Welch that she  jumped to escape being beaten again.</P>

<P>The defense case focused on two key pieces of information in the medical examiner's report. Word had traces of the hallucinogenic drug PCP or angel dust in her system at the time of her death. The defense suggested that she may have thought she could fly when she jumped off the bridge.  The defense also argued Word's body only had minor scratches and bruises, contradicting claims that Welch brutally beat her up.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On April 29, 1996, a jury convicted Welch of second-degree murder. He was sentenced to 16 to 40 years in prison.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
