<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Mickler v. Southeastern Freight Lines (3/96)</H2>

<P>Belinda Mickler and her three young children sued for the alleged wrongful death of her husband who was killed in a motor vehicle accident involving a Southeastern Freight Lines truck. </P>

<P>Mickler sought damages for her husband's pain and suffering prior to his death and for the costs of his funeral and burial. The defendants denied any liability and claimed the fatal collision was the result of an unavoidable accident or sudden emergency, possibly caused by Mickler's negligence. </P>

<P>This is what happened.</P>

<P>During the early morning hours of October 20, 1993, Reginald Mickler parked his pickup truck in an emergency lane on Interstate 75, just south of the entrance from Georgia Highway 42, some 50 miles south of Atlanta. The owner of a small construction company, he was transporting materials in his truckbed. It was not known why he had stopped his truck, but the truck company suggested Mickler had failed to properly secure his load and had to stop to retrieve an object that had tumbled onto the road. </P>

<P>A Southeastern Freight Lines tractor-trailer collided with the left rear portion of Mickler's truck, scraped along the side of the pickup, passing it, then struck and climbed the guard rail. When it finally came to rest, it burst into flames.</P>

<P>Mickler's body was found behind his vehicle. He was dead at the scene. An eyewitness observed Mickler before impact and testified that he appeared to see the approaching tractor-trailer and tried to run away. </P>

<P>The truck driver, Mike Hall, denied allegations that he was speeding  or driving in the emergency lane. He said that as he pulled abreast of the pickup, his steering jerked sharply to the right and locked, causing him to swerve into Mickler. (A jury acquitted Hall of involuntary manslaughter in the case.)</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
The jury found the trucking company liable and awarded $5.2 million in damages.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
