<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Missouri v. Feeney</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif"
ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Missouri v. Feeney</H2>

<P>Jon Feeney, a former high school science teacher, was charged with three counts of first-degree murder for the bludgeoning death of his wife and six-year-old son and the strangulation of his 18-month-old daughter. 
Feeney said on the night of the killings he was about 100 miles away from his home, where the incident occurred, attending a teachers conference. Prosecutors presented a timeline that they said proved Feeney had the opportunity to return from his hotel and commit the crimes. They presented evidence to suggest that Feeney had stocked up on life insurance to benefit financially from the murders. They also attacked Feeney's character, calling several woman who said they had affairs with him. Defense attorney Shawn Askinosie questioned the integrity of the state's investigation and hammered away at the lack of physical evidence linking Feeney to the murders.</P>


<P><B>The Verdict</B><BR>
On Sunday, Oct. 6, 1996, after five hours of deliberations, the jury acquitted Feeney.
