<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Missouri v. Revelle (2/96)</H2>

<P>George Revelle appeared to have it all: a successful banking career, a nice home in an exclusive community, a wife and two children. But Revelle's world came crashing down in the early morning hours of  September 28, 1994, when his wife was killed in the couple's home.</P>

<P>Revelle told police that one or two masked men broke into the couple's home in Fremont Hills, a country club community south of Springfield, and shot his wife in the head during a bungled attempt to force him to get them money from his bank. At the time, Revelle was chief  financial officer and executive vice president of the Ozark Bank.</P>

<P>But authorities soon became suspicious of his story. They discovered that Revelle was deeply in debt and had taken out a $500,000 life insurance policy on his wife several months before the shooting. </P>

<P>The shooting also sparked an FBI investigation into suspected extortion and possible discrepancies in the Ozark Bank's finances. Revelle was subsequently indicted. In June 1995, he pleaded guilty to embezzling or misapplying more than $53,000 from the bank and was sentenced to 27 months in prison.</P>

<P>Revelle continued to maintain his innocence during the murder trial. He told the jury about the intruders and the alleged extortion attempt.</P>

<P>But prosecutors argued that Revelle couldn't be counted on to tell the truth. Among other witnesses, an alarm company technician testified that Revelle's account of house his house alarm went off on the night of the shootings was not possible. The prosecution also argued that Revelle stole money from the bank after the home he and his wife built went $150,000 over budget.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On February 13, 1996, a jury found Revelle guilty of first-degree murder. The jury recommended that he be sentenced to life in prison.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
