<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Montana v. Lilburn (3/95)</H2>

<P>In a case pitting the purported constitutional rights of protesters against the rights of hunters, John Lilburn was charged with hunter harassment in connection with his actions on March 13, 1990.</P>

<P>Lilburn, a 41-year-old animal rights activist, allegedly stood in front of hunter Hal Slemmer as Slemmer attempted to shoot a bison just outside of Yellowstone National Park.</P>

<P>The state claimed Lilburn's actions violated Montana's hunter harassment statute. Lilburn argued that his actions were protected by the First Amendment free speech rights and that the harassment statute was unjust.</P>

<P>Lilburn was originally tried and convicted in 1992. However, the charge was dismissed when a judge found the harassment statute to be unconstitutional. The Montana Supreme Court then reversed the ruling and ordered a new trial.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><BR>
Lilburn was found guilty on March 28, 1995. He received a 30-day sentence, suspended with the provision that he undergo 40 hours of community service. He also was ordered to pay an administrative fee of $15.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
