<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>New Mexico v. House (5/95)</H2>

<P>Gordon House stood trial a third time for vehicular homicide in 
connection with the deaths of four people in a car accident. On 
Christmas Eve, 1992, House was driving up to 90 miles per hour in 
the wrong lane of Interstate 40, west of Albuquerque, when he 
crashed into an oncoming car.  House was charged with vehicular 
homicide, drunk driving, great bodily injury and reckless driving.</P>

<P>The state argued that House never hit the brakes when he saw the 
car driven by Paul Cravens because he had been drinking for 
several hours before the accident. The defense argued that House 
was suffering a severe migraine headache which impaired his 
physical abilities and judgment. The migraine restricted the blood 
flow to House's brain, so even if  he did have a high blood 
alcohol content, he wouldn't feel the alcohol's effects as much as 
he would if his blood flow was not restricted. </P>

<P>The two previous trials ended in deadlocked juries. The fact that 
House, a native of the Navajo Nation, stood trial a third time was 
seen by some in the Navajo Nation as racist.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><br>
A jury found House guilty on all counts on May 26, 1995. He was 
sentenced to 22 years in prison.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
