<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>New Mexico v. Smith (12/95)</H2>

<P>William Smith was accused in the 1977 murders of two women, Kerry Tulton, 22, and Leslie MacDonnell, 18. He allegedly killed the women because of an earlier dispute over $50 worth of drugs.
 
Smith's 1977 trial ended in a hung jury but he was convicted of first-degree murder in a 1978 trial and sentenced to life in prison.  He spent 17 years in jail before a federal appeals court threw out the conviction because the prosecution had withheld evidence from the defense in the original trials. The police had found bloody clothes in the trunk of Tulton's husband's car, but the clothes were destroyed before the defense had a chance to test them.</P>

<P>The appeals court said that the state must release Smith or retry the case. Since all the physical evidence had been destroyed from the original trials, the state was ready to release Smith. But Lois Cooper, the mother of one of the victims, hired private investigators who were able to track down witnesses, and Smith was retried.</P>

<P>During the trial, the defense contended that Tultons husband, who had died of a drug overdose in 1978, was the killer. The states key witness was Harvey Bylsma, a former close friend of Smith. He was one of the original suspects in the case and spent four months in jail before he was released because of a lack of evidence. He testified that he saw Smith shoot the two women. </P>
<b>Verdict</b><br>
On December 14, 1995, the jury announced that it was deadlocked, 11-1 for acquittal.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
