<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>New York v. Cox</H2>

<P>Paul Cox, a 26-year-old carpenter, was charged with murdering two doctors who were living in his childhood home. The defense argued Cox was temporarily insane and not legally responsible in the 1989 New Year's Day deaths of Lakshman Rao Chevru and his wife Shanta Chevru. Defense experts testified that Cox was delusional and may have believed he was killing his parents. The prosecution argued that Cox, after drinking with friends, smashed up his mother's car and then intended to burglarize the Chevrus home.</P>

<P><B>Verdict:</B><BR>
A mistrial was declared on June 28, 1994 after the jury deadlocked 11-1 to find Cox guilty of intentional murder. Cox was retried, and a jury found him guilty of two counts of manslaughter on December 5, 1994. The jury determined that Cox intentionally killed the Chevrus while suffering from an "extreme emotional disturbance."</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
