<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>New York v. Del-Debbio (3/96)</H2>

<P>A New York City police officer stood trial for shooting an undercover transit police officer in a crowded subway station during a moment of chaos and mistaken identity.</P>

<P>Peter Del-Debbio was charged with first- and second-degree assault in connection with the August 22, 1994, shooting of  Desmond Robinson.</P>

<P>The trial focused on whether Del-Debbio was justified in firing at Robinson.</P>

<P>The shooting occurred as Del-Debbio, a member of the Police Department's Organized Crime Control Bureau, was waiting for a subway train to take him home. At the same time, Robinson and other officers were chasing two teenagers, one of whom dropped a sawed-off shotgun inside the doorway of the last car of the train.</P>

<P>Del-Debbio put on his badge, took out his off-duty revolver and leaned over to get the shotgun. What happened next was the subject of conflicting testimony during the trial.</P>

<P>Del-Debbio testified that he saw a man with a gun running towards him. He suspected the man might be the person who dropped the shotgun. </P>

<P>When the man was about eight feet away,  Del-Debbio said he opened fire.</P>

<P>"At this point, I eliminated him from being a police officer so now I must shoot him to prevent him from shooting at me or anyone else," he testified. "I fired my weapon at the individual once, possibly twice. I continued to look at him and realized he was still coming at me. I thought I would be shot so I turned away and fired the remaining shots I had."</P>

<P>Del-Debbio's testimony on several important points differed sharply from Robinson's account of the shooting.<p.</P>

<P>Robinson testified that he was not running toward Del-Debbio but alongside the train. He also said he had his gun in both hands and pointed downward as he responded to the shotgun blast. </P>

<P>He said he never saw Del -Debbio and was past the open doors of the last car when he felt the first two shots in the back. He said he felt the other two as he lay on the subway platform, wondering why he was being shot and by whom. </P>

<P>Del-Debbio said he fired at Robinson as he faced him, and did not empty his gun into Robinson's back. </P>

<P>Robinson conceded that he was not wearing his badge or the color of the day, by which undercover officers can be recognized by fellow officers. But Del-Debbio said he never yelled to Robinson that he was a police officer because there was no time. </P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On March 27, 1996, a jury concluded that Del-Debbio "recklessly caused serious physical injury to another person by means of a deadly weapon," and convicted him of second-degree assault. He was acquitted of first-degree assault. The judge sentenced Del-Debbio to five years probation and 200 hours of community service.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
