<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>New York v. Senko (3/96)</H2>

<P>Dmytro Senko, a New York City corrections department officer, was charged with grand larceny after  calling in sick for nearly two years with what he claimed was a debilitating injury. </P>

<P>Senko claimed a light fixture fell on his head and knocked him unconscious as he sat at a table writing in his logbook at the Riker's Island jail on December 30, 1992.  He did not return to work until November 1994.</P>

<P>The prosecution contended Senko faked the injuries and therefore was guilty of defrauding the city into paying his salary. During the trial, prosecutors presented evidence disputing Senko's version of the accident, and showed jurors surveillance videotapes of Senko going about his daily routine, including driving his car, and shoveling show and clearing ice near his home.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
A New York jury found Senko guilty of grand larceny. He was sentenced to six months in prison and 4-1/2 years probation. Senko also was ordered to pay $50,000 in restitution. </P>
