<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<p><H2>Noonkester v. Kline (7/96)</H2>
Virgil Ray Noonkester knew that he was dying.<p>

So the 67-year-old San Diego man suffering from amyothrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), commonly known as Lou Gehrig's Disease, started planning for his own death.<p>

He made several arrangements -- for a memorial service and to donate his body to further Lou Gehrig's Disease research -- and he made plans to enter hospice care.<p>

One thing Noonkester did was go on "do not resuscitate" status. Since most ALS patients eventually die of lung failure, Noonkester said that if he lost his breathing ability, he did not want to be kept alive by being put on a respirator.<p>

Several months before he went on "dnr" status, he started seeing Dr. Lawrence Kline, a doctor of osteopathy. Dr. Kline helped him with breathing problems he had at night, and soon became Noonkester's primary care physician. It was under Dr. Kline's care that Noonkester enrolled in hospice care and went on "dnr" status.<p>

But on December 22, 1993, Noonkester began to have severe breathing problems. His health care aide called 911, and Noonkester was taken to the emergency room. He had a tube inserted in his throat to help him breathe. His family soon joined him at the hospital. The next day, Noonkester underwent a tracheotomy and was put on a respirator.<p>

Noonkester claimed he did not want to have surgery and that Dr. Kline was ware of this. He and his family claimed that at the time of the emergency, Noonkester tried to find out what his options were. They claim Dr. Kline said he must either have a tracheotomy or "suffocate to death." He said his consent to the surgery was a "coerced, uninformed consent under severe emotional duress."  He claimed Dr. Kline should have informed him of all his options and made him comfortable in his death. <p>

Dr. Kline contended that Noonkester changed his mind and when asked if he wanted the surgery, he gave a "thumbs up." He noted that Noonkester wasn't rushed into surgery and never indicated that he did not want it. Dr. Kline also made the point that "do not resuscitate" patients can change their status at any time and that's what Noonkester did.<p>

The jury had to decided whether Dr. Kline was negligent for not giving Noonkester the information needed for him to make an informed decision about his treatment.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><<br>
The jury found for Dr. Kline on July 8, 1996.<p>

<p>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
