<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Random House v. Collins (2/96)</H2>

<P>It was lights, camera, action in a New York City courtroom when actress Joan Collins and publishing giant  Random House battled over a multi-million-dollar book deal.</P>

<P>The publishing firm wanted its $1.3 million advance back from Collins, claiming she failed to deliver "ready for press" books. Collins, best known for playing the scheming Alexis Carrington in the television series ''Dynasty  wanted Random House to hand over the rest of  money owed her under a $4 million deal.</P>

<P>She insisted that she turned in a novel tentatively titled "The Ruling Passion" in September 1991 and a second, "Hell Hath No Fury,'' the following  September, and that Random House never gave her the editorial assistance or guidance that it was required to provide. She also accused Random House of stringing her along, because her contract required she be paid within a year of a decision not to publish her work.</P>

<P>While most authors must return advances if a publisher rejects a manuscript. Collins's deal, negotiated by her legendary agent, the late Irving (Swifty) Lazar, contained an unusual clause -- Collins would be paid whether or not the completed manuscripts were published. </P>

<P>The dispute centered on a simple question:  what is a completed manuscript?</P>

<P>Collins's lawyers argued she had turned in the required number of words and therefore had complied with the contract.</P>

<P>At one point in her testimony, Collins described herself as the "queen of the adjectives and adverbs," but admitted that her work needed lots of editing.</P>

<P>Random House editors testified that a completed manuscript was expected to be an author's best, final effort, and should be ready for a final editing.</P>

<P>Former Random House editor Joni Evans testified that she was alarmed when she first read Collins's manuscript about two sisters fighting with one another. "It just wasn't working in any shape or form,'' said Evans, now a literary agent. ''It was no good. It was not something people on the street would read. It was dated. It wasn't grounded in reality,'' she added. ''It was dull. It was cliched in plot.''</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On February 13, 1996, a jury decided that Collins had completed one manuscript in compliance with her contract. But Random House did not have to pay her for the second manuscript because it was merely a rehashing of the first and not a separate piece of work. </P>

<P>The verdict meant Collins could keep the advance and collect more from Random House, though how much more remained in dispute. Her lawyer, Kenneth Burroughs, said Random House should owe Collins hundreds of thousands of dollars. Random House lawyer Robert Callagy agreed that the publisher would have to pay Collins more money, but did not know how much. The contract was split evenly between the two books.</P>

<P>The trial judge subsequently ruled that Random House owed Collins an additional $1.3 million. Judge Ira Gammerman decided the publisher owed Collins $925,000 plus interest -- or a grand total of about $1.3 million. The interest was compounded from September 1991, when the actress delivered a 690-page manuscript to Random House.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
