<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Scholz v. Orlando Magic (2/96)</H2>

<P>George Scholz sued the Orlando Magic basketball team for racial discrimination and defamation, claiming he was fired in 1992 because the team wanted to replace him with a black assistant coach.</P>

<P>Scholz, who is white, maintained he was an assistant coach, but Magic executives insisted he was a scout and given the title of assistant coach only as a courtesy. They also maintained Scholz was paid a scout's salary. Team officials contended that they fired Scholz because he didn't get along with Magic coaches and complained about his primary task of scouting opponents.</P>

<P>About a year after Scholz was dismissed, the team hired former NBA center Tree Rollins, who is black, as an assistant coach. Rollins was picked to share his experience and playing skills with Magic star player Shaquille O'Neal, team officials said.</P>

<P>During the trial, Scholz's lawyers tried to portray the Magic as a company that plotted to fire Scholz because it was under community pressure to hire blacks. Magic executives, according to their depositions, prepared the list of NBA minority coaches and scouts after they met with the team's Community Advisory Board.</P>

<P>The advisory group had made diversity an issue because the Magic's front office and coaching staff at the time did not include any black employees.</P>
Scholz testified that former Magic coach Matt Goukas told him in July 1992 that the team fired him for racial reasons.</P>

<P>But Goukas offered a different version of the meeting. He testified that Scholz badgered him for four hours practically insisting that Guokas agree that the firing was over skin color. Guokas testified that Scholz "tried to put words in my mouth...I told him, 'Believe whatever makes you happy.' I said that in total sarcasm."</P>

<P>Guokas admitted that he was pleased with Scholz's work with the team. And Scholz's lawyers used testimony from Guokas' depositions to suggest that Magic executives pressured Guokas to fire him.</P>

<P>They pointed to one deposition in which Guokas said of the firing: "It was primarily their wish...and I had to eventually agree with it." Guokas responded that the team had legitimate reasons to fire Scholz and that he agreed with them. He said Scholz disrupted team chemistry by not getting along with the coaching staff and by complaining about his primary duty,  scouting opponents.</P>

<P>Goukas also was questioned about Scholz's job responsibilities. Goukas said Scholz was unquestionably hired as a scout and that the title of assistant coach was given only as an afterthought minutes before a news conference announcing the hiring.</P>

<P>But a former employee of the Magic's public-relations staff claimed he wrote the news release naming Scholz as an assistant coach at  least the night before the news conference.</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
Judge Linda Gloeckner dismissed Scholz's lawsuit on February 9, 1996. She ruled that Scholz failed to provide enough evidence to support his claims of discrimination and defamation.</P>

<P>The judge ruled that Scholz failed to prove that race was the only cause for his termination. She said the Magic offered other explanations for the firing, and Scholz "couldn't prove that the other reasons were a pretext for racial discrimination."</P>

<P>The judge also threw out Scholz's allegation that a Magic executive made defamatory comments about him to the news media after his firing. The judge dismissed the charge, in part, because the comments did not "express malice."</P>

<P>Scholz, who now coaches at Jacksonville University in Florida, said he will appeal the judge's decision.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
