<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<p><h2>St. Agathe and Wilson v. City of New York (1/95)</H2>

The estates of two teenagers who drowned at Rockaway Beach in New York sued the city and several municipal departments for negligence. The families of Anthony St. Agathe, 15, and Bugani Wilson, 14, claimed the lifeguard on duty the day the boys drowned was not properly trained or supervised.<p>

The teens and a friend Roger Vaughn went swimming on June 20, 1990. The three swam out to a depth of about chest height. But that was too far for the lifeguard on duty. Lifeguard Jack Jordan whistled to them and motioned them ashore. Vaughn heard the whistle and began to swim inland. Wilson, however, got into trouble. It was not clear whether he had a cramp, got caught in the undertow or experienced some other problem. St. Agathe, a strong swimmer, went to his assistance. Vaughn also noticed the problem and told Jordan.<p>

The plaintiffs claimed Vaughn asked Jordan to help his friends and that Jordan initially ignored the request, stating: "if they can't  f...ing swim, why did they come to the beach?"  Within minutes, St. Agathe and Wilson disappeared below the water's surface. Jordan then issued an emergency signal and the rescue effort began.<p>

The plaintiffs claimed Jordan's delay in taking appropriate action cost the teenagers their lives. The defense claimed the boys failed to heed the whistle to come in and therefore were partly responsible for their own deaths.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
The jury found the city 100 percent liable and awarded the St. Agathe family $1,042,000 and the Wilsons $1,020,500.<p>

<p>
