<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>St. Claire Shores v. Provenzino (5/96)</H2>

<P>How far should society go in policing parents? Should we make parents pay for the crimes of their children? And isn't it possible for good parents to raise mixed-up kids?</P>

<P>Those were some of the questions raised in the trial of Anthony and Susan Provenzino. The working class couple was charged with violating a city of St. Claire Shores ordinance requiring them to be responsible parents. The city contended that 16-year-old Alex Provenzino got into drugs and became a burglar because his parents didn't keep a close eye on him.</P>

<P>The Provenzinos said they did the best they could under trying circumstances. They said their son started running with a bad crowd in the beginning of 1995, and his behavior immediately took a turn for the worse. He painted every wall in his room black. He started listening to different music. He started dressing all in black, and he began to show absolutely no respect for his parents. During the trial Alex testified that his parents did not know what he was doing because he took special measures to hide his criminal activitity.</P>

<P>But city attorneys wondered where the Provenzinos were when Alex was breaking into a church and his neighbors' homes. They also wondered how they did not know that he was using drugs and coming home with thousands of dollars in stolen property. The city maintained they should have gone into Alex's room when he wasn't there so they could see what he was up to. If they had done that, they clearly would have seen a live marijuana plant, a bag of marijuana and a stolen pistol.</P>

<P>Defense attorney William Buffalino countered that Provenzinos did not accompany Alex when he committed a string of burglaries, they didn't smoke marijuana with him, and they didn't condone any of his illicit activities. The only person responsible for Alex's action was Alex himself.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</B><BR>
On May 9, 1996, the jury deliberated for 30 minutes before finding the Provenzinos guilty of violating the ordinance. The Provenzinos each were ordered to pay a $100 fine and $1,000 in court costs. But the judge threw out the portion of the ordinance allowing for civil restitution. The judge determined that the ordinance was in conflict with state laws capping a parent's civil liability at $2,500 or $5,000. The city had sought $27,000 in restitution.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
