<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: South Carolina v. Beckham</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>South Carolina v. Beckham</H2>

<P>On June 12, 1994, Vickie Lander-Beckham's body was found in her car on the
side of a road near Little Mountain, South Carolina. What first looked like a
car accident was soon discovered to be murder.</P>

<P>Beckham's car was found in a ditch just off of Mountain Road -- a place
known for having many accidents. And Beckham, 36, had died as a result of a
broken neck -- something that did not seem out of the ordinary in car wrecks. But for investigators, it just didn't fit together.</P>

<P>Her life-ending injuries appeared to be the result of a beating -- not a car crash. An autopsy revealed that Beckham had sustained several blows
to her neck. Also, police found several clues suggesting that the scene was set up to look like an accident.</P>

<P>After further examination, police thought that the car had been pushed in the ditch and that the woman had been killed before being brought there. The death was planned, and the killer must have been familiar enough with the area to know that Mountain Road was a notorious crash site -- a perfect place to stage an accident.</P>

<P>Vickie Beckham's death received a lot of media attention in her hometown of
Newberry, South Carolina. She was a mother of three children and the daughter of state Senator Jim Lander, the local Democratic representative.</P>

<P>Police arrested Richard George Anderson, 35, a bouncer at a Myrtle Beach
nightclub, and charged him with the crime. In April, Anderson pleaded guilty to
first-degree murder. He is now in prison, serving his life sentence, with the
possibility of parole after 20 years.</P>

<P>But Anderson said he didn't kill Vickie Beckham alone. Rather, he said he  was hired to do so by the victim's husband, 37-year-old Stephen Beckham. After
Anderson gave police this information, a warrant went out for Beckham's arrest.
Police could not find Beckham for three days. He allegedly took his three children on a trip through North Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Tennessee and Kentucky. Police questioned Beckham's father, a prominent retired Episcopal bishop, about his son's whereabouts. He told them that his son was probably vacationing with his kids and wasn't aware of the warrant.</P>

<P>Police tracked Beckham down in Kentucky, where he and his children were
staying at the home of two Episcopalian ministers. His whereabouts were
discovered after these ministers called an ambulance because they suspected
Beckham had tried to overdose on pills. 

On July 15, 1995, Beckham surrendered to police in Kentucky, and he was brought back to South Carolina, where he was later charged with murdering his wife.</P>

<P><B>The Charges</B><BR>
Beckham faced charges of first-degree murder, kidnapping, and conspiracy to
commit murder.</P>

<P><B>The Prosecution's Case</B><BR>
Richard Anderson told the court about how Beckham allegedly approached him with the plan to kill his wife and how he carried out the murder. In detail, he described how he beat Vickie Beckham and tried to make the murder scene look like she had been killed in a car accident.</P>

<P>Crime reconstruction experts testified about how Anderson altered the
crime scene and how Vickie Beckham's injuries were not consistent with being
involved in an accident.</P>

<P>Police told the court about Beckham's claim that he was not avoiding arrest.
They said that no one who is on vacation hits six different states in two
days, as he did. Telephone, credit card, and bank
card records from these states made Beckham look like a man on the run, they said.</P>

<P>The coroner who examined the body talked about cause and time of death.
Investigators said Vickie Beckham was killed somewhere between 6 pm and 9:15 pm
on June 12, 1994 (her body was found that night at 9:30 pm). And while Stephen
Beckham claimed he was with his children during that time, investigators said his whereabouts were questionable for about 40 minutes during this time. This fact, along with Anderson's testimony, placed Beckham at the scene of the crime, they said.</P>

<P><B>The Defense's Case</B><BR>
Beckham claimed had nothing to do with his wife's death. Two of his children testified that he was at home at the hours when the police said the victim was murdered. 

<P>The defense also called DNA experts to testify that the blood found
under Vickie Beckham's fingernails did not match the blood of either Stephen
Beckham or Richard Anderson.</P>

<P><B>The Implications Of Publicity</B><BR>
Since the victim was the daughter South Carolina State Senator Jim Lander, a lot of publicity surrounded this case. A "gag order" was issued, preventing lawyers and family members from talking to the media about the case.</P>

<P><B>The Verdict</B><BR>
On Oct. 1, 1996, a jury of seven women and five men  convicted Stephen
Beckham of murder for killing his wife Vickie Beckham.</P>

<P>The verdict, which found Beckham guilty on all counts, came after the
sequestered jury deliberated for seven hours and listened to a full day of
closing arguments and jury instructions.</P> Two days later, the jury voted to
spare Beckham's life, after just over two hours of deliberation. <P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice." BORDER="0">
