<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Florida v. Puzio</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif"
ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>South Carolina v. Mathis</H2>

<P>At about 2 a.m. on Oct. 20, 1995, Jerry James Brown, a carnival worker at
the annual Aiken County Jaycees' Fair, was found shot to death in a parking
lot.</P> 
<P>Nine days later, police arrested 22-year-old Troy Mathis on the basis of two
witnesses who said that Mathis left them shortly before the killing and
returned sometime later that night, allegedly admitting he had killed Brown
while he was out.</P>

<P>Mathis, who has been in jail for the last year, denied making that
statement.</P> 

<P>The only eyewitness to the shooting, Daniel O'Donnell, failed to identify
Mathis from a photo line-up after the crime. Instead, the witness identified
Terry Tyler, who was currently serving a five-year sentence for Third degree
burglary, as the shooter. The prosecution said Mathis was with Tyler that
evening. </P>

<P><B>The Charges</B><BR>
Troy Mathis was charged with murder, armed robbery and possession of a firearm
during commission of a violent crime.</P>

<P><B>Key Legal Terms</B></P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><B>First-Degree Murder:</B> The South Carolina Code defines
first-degree murder as the killing of any person with premeditated malice,
either express or implied. A person convicted of or pleads guilty to murder
must be punished by death or by imprisonment for life and is not eligible for
parole until the service of twenty years.

	<LI><B>Armed Robbery:</B> A person convicted of robbery while armed with a
deadly weapon. This charge carries a penalty of no less than ten years -- or
more than thirty years -- imprisonment. The is no probation and no possibility
of parole for 7 years.

	<LI><B>Possession Of A Firearm:</B> If a person is convicted of possession
of a firearm during the commission of a violent crime, he or she must be
imprisoned five years, in addition to the punishment provided for the principal
crime, unless death or life without parole is imposed.
	</UL>

<P><B>The Participants</B></P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><B>The Judge:</B> Henry Floyd was admitted to the South Carolina Bar in
1973. After nine years as a trial lawyer, he was elected judge of South
Carolina's 13th Judicial Circuit in 1992.

	<LI><B>The Prosecution:</B> Barbara Morgan was appointed as solicitor of
South Carolina's 2nd Circuit. She was elected to the position in 1992 and
re-elected in 1996. 

	<LI><B>The Defense:</B> Regina Poteat was admitted to the South Carolina
Bar in 1992. She became a public defender a year later.
 	</UL>

<P><B>Verdict</B><BR>
On Dec. 11, 1996, Mathis was acquitted on all charges.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American
Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be
reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
