<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Tennessee v. Ducker (10/95)</H2>

<P>Jennie Bain Ducker was charged with two counts of first-degree murder in the deaths of her children, Dustin, age 1, and Devin, age 23 months.</P>

<P>The children died of heat exposure after being left in Ducker's closed car for about eight hours on June 6, 1995. The state claimed the 20-year-old Ducker strapped the boys into their car seats and left them in the parked car while she partied with four men in a McMinnville hotel room.</P>

<P>Ducker was charged under a Tennessee statute which said a killing does not have to be deliberate or premeditated to qualify as first-degree murder if a child dies as the result of aggravated abuse. The law was subsequently changed.</P>

<P>Prosecutors argued that Ducker had made too many deliberate moves to claim her sons died by accident. For instance, she checked on the boys from the balcony of the motel room, she propped bottles in their car seats and she locked the car doors, but she did not tell anyone her boys were helplessly alone.</P>

<P>The defense argued that Ducker suffered from a mental disease which affected her judgment. A defense psychiatrist witness testified Ducker had a bipolar condition which caused major mood swings and a sleeping disorder. As a result, the defense argued, Ducker was not aware of the possible consequences of leaving her children in the car. Also, the sleeping disorder which prevented her from sleeping for more than 22 hours prior to June 6, caused her to go into a deep sleep in the motel.</P>

<P><b>Verdict:</b><br>
On October 3, 1995, a jury convicted Jennie Bain Ducker of the lesser charge -- two counts of aggravated child abuse. She was sentenced to 18 years in prison.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
