<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Tennessee v. Frazier (9/95)</H2>

<P>Journalist Michael Frazier was charged with attempted murder in the "love triangle" attack on the allegedly abusive husband of his lover.</P>

<P>Frazier was accused of plotting with lover Lisa Whedbee - about whom he'd written an award-winning Mother's Day story in 1993 - to kill her husband, John Whedbee. </P>

<P>The two were arrested after Whedbee was attacked by a knife-wielding assailant as he was sleeping in his home on June 8, 1994. </P>

<P>During the trial, prosecutors tried to portray Frazier as someone who wanted another man's wife so badly he was willing to kill for her. </P>

<P>The defense contended that Frazier, 33, was in love with Lisa Whedbee, a member of the church choir that Frazier directed and the subject of an award-winning Mother's Day article he wrote in 1993 while a reporter for The Oak Ridger. </P>

<P>Because of that love, Frazier was driven to an admittedly "bizarre" extreme to protect her from alleged beatings and abuse by her husband. </P>

<P>There was conflicting testimony on abuse allegedly committed by Whedbee. He denied it in court. Police officers called to the Whedbee home failed to see signs of it. Friends of Lisa Whedbee saw bruises but not the abuse itself. </P>

<P>Prosecutors suggested that Frazier was manipulated by Lisa Whedbee, who didn't testify during the trial. She faces a separate trial on conspiracy and attempted- murder charges. The state argued that she was motivated by her husband's $1 million in life insurance and desire to keep her family, home and possessions. </P>

<P>During the trial, Frazier admitted to putting on surgical gloves and dark clothes, riding with Lisa Whedbee to her home and hiding in a closet for hours until she came for him, handed him a knife and led him to the bedroom of her sleeping husband. But Frazier testified that he never intended to kill John Whedbee.</P>

<P>"When I saw him in that light (from a window) I realized this was crazy, that I couldn't kill him. This wasn't the horrible monster. It was just a man lying in his bed. I couldn't kill him."</P>

<P><b>Verdict</b><br>
On September 16, 1995, a jury convicted Michael Frazier of attempted manslaughter. The jury's verdict was the least of three possible offenses before them, including attempted first-degree murder. Frazier received the maximum sentence, four years in prison.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
