http://www.courttv.com:80/casefiles/verdicts/johnroe.html 199.29.97.40 19970108064751 text/html 1780
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 06:57:29 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 01-Nov-96 15:25:39 GMT
Content-length: 1589
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<P><h2>Tennessee v. Roe (7/96)</h2>
John Roe, a former Memphis police officer, was charged in the fatal shooting of his wife.<p>

Roe was accused of shooting Lisa Michelle Roe, 24, on September 16, 1994, at the couple's home. Lisa, a radiology student, had told friends that her husband was abusive and had threatened to kill her. The day before she was murdered, she told friends to call her parents and authorities if she did not show up for work the next day.<p>

The defense contended Roe was insane at the time of the shooting. Since Roe refused to cooperate with court orders concerning psychiatric evaluations the defense could not use expert testimony about Roe's mental state. Instead, it relied on the testimony of witnesses who said Roe looked and acted weird after the shooting.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
Roe was found guilty of first-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison.<p>

<p>
