<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A></P>
<P><h2>Tennessee v. Tate and Blades (7/96)</h2>

<A href=/report/tate.html> George Tate and Rodney Blades</a> were charged with first-degree murder in the stabbing death of a prominent Memphis woman.<p>

Emily Klyce Fisher, who was well known in Memphis for her involvement in charities and the arts, died of multiple stab wounds on February 27, 1995, after she and her elderly maid were attacked in Fisher's home. <p>

The assailants ransacked the home and made off with money and Fisher's 1994 Ford Taurus. The car was found abandoned a day later in north Memphis. Blades's fingerprints reportedly were found in the car. Blades told police he took items from the car, but had nothing to do with the murder. Authorities never found the murder weapon.<p>

The maid, 81-year-old Leester Redmond, identified the defendants as the assailants through photographs and a line-up in a videotaped statement.<p>

But the judge that Redmond was not competent to testify at the trial, so prosecutors were forced to rely on the videotaped statement.<p>

The defense challenged the credibility of the identification. Defense lawyers also presented evidence that DNA of a blood sample taken from the crime scene did not belong to either defendant or the victims.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
On July 24, 1996, Tate and Blades were acquitted of all charges.<P>

<p>
