<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: South Carolina v. Beckham</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif"

ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>



<H2>Turner v. Dolcefino</H2>



<P>In October 1991, Sylvester Turner was in a close race for mayor of Houston. He claimed that he was on the verge of becoming the city's first black mayor. But one week before the election Houston's KTRK-Channel 13's Wayne Dolcefino reported that an unidentified source had linked Turner to Sylvester Foster, a man who faked his own death in a 1986 insurance scheme.</P>



<P>Turner claimed the story was false and reported with reckless disregard for the truth. He said the story was designed to impeach his honesty, integrity, virtue and reputation and expose him to public hatred, contempt and ridicule. He asked for $10 million to $15 million in actual damages and a similar amount for exemplary damages.</P>



<P>The defense claimed the story was true and that Dolcefino properly researched it. The story merely asked questions about Turner's involvement and  did not definitively say Turner knew about the scam. The defense also said that other news organizations published and aired negative stories that may have damaged Turner's reputation and cost him the election.</P>



<P><B>The Verdict</B><BR>

On Oct. 14, 1996, a jury awarded Turner $5.5 million in damages.</P>

