<p><h2>Vermont v. Brooks (11/92)</h2>
Stephen Brooks, a former chairman of the Burlington Republican Party, was charged with three counts of manslaughter after a couple and their two-year-old daughter died in a house three months after Brooks sold it to them. The three died of carbon monoxide poisoning caused by a defective boiler. The state claimed Brooks knew about the problem (his wife and child previously had been treated for carbon monoxide poisoning) and failed to disclose it to the buyer.<p>

<b>Verdict</b><br>
Brooks was found guilty of three counts of involuntary manslaughter. He was sentenced to four years in prison and six years probation.<p>

<p>
