<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Weeks v. Baker & McKenzie and Greenstein (8/94)</H2>

<P>Rena Weeks sued the world's largest law firm and a former partner for sexual harassment. Weeks, who worked as Martin Greenstein's secretary in 1991, accused the intellectual property specialist of verbally and physically abusing her.  The incidents, she said, included his dropping candies in the pocket of her blouse and asking her which of her breasts was bigger. She claimed the firm of Baker & McKenzie ignored Greenstein's repeated harassment of other women.</P>

<P>Greenstein denied harassing Weeks but did concede during the trial that he believed two former female employees who said he harassed them. Baker & McKenzie argued that even if Weeks was abused, she suffered minimal damages. The defense also claimed Weeks' psychological problems are due more to a head injury she suffered as an adolescent than Greenstein's alleged behavior. Since Weeks voluntarily left the firm, the defense contended she was not entitled to economic damages due to job loss. The firm also claimed it asked Greenstein to resign because of the pattern of alleged abuse and because he was back-dating forms involving his copyright practice.</P>

<P><B>Verdict</b><br>
On August 26, 1994, a San Francisco jury ruled Greenstein had harassed Weeks, and the law firm failed to take reasonable steps to prevent the harassment. She was awarded $50,000 in compensatory damages.  On September 1, 1994, the jury awarded her $7.1 million in punitive damages. The law firm was ordered to pay  $6.9 million and Greenstein, $225,000. The award was believed to be the largest in a sexual harassment case in California.</P>

<P>In a post-trial ruling on November 28, Judge John Munter ruled that the jury's $6.9 million punitive damage award against the firm was excessive, but that he would affirm a $3.5 million punitive award if the plaintiff consented.  The judge, noting that Weeks' counsel Philip Kay had asked for $3.5 million in his closing argument, said he would order a new trial on punitive damages unless Weeks accepted the lesser amount.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
